<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Reagan-Transition     11-22 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Transition,1st Ld Writethru,a0741</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Following ADDs 1 graf to include Mary Schapiro's appointment:
^By MERRILL HARTSON</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan has given ``recess
appointments'' to about 30 people to maintain continuity in various
agencies, boards and commissions while Congress is in recess, press
spokesmen said Tuesday.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said names of most of the
candidates for the posts had been submitted to Congress earlier but
had not been confirmed by the time adjournment came on Oct. 23.
   Fitzwater also said that Reagan administration Cabinet officers
and agency heads had been asked to provide the Bush transition team
with information on issues facing their agencies.
   Briefing reporters who accompanied Reagan to southern California
for the president's six-day vacation, Fitzwater said the Bush team
was seeking information ``of a routine nature,'' including
department and agency organizational charts, missions and
chains-of-command.
   Fitzwater said that White House chief of staff Kenneth
Duberstein, who also is the head of Reagan's transition team, asked
that the information be provided to the Bush people no later than
Friday.
   Noting that top-level executive branch political appointees had
been asked earlier to offer resignation letters to give Bush more
hiring flexibility, Fitzwater said, ``I don't interpret this as any
kind of hit list or any special effort to weed out people or
anything like that. It simply is a routine description of jobs,
functions, people, etc.''
   As for the recess appointees, he said, ``With the exception of
the few people that are being appointed to fixed-term positions, all
are being asked to submit their resignations with their
appointments.''
   He said the appointments were necessary because, ``in some cases
we have boards and commissions and so forth that need people in them
so they have a quorum. ... In other cases, they fill positions that
have decisions coming up in the next few months and we feel that
they should be filled.''
   Among the 32 recess appointments announced Tuesday were these:
   _William Andreas Brown, former ambassador to Thailand, to succeed
Thomas R. Pickering as the U.S. envoy to Israel.
   _Margot E. Machol, to be a commissioner on the Federal Trade
Commission.
   _Jill Houghton Emery to be director of the Women's Bureau at the
Department of Labor, succeeding Shirley Dennis.
   _Dennis Devaney to be a member of the National Labor Relations
Board for the remainder of a term expiring Dec. 16, 1989, succeeding
Marshall B. Babson.
   _Becky Norton Dunlop, to be assistant secretary for fish and
wildlife at the Interior Department.
   _Mary L. Schapiro, a lobbyist for the commodity futures industry,
to be a member of the Securities and Exchange Commission for a term
to expire next June.
</TEXT>
