<2ND_LINE>PM-Box Office,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Land Before Time' Takes Box Office Title</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``The Land Before Time,'' the animated tale of a
baby dinosaur's perilous journey through a prehistoric world, made
its debut as the top box office attraction, trampling the stylish
horror movie ``Child's Play.''
   ``The Land Before Time'' grossed $7.5 million last weekend as the
holiday movie season began.
   ``Child's Play,'' the story of a psychopathic doll named Chucky,
was next with $5.2 million in its second week of release. In third
was ``Ernest Saves Christmas,'' in which a loony cabdriver (Jim
Varney) rescues the holiday by driving Santa's sleigh. ``Ernest''
reported ticket sales of $4.8 million.
   ``Oliver and Co.,'' the second animated film to open last
weekend, finished far behind ``The Land Before Time'' in fourth
place. ``Oliver and Co.,'' using a variety of celebrity voices,
including Bette Midler's, to recount the Oliver Twist-inspired story
of a homeless kitten, grossed $4 million.
   ``High Spirits,'' a new comic ghost story about an Irish castle
run by Peter O'Toole, got $3.3 million in receipts to finish in
fifth. The debut of ``Fresh Horses,'' a serious study of love
starring Molly Ringwald and Andrew McCarthy, claimed sixth place
with ticket sales of $3.1 million.
   The only long-standing film in the top 10 was ``The Accused,''
finishing No. 7. The movie, featuring Jodie Foster in a chronicle of
rape and the justice system, grossed $1.903 million. ``Iron Eagle
II,'' a military adventure about U.S. and Soviet pilots joining
forces to prevent nuclear war, gathered $1.894 million to finish at
No. 8.
   In the last two top spots were ``Everybody's All American,''
starring Jessica Lange, with sales of $1.8 million, and ``1969,'' a
new movie about the Vietnam War's impact on everyday Americans,
which got $1.7 million.
   The holiday movie season expands this week. ``Cocoon: The
Return,'' starring Don Ameche, ``Scrooged,'' with Bill Murray, and
``Full Moon in Blue Water,'' featuring Gene Hackmann, open Wednesday.
   Here are the top movies for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations Co., with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater
screens, average per screen, total gross and number of weeks in
release.
   1. ``The Land Before Time,'' Universal, $7.5 million, 1,395
screens, $5,395 per screen, $7.5 million, one week.
   2. ``Child's Play,'' United Artists, $5.2 million, 1,386 screens,
$3,754 per screen, $14.8 million, two weeks.
   3. ``Ernest Saves Christmas,'' Disney, $4.8 million, 1,640
screens, $2,952 per screen, $11.6 million, two weeks.
   4. ``Oliver and Co.,'' Disney, $4 million, 952 screens, $4,226
per screen, $4 million, one week.
   5. ``High Spirits,'' Tri-Star, $3.3 million, 825 screens, $4,010
per screen, $3.3 million, one week.
   6. ``Fresh Horses,'' Weintraub, $3.1 million, 1,272 screens,
$2,416 per screen, $3.1 million, one week.
   7. ``The Accused,'' Paramount, $1.903 million, 904 screens,
$2,105 per screen, $24 million, six weeks.
   8. ``Iron Eagle II,'' Tri-Star, $1.894 million, 878 screens,
$2,158 per screen, $6 million, two weeks.
   9. ``Everybody's All American,'' Warner Bros., $1.8 million,
1,002 screens, $1,799 per screen, $9.5 million, three weeks.
   10. ``1969,'' Atlantic, $1.7 million, 520 screens, $3,281 per
screen, $1.7 million, one week.
</TEXT>
