<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-88 0102EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Bush-Soviet Bjt   11-22 0694</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-Soviet, Bjt,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: New York Meeting Could Pressure Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The specter of Reykjavik is hanging over the
scheduled meeting between President-elect George Bush and Kremlin
leader Mikhail Gorbachev in New York on Dec. 7.
   Bush said Monday he does not want the session to turn into an
anything-goes bargaining session, although his aides say they will
be going with open ears and minds.
   The Reagan administration took the same approach before an
October 1986 meeting in Reykjavik, Iceland, between between
President Reagan and Gorbachev, billed in advance by the Americans
as a non-summit.
   In Reykjavik, however, Gorbachev engaged Reagan in bargaining
over the eventual elimination of all nuclear weapons. That prospect
upset U.S. allies in Western Europe, who rely on American nuclear
deterrence and who complained they had not been fully consulted on
an arms cut as broad as Reagan was considering.
   After Reykjavik, the Reagan administration tried to match
Gorbachev's diplomatic pace, signing a treaty to eliminate some
intermediate-range nuclear weapons and making progress toward a
Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty (START).
   Gorbachev will probably try to pressure Bush to match that pace.
   Bush told a news conference Monday that the New York session with
Gorbachev will not be the first Bush-Gorbachev summit, but will be
``President Reagan's meeting.''
   ``I'll be there as vice president of the United States and I
expect they'll be aware they're talking to the next president,'' he
said.
   ``In terms of specificity, in terms of my committing a brand new
administration to specifics in arms control or anything else, I'm
not going to do that,'' said Bush.
   But, said one Bush aide, ``we expect Gorbachev to try to advance
some of his ideas. And given his record, he may unveil some new
ones, right at the meeting.''
   ``We don't want this to turn into a summit, but we will be
listening,'' said the aide, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The Bush team thinks Gorbachev might try to break new ground in
START and in efforts to cut East-West conventional, or non-nuclear,
forces in Europe.
   Gorbachev may restate his desire for Soviet participation in a
proposed Middle East peace conference, perhaps trying a new twist in
the wake of a declaration of a Palestinian homeland by the
parliament of the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   The Bush camp believes Gorbachev will restate the Soviet intent
to withdraw its remaining troops from Afghanistan, although they
have halted that withdrawal to protest renewed offensives by Afghan
guerrillas.
   ``We think they just want to get out without being humiliated,''
said the Bush aide.
   Conventional and strategic arms control are considered the most
likely areas for a Gorbachev diplomatic initiative.
   Gorbachev and other Soviets have been talking for more than a
year about a new military doctrine of ``reasonable sufficiency,''
which could entail sharp cuts in Warsaw Pact conventional forces.
   So far, there has been no change in the deployment of
conventional Warsaw Pact forces, and Soviet chief of staff Sergei
Akhromeyev said during a Pentagon visit last summer that Moscow
would cut back only if Washington did likewise.
   ``But that doesn't mean that Gorbachev won't make a new proposal
on conventional arms. He knows it plays well in West Europe,'' said
the Bush aide.
   Gorbachev might also try to resolve disagreements that remained
after the Moscow summit last June over mobile missiles,
submarine-launched cruise missiles and limits to space tests of
anti-missile defenses.
   The dispute over Reagan's Strategic Defense Initiative is the
most emotional obstacle to START. Gorbachev insists the United
States agree to abide for another decade by the 1972 Anti-Ballistic
Missile treaty, which bars space defenses.
   For its part, the United States insists mobile missiles be banned
under START. The Soviet Union has deployed two mobile missiles, the
10-warhead SS-25, based on rails, and the single-warhead SS-24,
based on trucks. America is devising, but has not deployed, a
rail-mobile system for the 10-warhead MX and is developing the
single-warhead road-mobile Midgetman.
   The Soviets, in turn, are insisting on strict limits for
submarine-launched nuclear-tipped cruise missiles, but the Reagan
administration has balked at the stringent verification procedures
that would be needed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
