<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0774 11-22 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0774,0443</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS Parish; Separates moved for AMs on Hubbell as a0759 and
Parish as a0417. Hubbell also moved on the sports wire along with
LaserPhotos NY70,79.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Carl Hubbell</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carl Hubbell, one of baseball's top
pitchers in the 1930s, died Monday of head and chest injuries, two
days after being critically injured in an automobile accident. He
was 85.
   Hubbell's most celebrated feat was striking out Babe Ruth, Lou
Gehrig and three other future Hall of Famers in a row in the 1934
All-Star Game. He also threw a no-hitter against the Pittsburgh
Pirates in 1929. Hubbell was elected to the Hall of Fame in 1947.
   The left-hander won 253 games, including 21 or more games five
years in a row for the New York Giants. He won the Most Valuable
Player Award with a 26-6 record in 1936 and set a then-record of 46
1-3 consecutive scoreless innings from July 13 to Aug. 1, 1933.
   His major league career, all with the Giants, ran 16 years from
1928-43 when the team won three pennants and the 1933 World Series.
Hubbell later worked for the Giants as an executive and scout.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Elgin Gates</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>IDAHO FALLS, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elgin T. Gates, a sportsman and
internationally renowned big game hunter, died Wednesday of a heart
attack at age 66.
   Gates took up boat racing after World War II, and in a 10-year
period won several national championships and set 26 records. He was
named to the all-American Racing Team for seven consecutive years
and to its Hall of Fame.
   Gates won 17 national and international championships in
clay-target shooting in six different countries and was inducted
into the American Handgun Hall of Fame last year and received the
Outstanding American Handgunner award.
   Gates was a winner of the Weatherby Big Game Trophy in 1960. He
was inducted into the Big Game Hall of Fame in 1978 for lifetime
achievement in the sport.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Margaret Parish</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANNING, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Margaret C. ``Peggy'' Parish, noted
children's author of the ``Amelia Bedelia'' series and other books
during a career spanning three decades, died Friday of a ruptured
abdominal aneurism. She was 61.
   The ``Amelia Bedelai'' series was about a a mistake-prone,
literal-minded maid _ the kind of character who puts sponge in
spongecake.
   In addition to the Amelia Bedelia series, Miss Parish was also
the author of such books as ``The Cats Burglar,'' `Dinosaur Time,''
``The Ghosts of Cougar Island,'' ``Good Hunting Little Indian,''
``Hermit Dan'' and ``Let's Be Early Settlers with Daniel Boone.''
</TEXT>
