<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AtlantaEditor     11-22 0160</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Atlanta Editor,0164</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rosenfeld In Stable Condition After Kidney Removed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An editor who was to take over leadership of
the Atlanta Journal-Constitution on Monday underwent surgery here to
remove a cancerous kidney, hospital officials said.
   Arnold Rosenfeld, 55, was in stable condition Monday night, said
a spokeswoman at Seton Medical Center.
   He was hospitalized Thursday for treatment of a suspected kidney
infection. A malignant tumor was found in the kidney, requiring its
removal, hospital spokeswoman M.A. Bengtson said.
   Doctors found no evidence the tumor had spread to other areas of
the body or to the attending blood vessels, Ms. Bengtson said.
   Rosenfeld officially became editor of the Journal-Constitution on
Monday, replacing Bill Kovach, who resigned Nov. 4 after a
disagreement with the publisher.
   Rosenfeld, who previously was editor of the Austin
American-Statesman, will probably be hospitalized about five to
eight days, with an expected recovery time of two to three weeks,
the hospital spokeswoman said.
</TEXT>
