<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Thornburgh     11-22 0671</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Thornburgh,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attorney General To Reach Out To Civil Rights Leaders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh, who has been
allaying conservative concerns over his tenure, now plans to reach
out to civil rights leaders who have been criticizing the Reagan
administration for eight years.
   After President-elect George Bush announced Monday that he
intended to retain him, Thornburgh signaled that he seeks to reopen
lines of communication to civil rights groups. Administration
relations with such groups have deteriorated because of its
opposition to affirmative action hiring and promotion, court-ordered
school desegregation and other programs.
   ``In the civil rights area, the vice president has indicated a
desire to reach out to groups that may feel disaffected from the
process,'' Thornburgh told reporters. ``I have a long history of
working effectively with leadership of the civil rights groups which
I hope to continue.''
   In the coming weeks, the attorney general will meet with the
Leadership Conference on Civil Rights, a coalition of 180
organizations. Thornburgh knows the conference's executive director,
Ralph Neas, who is spending several months at Harvard University's
institute of politics which was formerly headed by Thornburgh.
   ``There's obviously some perception'' on the part of civil rights
leaders ``that we're not willing to listen and talk with and
consider their views in framing the administration's views,''
Thornburgh said, adding, ``We want to dispel that.''
   He said ``there's certainly no conscious effort to change the
basic civil rights agenda'' and he said ``we're going to disagree
... but I think the importance of the effort we're going to try to
make is to establish a dialogue.''
   Thornburgh's and the Bush administration's first important task
in the area will be to find a replacement for the Justice
Department's civil rights division chief, William Bradford Reynolds,
who spearheaded the Reagan administration's controversial policies.
   Thornburgh's overtures to the civil rights community follow three
months in which he has been watched closely by conservatives.
   ``Dick Thornburgh has been very open to conservatives, his staff
has got good lines of communications to conservative leaders on the
legal issues,'' said Dan Casey, executive director of the American
Conservative Union.
   A number of weeks ago, Casey singled out the then-imminent
question of whether Thornburgh would step into the abortion issue
before the Supreme Court as a key test of how the attorney general
would be regarded among conservative groups represented in his
organization.
   Thornburgh was deeply involved in the solicitor general's
decision to invite the Supreme Court to review the landmark ruling
legalizing abortion.
   The attorney general's track record to date has ``very much eased
conservative fears about what he might be inclined to do as attorney
general over the long haul,'' said Patrick Korten, a Justice
Department spokesman under Thornburgh's predecessor, Edwin Meese
III, and now with the conservative Heritage Foundation.
   Shortly after coming to Washington, Thornburgh had delivered a
speech on ethics at the Justice Department that was viewed as being
a thinly veiled reference to Meese, who had been under criminal
investigation for 14 months before resigning in August. Also,
Thornburgh made clear he had serious reservations about an order
Meese signed in his final day at the Justice Department setting
forth procedures under which independent counsels could be appointed
to investigate members of Congress.
   Thornburgh still has reservations about the Meese order, but now
says he wants to review the matter with the incoming Bush
administration before taking action.
   In addition, he persuaded President Reagan to announce plans to
veto a whistleblower protection bill passed by Congress and argued
before the Supreme Court in favor of a drug testing program.
   Thornburgh also defended the Justice Department's decision to
file a brief attacking independent counsel Lawrence Walsh's legal
theory in the Iran-Contra that former National Security Council aide
Oliver North obstructed Congress' foreign affairs authority.
   When it was suggested the Iran-Contra brief may have been filed
to bolster his image among conservatives, Thornburgh told reporters
``That's absolute nonsense ... Nobody's got to shore up Dick
Thornburgh's conservative credentials.''
</TEXT>
