<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WheatOutlook     11-22 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wheat Outlook,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Big Wheat Crops Needed To Meet All Commitments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A near-record amount of wheat will be needed to
meet all U.S. domestic and export commitments in 1988-89, despite a
sharp rise in prices from last season, says an Agriculture
Department report.
   About 2.65 billion bushels will be used, down only about 5
percent from the record use of 2.69 billion bushels in 1987-88.
   Over the entire marketing yearthat runs through next May 31,
wheat prices may average $3.55 to $3.85 per bushel, up 40 to 50
percent from the 1987-88 season.
   ``Demand should be strong, despite higher prices, because foreign
and domestic food use (of wheat) is not very price-sensitive, at
least in the short term,'' the department's Economic Research
Service said Monday in its latest outlook report.
   The price of wheat used for food in the United States ``responds
little to changes in prices because wheat represents only a small
portion of the total cost to the consumer of products made with
flour,'' the report said.
   Meanwhile, world wheat export prices continue to edge higher
because of tight supplies and relatively strong demand.
   ``While the higher prices are rationing the available wheat among
importers, export subsidies, credit availability and food aid
programs are, to some extent, softening the impact of increased
costs for countries that might otherwise have to further reduce
purchases and consumption,'' the report said.
   Even so, total world wheat trade is expected to decline in
1988-89, led by a sharp drop in imports by the Soviet Union and a
decline in wheat sold as livestock feed.
</TEXT>
