<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DarmanProfile     11-22 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Darman Profile,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush's Budget Chief Is Veteran Of Bureacratic Battles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard G. Darman, President-elect George
Bush's choice as his budget director, is an aggressive veteran of
two decades in the bureaucratic battles of Washington who is known
more for his efficiency than his modesty.
   After Darman moved into the White House as an assistant to the
president in 1981, Jim Edwards, an old Harvard friend, told a
reporter, ``He just has a natural feeling that he's superior to most
people and deserves to be at a high policy level.''
   Few deny that Darman, 45, is bright.
   In the early days of the Reagan administration, James A. Baker
III, then White House chief of staff, said he was ``the guy, more
than anybody else, who flagged the fact that we were going to have
to come up with an additional round of cuts to handle the deficit
problem.''
   When Baker left the White House to become secretary of the
treasury, Darman went with him as deputy secretary. Now Baker is
secretary of state-designate and a key adviser to Bush on
appointments and other matters.
   It was not the first time Darman had hitched his wagon to a
rising star in the Washington firmament.
   When he first came to Washington in the Nixon administration, he
went to work for what was then the Department of Health, Education
and Welfare, where he caught the eye of Secretary Elliott Richardson.
   He followed Richardson as an aide during the patrician Boston
lawyer's stints at the departments of Defense, Justice and Commerce
and in the Law of the Sea negotiations for the State Department.
   Darman grew up in the affluent Boston suburb of Wellesley, Mass.,
the son of an industrialist who owned textile mills and marketed oil
and gas in New England.
   After prep school, where he was captain of the lacrosse team as
well as editor of the literary journal, he went on to Harvard
University, Harvard Business School and Washington.
   Then followed his years in the Nixon and Ford administrations,
after which he did corporate planning with a Washington consulting
firm and taught at Harvard's Kennedy School of Government.
   When President Reagan was elected in 1980, Darman became a member
of the White House transition team.
   In recent remarks at a Kennedy School conference in Washington,
Darman said he thought this team worked well because it was small
and the people ``knew where they were going.''
   Of the overall Reagan transition effort, involving more than
1,500 people, he said, ``If there has been a more colossal waste,
I'm not aware of it.''
   After the transition, Darman became assistant to the president
and deputy to the chief of staff, responsible for the flow of paper
to the president's desk.
   ``He's the fourth most powerful person at the White House,''
Deputy Chief of Staff Michael K. Deaver said at the time.
   Supporters lauded him as an extraordinarily bright and diligent
organizer, but detractors accused him of boundless ambition and ego.
   Darman resigned as deputy Treasury secretary in April 1987 to
take a job with Shearson Lehman Brothers investment banking division
at a salary, with stock options, that reportedly approached $1
million annually.
   This summer, however, he joined the Bush campaign as a top
adviser and served as the Michael Dukakis stand-in during Bush's
practice sessions before his two debates with the Democratic
challenger.
   Darman is married to the former Kath Emmett, a Ph.D. who is
writing a book about Americans in Paris after World War II. They
have two children.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
