<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PresidentialVote     11-22 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Presidential Vote,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Third-Party Candidates Got Less 1 Percent of Vote</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Third-party presidential hopefuls tallied less
than one percent of the more than 90 million votes cast in the
presidential race Nov. 8 as Republican George Bush defeated Democrat
Michael Dukakis.
   Libertarian nominee Ron Paul was the leading vote-getter among
the non-major party candidates, garnering more than four-tenths of
one percent of the votes. That is above the one-quarter of a percent
of the 1984 vote won by Libertarian candidate David Bergland.
   New Alliance candidate Leonora Fulani won more than two-tenths of
one percent, good for second place among the independent hopefuls.
   Most of the third-party candidates were on the ballot in only a
handful of states each. Only Fulani was on the ballot in all 50
states, although Paul was on the ballot in 47 states.
   The figures are based on an Associated Press canvass of all 50
states.
   In five states, final, official vote returns were available. In
39 states and the District of Columbia, final, unofficial figures
were used. These were compiled by the AP, the News Election Service
or state government officials.
   In four states _ Maine, New Jersey, New York and Pennsylvania _
partial returns were used for Bush, Dukakis and all the third-party
candidates on the ballot in those states. In two states _ Alabama
and Rhode Island _ partial returns were available only for Bush and
Dukakis.
   The raw vote totals for all candidates should increase slightly
when all returns are counted. That is not expected until all states
certify their votes by late December.
   The only significant change from these numbers to the complete
tabulation could come in the totals for Fulani. No vote returns for
Fulani, who is from New York, were available at all from New York
City. Returns for all candidates on the ballot were tallied for the
rest of the state, plus the major party totals in New York City.
   Alaska was the best state for Paul, who received almost 3 percent
of the votes in America's northernmost outpost. The District of
Columbia was the site of Fulani's best showing, about 1.5 percent of
the vote.
   Here are the latest national vote returns and the percentage for
each candidate. A party identification is listed for most
candidates, although many third-party candidates run under different
banners in different states.
   Bush, GOP 48,138,478 _ 53.44 percent.
   Dukakis, Dem 41,114,068 _ 45.64 percent.
   Ron Paul, Libertarian 409,412 _ 0.45 percent.
   Lenora Fulani, New Alliance 201,430 _ 0.22 percent.
   David Duke, Populist 44,135 _ 0.04 percent.
   Eugene McCarthy, Consumer 30,074 _ 0.03 percent.
   James Griffin, American Independent 26,053 _ 0.02 percent.
   Lyndon LaRouche, National Ecnoomic Recovery 23,713 _ 0.02 percent.
   William Mara, Right to Life 22,560 _ 0.02 percent.
   Ed Winn, Workers League 18,645 _ 0.02 percent.
   James Warren, Socialist Workers 11,435 _ 0.01 percent.
   Earl F. Dodge, Prohibition 7,868 _ 0.00 percent.
   None of the Above 6,923 _ 0.00 percent.
   Larry Holmes, Workers World 6,628 _ 0.00 percent.
   Herbert Lewin, Peace Freedom 3,968 _ 0.00 percent.
   Delmar Dennis, American 3,443 _ 0.00 percent.
   Willa Kenoyer, Socialist 3,412 _ 0.00 percent.
   Jack Herer, Grassroots 1,949 _ 0.00 percent.
   Louie Youngkite, Independent 363 _ 0.00 percent.
   John Martin, Third World Assembly 229 _ 0.00 percent.
</TEXT>
