<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Hepatitis     11-22 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hepatitis,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Experts Say Hepatitis B Increasing Steeply In US</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health authorities are considering whether to
immunize all newborns or children against hepatitis B, a viral liver
disease that is spread in the same manner as AIDS and is now posing
a major health and economic threat.
   Harold Margolis, chief of the hepatitis branch at the Centers for
Disease Control, said the incidence rate of hepatitis B in the
United States is on a steep increase, with about 300,000 new cases a
year and national treatment costs now about $1 million a day.
   Margolis spoke Monday at a news conference sponsored by the
National Foundation for Infectious Diseases, a non-profit
organization that promotes disease prevention.
   Sanford F. Kuvin, an infectious disease expert who operates
clinics in the United States and Israel, said hepatitis B is ``a
national tragedy in incubation in the United States.''
   Hepatitis is a viral disease that attacks the liver, causing
jaundice, fatigue and loss of appetite. Hepatitis A is spread mostly
through food and is generally a mild disease. Hepatitis B, however,
is spread through an exchange of body fluids, usually through sexual
contact, the sharing of IV drug needles or from birthing mother to
child.
   Hepatitis B is thought to be the major cause of primary liver
cancer and is thought to cause about 5,000 deaths a year, either
directly or indirectly, in the United States, according to the
foundation.
   Margolis said that between 6 percent and 10 percent of the
hepatitis B cases become chronic, in which symptoms are very slight,
but the carrier is able to spread the disease.
   Hepatitis B has a long incubation period, several months, but the
serious effects of the disease, such as cancer or liver failure, may
not appear for decades in chronic carriers.
   There is a vaccine against hepatitis B, but its use in the United
States has been recommended only for health-care workers and those
at high risk. The vaccine can prevent the disease, but it cannot
cure it once a patient is infected. And the vaccine is expensive _
about $120 for the recommended three-shot series.
   Margolis said the Centers for Disease Control has proposed that
consideration be given to the universal use of the hepatitis B
vaccine among newborn infants or among children. But he said a
program of vaccination among the young would not have a noticable
effect on the spread of hepatitis B for 10 to 30 years.
   Kuvin said he believed the threat of the disease could be
controlled with the vaccine, but that since the innoculation became
available in 1982 it has not been widely used.
   ``Unless it becomes utilized, we are in for a serious national
tragedy,'' said Kuvin.
   The number of U.S. hepatitis B cases has increased from 200,000
in 1978 to about 300,000 in 1988, he said. On a global basis, the
problem is even more severe. There are an estimated 300 million
cases worldwide, Kuvin said, and an estimated 1.5 million of the
babies born this year will die eventually of the disease or its
complications.
   The foundation is sponsoring a two-day conference on AIDS, or
acquired immune deficiency syndrome, and hepatitis B.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
