<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BoardinghouseMurders     11-22 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Boardinghouse Murders,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Victim Identified</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG WILLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities on Monday identified one of the
seven bodies found buried outside a boardinghouse, but the coroner
said he has not yet determined how any of the victims died.
   County coroner Charles Simmons said the body of Benjamin Fink,
60, a former resident of Dorothea Puente's Victorian boardinghouse
in downtown Sacramento, was identified through fingerprints.
   No further information was released on Fink. But Robert Fink told
reporters last week that his brother had been a chronic alcoholic
since age 17, that he spent most of his life in Sacramento on the
streets, and that he had moved into the Puente boarding house
earlier this year.
   Simmons said his office had completed autopsies on six of the
seven victims. He said the seventh autopsy would be finished on
Tuesday, but that a final report with toxicology studies would not
be completed until sometime next week.
   Simmons said despite the extreme decomposition of most of the
bodies, he obtained good fingerprints from at least three victims
and there are still ``better than 50-50 chances'' of determining the
cause of death.
   The victims have been identified as three men and three women,
with an autopsy still pending on a seventh badly decomposed body.
   Puente, 59, the landlady at the boardinghouse where the bodies
were discovered last week, remained in jail without bail on one
murder charge. Authorities said they expect to file additional
charges soon.
   Detectives say they believe Puente murdered elderly boarders and
hid their bodies in order to collect their Social Security checks.
She said in a television interview after her arrest last Wednesday
that she didn't kill anyone but admitted, ``the checks I cashed,
yes.''
</TEXT>
