<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-88 0121EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-HumanRights     11-22 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Human Rights,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Psychiatrists To Inspect Soviet Institutions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sixteen American psychiatrists will visit
Soviet mental institutions for two weeks in January to check on
allegations that political dissidents are held there for harsh
treatment as punishment for their views.
   When the psychiatrists return they will publish their findings,
and the Soviets will be permitted to send psychiatrists to the
United States for meetings with American experts on practices in
this country.
   The reciprocal agreement, announced Monday at the State
Department, appeared to represent another step to improve superpower
relations. However, the Soviet reputation in the controversial area
of psychiatry could be at stake.
   Charles E. Redman, the State Department spokesman, said the
purpose of the visit, which was arranged last week in Moscow by a
visiting U.S. delegation, was ``to study and analyze the U.S.
psychiatric process.''
   He declined to say exactly how many Soviet citizens were in
institutions as punishment, but said there were ``a number of people
in that category.''
   Soviet dissident psychiatrist Anatoly Koryagin said last year he
knew of 183 political activists detained in psychiatric institutions.
   ``That is the number known to me,'' he told the American
Psychiatric Association at a meeting in Chicago. ``The total is much
larger, of course.''
   Koryagin was imprisoned for ``anti-Soviet agitation'' in 1981
after detailing numerous cases in which political dissidents were
confined in Soviet mental hospitals. After examining many, he
diagnosed them as sane.
   During his imprisonment, he was tortured, force-fed, mentally
abused and given powerful psychotropic drugs, Koryagin said.
   Koryagin, who was freed in February 1987, said there were 16 such
institutions for the criminally insane in which political dissidents
were held.
   Leading Soviet dissident Andrei D. Sakharov, during a visit to
Washington last week, called detention in psychiatric institutions
for political purposes ``one of the most acute abuses of human
rights'' in his country.
   Sakharov said some political dissidents were detained but were
outnumbered by ``chronic complainers'' who had been sent to
institutions for habitually criticizing their supervisers.
   Redman said the American psychiatrists and other experts would be
able to examine patients and also discuss law and mental health with
Soviet authorities.
   He said the agreement anticipated ``an intensification of
professional contacts'' between American and Soviet psychiatrists.
   The spokesman said the United States was interested is discussing
with the Soviets the ``use of psychiatry as a threat or punishment
for people who we feel are actually incarcerated for political and
religious activity.''
   The Soviets had promised earlier this year to allow an American
delegation to visit their institutions. The issue is one of many
human rights concerns the Reagan administration has raised with
Moscow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881122-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-88 0128EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ConservativeCabinet     11-22 0879</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Conservative Cabinet,890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Conservatives Gleeful Over Recent Bush Appointments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conservatives, watching warily as their ranks
are passed by for one top-level post after another, are nonetheless
buoyed by George Bush's appointment of their philosophical soul
mates John Sununu and Lee Atwater.
   The week after the election, a virtual Who's Who of the right
beat a path to the Jackson Place brownstone housing the offices of
Dan Quayle's transition team to court what some considered their
main link in the new administration.
   But with Bush's selection of Sununu as White House chief of staff
and Atwater for stewardship of the Republican National Committee,
members of the right believe they will have more than one partisan
in the White House even as Bush turns to people known more as
pragmatists than ideologues to fill out Cabinet posts.
   ``We see Dan Quayle as a strong ally but with the moves George
Bush has been making recently the indication is that we don't need a
one-man allegiance inside the administration,'' said L. Brent Bozell
III, executive director of the Conservative Victory Committee, a
political action committee that works for conservative candidates.
   ``The choice of Sununu, the choice of Lee Atwater _ I think
George Bush is making a very strong pitch to conservatives that he
wants them active in the administration,'' he said in an interview
last week.
   Other conservatives are simply beside themselves with glee.
   ``I think it's the best chief of staff appointment in my 22 years
in Washington,'' Paul Weyrich, president of the Free Congress
Research and Education Foundation, said of the Sununu selection.
Weyrich's group is a conservative think-tank.
   ``Last Thursday was really neat about Sununu and Atwater,'' said
conservative activist Richard Vigurie.
   In August, conservatives hailed the selection of Quayle, the
Indiana senator who stood on the right side of such issues as
abortion, aid to the Nicaraguan rebels and school prayer.
   But some still wondered about Bush, who ran as a moderate in his
1980 bid for the presidency.
   ``I don't think Mr. Bush has completely dispelled some of the
uncertainty that has come down over the years,'' said Dr. Robert
Grant of the American Freedom Coalition, a conservative organization
that has worked for aid to the Contras. ``With some of the
conservative leaders, there's still a certain amount of reservation
there but with Quayle there is no hesitancy ... because he has a
track record.''
   Conscious of Quayle's background, conservatives sought him out in
the days after the election.
   On a single day, the vice president-elect's schedule included a
breakfast meeting with columnist William Safire, lunch with former
United Nations ambassador Jeane Kirkpatrick and an afternoon
discussion with Ed Feulner, president of the Heritage Foundation, a
conservative think-tank.
   The wooing of one of their own made perfect sense to
conservatives who scoff at questions about Quayle's academic
background and military career that have dogged him since his
selection at the Republican National Convention.
   ``He's been an ally and a friend for many years and it's a
logical channel for conservatives to this administration because we
don't have to teach him the philosophy,'' Weyrich said. ``I think
he's gotten a very bad rap in this campaign _ he's a lot brighter
and more able than I think he was pictured to be.''
   Concerns that Bush will return to his moderate leanings have
forced conservatives to act, Grant said. ``The way to avert that
concern is to push your agenda and find people who will underscore
that agenda.''
   But former President Richard M. Nixon, who met with Quayle on
Monday, cautioned the vice president-elect against becoming the
conservative voice in the administration.
   ``I would not want to have Senator Quayle, who is a conservative,
to simply be a so-called house conservative. That doesn't serve his
interest,'' Nixon said. ``I urged him _ and he agrees _ that he
should reach out, not only to conservatives, listen to them, but
others within the party, and in the Democratic Party as well.''
   Self-interest is not the only reason conservatives are seeking
out Quayle. Some worry about the role their ally will play in the
Bush administration.
   ``I think what you're seeing from these conservatives is a move
to bolster Dan Quayle and show solidarity with the man,'' said
Bozell.
   ``I just don't think that conservatives want to see Dan Quayle
put in a back office somewhere, in the proverbial windowless office
of the administration,'' he said. ``They want to see him active out
there and I think that's going to happen.''
   But Donald Devine of the American Conservative Union, a
legislative interest organization, believes that Quayle shouldn't
rush into a high-profile role.
   ``The most important thing for Dan Quayle is that he takes his
time, learns the job and solidifies his reputation. He shouldn't be
in a hurry,'' said Devine, who served as President Reagan's director
of the Office of Personnel Management from 1981 to 1985.
   As for a conservative link in the administration, the selection
of Sununu and Atwater indicates that Quayle is not the only liaison,
according to Devine.
   ``I would say he is a link to the administration but ... I think
George Bush is going to be a good link,'' he said.
</TEXT>
