<1ST_LINE>r i PM-IRAArrest     11-22 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-IRA Arrest,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say Last Of 8 Jailbreakers Is Held</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police say they have arrested a man they
identified as the last of eight IRA members still at large after a
1981 escape from a Northern Ireland courthouse.
   Police said Gerard Michael Sloan, 35, of Belfast, Northern
Ireland, was arrested Monday at Dublin Airport, where he was about
to board an airliner. He was traveling under an assumed name and had
a ticket to Toronto, police said.
   Six other members of the outlawed Irish Republican Army,
including Sloan's brother Anthony, were recaptured in the republic
five years ago and were imprisoned in Portloaise jail. They were
sentenced under laws permitting guerrilla suspects to be tried in
the jurisdiction of their arrest, regardless of where their alleged
crimes were committed.
   The laws have been used to overcome difficulties in extraditing
IRA suspects from the republic to Britain. The IRA, fighting to
drive the British out of predominantly Northern Ireland, wants to
unite the British province with the Roman Catholic republic.
   The seventh man among the escapees, Joseph Doherty, was arrested
by the FBI in New York in 1983 and has since been resisting
extradition to Northern Ireland from his cell in the Manhattan
Correctional Center.
   The eight escaped after being convicted of trying to murder Capt.
Herbert Westmacott of Britain's undercover Special Air Services in
Belfast. Gerard Sloan got 18 years for his part and for arms
possession.
</TEXT>
