<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-88 0220EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     11-22 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Drops, Stocks At Record High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar dropped against the Japanese yen Tuesday
while share prices rose moderately, reaching another record high on
the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 121.78 yen, down 0.74 yen from Monday's
close of 122.52 yen. Opening at 121.85 yen, the currency moved
within 121.60 yen and 122.85 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 104.06-point
winner the previous day, added another 145.86 points, or 0.50
percent, to finish trading at 29,430.12, its record high. On Monday,
the index closed at 29,284.26 points.
   The dollar slumped at the opening of trading due mainly to the
absence of joint central bank intervention during the previous
session, according to dealers. They also cited recent remarks by
President-elect George Bush ruling out tax hikes to narrow the U.S.
federal budget deficit.
   Market sources said the Bank of Japan entered the market to buy
dollars Tuesday when the dollar fell to around 121.60 yen.
   ``It's not dollar-selling that's pushing the currency down
further at the moment, but rather that nobody wants to keep many
dollars around prior to a holiday,'' said a dealer with the Bank of
Tokyo, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Market participants were inclined to sell the dollar ahead of the
Labor Thanksgiving Day national holiday on Wednesday, when currency
and stock markets will be closed, he said. The dealer also said many
others were sitting on the sidelines in expectation of further
intervention by the central bank.
   Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa said Tuesday morning that Japan
was willing to take measures to save the U.S. currency. But he
indicated he was not overly concerned about the dollar's fall to the
upper 121.00-yen level.
   Miyazawa also said the dollar's slide following the U.S.
presidential election on Nov. 8 stemmed from speculation that has
ignored basic economic fundamentals between the United States and
Japan.
</TEXT>
