<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-88 0323EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Korea     11-22 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea,0538</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chun Faces Subpoena On Uprising, To Apologize To Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A National Assembly committee probing
the bloody military suppression of the 1980 Kwangju uprising voted
today to subpoena former President Chun Doo-hwan to explain his role
in the incident.
   The subpeona came a day before aides say Chun, in a last ditch
attempt to calm growing public anger, will apologize on national
television for corruption and abuses of power during his rule.
   Opposition lawmakers on the National Assembly committee ignored
pleas from government members to wait until Chun speaks to the
nation before deciding whether to proceed with a subpoena.
   The committee voted 16-12 to subpoena the former president, with
members of the governing Democratic Justice Party voting against.
   Opposition groups and many ordinary Koreans have been demanding
Chun be investigated and punished for alleged corruption and
wholesale violation of human rights. Radical groups demanding Chun's
arrest have staged a series of violent demonstrations.
   According to his aides, Chun will apologize on national
television Wednesday for corruption by some of his relatives and
associates and human rights abuses during his seven-year term that
ended in February.
   The former general, who took power with military backing in 1980,
is also to announce he will turn over most of his wealth to the
government and accept rural banishment to atone for abuses under his
rule.
   Plans for Chun to make his statement Monday or today were delayed
by problems finding a safe haven where he would be secure from
attacks by radical students and other opponents, aides said.
   Chun denies any personal wrongdoing, but some of his relatives
and associates have been convicted or charged with embezzling public
funds and peddling government influence.
   President Roh Tae-woo, another former general and associate of
Chun, is trying to defuse the crisis without damaging his
government's position.
   Roh, who won a plurality but not a majority in December
presidential elections as two other candidates split the opposition
vote, must somehow satisfy public indignation against Chun while
distancing his government and party from the past abuses.
   Roh indicated he is considering pardoning Chun after the former
leader makes a public apology, according to South Korean press
reports. But governing party officials indicate they will initiate a
probe against Chun if the apology fails to quiet public anger.
   The National Assembly subcommittee probing the incident in the
southern city of Kwangju decided to go ahead and subpoena Chun after
he refused to answer requests earlier this year to appear before the
panel.
   Chun was a senior general and in effective control of the
government when troops killed some 200 people putting down an
uprising by citizens and students in Kwangju. Dissident groups claim
up to 2,000 people were killed.
   The committee said it expected to issue subpoenas in the next few
days and officials indicated Chun would be summoned in early
December. The ex-president would face prosecution if he did not obey
the subpoena.
   South Korean newspapers speculated today that Chun will apologize
for the handling of the Kwangju incident in his address to the
nation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
