<DOCNO> AP881122-0038 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-88 0331EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Scarfo-Mob     11-22 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scarfo-Mob,0533</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities: Mafia Power Vaccuum From Convictions Will Be Filled</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On the streets of south Philadelphia, home to
many of the area's Mafia members, few believe the racketeering
conviction of mob boss Nicodemo ``Little Nicky'' Scarfo and 16
associates means the end of organized crime.
   ``The convictions aren't gonna change anything,'' said Dino
Crimi, whose cousin, Salvatore Scafidi, was one of the 17 convicted
Saturday after a two-month trial. ``In fact, it should get worse.
Now it's all open territory out here.''
   Scarfo and his associates were convicted on all charges in a
racketeering conspiracy that included nine murders, four attempted
murders, drug dealing, loan-sharking and illegal gambling.
   All face possible sentences of 40 to 55 years in prison. Scarfo
is already serving a 14-year sentence for a 1987 extortion and
conspiracy conviction.
   Scarfo, whom the government called ``a paranoid, cold-blooded
killer,'' seized control of the Philadelphia-southern New Jersey mob
after the murders of his predecessors.
   Former boss Angelo Bruno was shot in the head in 1980 as he sat
in a car outside his south Philadelphia home. His successor, Philip
``Chicken Man'' Testa, was killed less than a year later when a
remote-controlled bomb packed with nails exploded when he opened his
front door.
   Scarfo continued the murders to eliminate enemies and consolidate
power, according to prosecutors.
   Capt. Frank Friel, head of the police department's
organized-crime unit, believes the mob has learned its lesson and
won't put a killer in charge again. He sees a local leader emerging
in the mold of Bruno.
   ``They'll get a low-profile businessman,'' Friel said.
   Joel Friedman, chief of the U.S. Justice Department's Organized
Crime Strike Force in Philadelphia, said the mob was crippled but
will not disappear as long as there is money to be made through drug
trafficking, loan sharking, extortion and gambling.
   Nevertheless, the conviction of the mob's key figures has
``shifted the equilibrium in the public's favor'' and police will
maintain the pressure to diminish mob influence, he said.
   ``With one conviction, we were able to take the guts out (of the
mob),'' said Assistant U.S. Attorney Louis Pichini, who headed the
five-member prosecution team. ``It broke the myth of the Mafia's
invincibility.''
   Friedman said he expects other gangsters to fill the leadership
vacuum.
   Some predict mobsters from New York, particularly the Gambino
family, will try to take over in Atlantic City, N.J., where Scarfo
lived.
   An FBI agent quoted anonymously by the Philadelphia Daily News
speculated that reputed Gambino family head John Gotti will take
control, possibly even with Scarfo's approval, because the two were
friendly in recent years.
   Officials agree that with or without Scarfo's blessing, someone
eventually will fill the void to control the millions generated by
the area's illegal enterprises.
   ``Even though all the bosses have been in jail (awaiting trial),
the numbers game has been going on and so has the loansharking,''
the agent said. ``We have seen signs that they're becoming more
involved in methamphetamine. We expect that to continue under a
caretaker or somebody coming in from the outside.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
