<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Steinberg     11-22 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Steinberg,0595</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Psychiatric Report on Nussbaum; Photographer Used Tricks To Hide
Bruises</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On the night prosecutors say Joel Steinberg
fatally beat his 6-year-old daughter, Lisa, his live-in companion
said she heard noises from a bedroom in their apartment ``like Joel
throwing Lisa,'' sources say.
   Steinberg, on trial for murder in the girl's death, was angry the
night of Nov. 1, 1987, because he wanted Lisa to drink more water
and had given her and companion Hedda Nussbaum hot peppers to make
them thirstier, Nussbaum reportedly told a psychiatrist at Columbia
Presbyterian Medical Center on Nov. 20.
   A copy of the unidentified psychiatrist's report was obtained by
WCBS-TV, which reported it Monday. The Associated Press confirmed
the report's contents through sources close to the case who spoke on
condition they were not identified.
   The report quoted Nussbaum as saying that Lisa asked, ``Will
daddy still take me out with him?'' Nussbaum said she responded,
``Go ask him.''
   Nussbaum said that after Lisa went to ask Steinberg, she heard
noises in the bedroom ``like Joel throwing Lisa,'' the report said.
   Steinberg then appeared in the bathroom carrying the child and
said, as he handed her over to Nussbaum, ``This is your child; what
have you done; this has gone far enough,'' the report said.
   Nussbaum placed Lisa on the floor and noticed water and food
coming out of her mouth.
   The report said Nussbaum thought Steinberg may have poured water
down Lisa's mouth and that she was drowning. Nussbaum said she then
began pumping the child's chest.
   Nussbaum told the psychiatrist that Steinberg left the Greenwich
Village apartment shortly afterward and returned about 10 p.m.
Around 6 a.m., Steinberg said, ``She's stopped breathing,'' and told
Nussbaum to ``call 911.''
   Lisa was taken unconscious from Steinberg's apartment. She died
three days later at St. Vincent's Hospital.
   Steinberg, a 47-year-old disbarred lawyer, denies he hit Lisa,
and says she fell unconscious after choking on food she had vomited.
   Nussbaum, 46, a former editor of children's books, also was
charged in Lisa's death, but those charges were dropped.
   Nussbaum has spent the last year undergoing physical and
psychiatric rehabilitation for injuries the prosecution says she
suffered at Steinberg's hands.
   In testimony Monday at Steinberg's state criminal court trial, a
photographer said he used poses and lighting tricks to hide bruises
he saw on Lisa when he took pictures of her in school two weeks
before she died.
   Stuart Gross said he initially was reluctant to photograph the
first-grader when he visited the school Oct. 22, 1987, because of
her numerous bruises and dirty, unkempt appearance.
   Gross said he eventually took several black and white pictures of
Lisa. He said he was drawn to her when she began directing two other
children on posing the way he wanted them.
   ``She seemed older, more mature,'' he said.
   ``I put her on the right side and I flooded my light into her and
I had her turn her head this way and down so you wouldn't see it.
The last thing my client wants to see is bruises.''
   He said the rumpled, dirty quality of Lisa's clothing was
eliminated ``in the way I photographed them.''
   Also Monday, Justice Harold Rothwax replaced a juror who sources
say was beaten last week by her live-in boyfriend. The juror is a
30-year-old mother of two whose name was withheld.
</TEXT>
