<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Obit-Kidd     11-22 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Kidd,0502</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Socialite Daughter Of First Lord Beaverbrook Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Janet Kidd, socialite daughter of the first Lord
Beaverbrook, the Canadian-born newspaper magnate and politician, has
died at age 80, her family reported today.
   Mrs. Kidd died Nov. 18 at home in the village of Ewhurst 25 miles
southwest of London. No cause of death was given.
   In 1987, she published ``The Beaverbrook Girl,'' a lively volume
of memoirs about her active and adventurous life, which included
horse breeding and flying helicopters.
   She was born in Halifax, Nova Scotia, to Max Aitken and his first
wife Gladys Drury.
   In 1910, her multi-millionaire father brought the family to live
in England, where he became a Conservative Party legislator and in
1916 bought the Daily Express, turning it into a major national
circulation newspaper.
   He was made a peer with the title Lord Beaverbrook in 1917 and in
World War II was minister of aircraft production and later minister
of supply.
   Janet Kidd grew up surrounded by celebrities, including writer
Rudyard Kipling and politician Lloyd George.
   She met her first husband, Ian Campbell, a compulsive gambler and
heir to a dukedom, in the casino at the fashionable French resort of
Le Touquet. Married in 1927, they were divorced in 1934.
   The following year, she married Drogo Montagu, son of the Earl of
Sandwich, but four years later he was killed as a flying instructor
with the Royal Air Force.
   Her third marriage was to Canadian Army officer Edward Kidd.
After the war, they lived in rural southwest England to indulge in
their mutual love of fox hunting. Her third husband died in 1979.
   At one stage, they were neighbors of the late Evelyn Waugh, whose
novels include ``Brideshead Revisited.''
   Waugh, who was known for his vitriolic pen, described in a
published letter one of their lavish parties _ ``Two bands... a
cabaret, an oyster bar in the harness room, stables floodlit, much
to the discomfort of the horses. One bit an American pornographer
who tried to give it vodka.''
   The bitten man was writer Norman Mailer, sometime husband of Mrs.
Kidd's elder daughter, Lady Jeanne Campbell.
   During her equestrian career, Mrs. Kidd was for more than 20
years a director of the All-England Show Jumping Ground at Hickstead
outside London.
   After twice breaking her back in falls from horses, she took up
racing horse-drawn carriages and breeding tough little Fjord horses
at her stud farm at Ewhurst, where she went to live in 1964.
   Another interest was flying helicopters. She was granted her
helicopter pilot's licence on her 60th birthday.
   In 1960, she bought a second home in Barbados, where she
entertained jet-setters, local politicians and members of various
royal families. She was a close friend of American career diplomat
Averell Harriman, who also had a home there.
   She is survived by a total of two daughters and two sons from her
three marriages.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881122-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-88 0504EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Mulroney     11-22 0632</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mulroney,0653</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Celebrates Victory With Hugs, U.S. Hymn In Hometown
Hall</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Canada-Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   BAIE-COMEAU, Quebec (AP) _ Prime Minister Brian Mulroney
celebrated his re-election in his rural hometown today with hugs,
handshakes and the playing of the U.S. Battle Hymn of the Republic.
   The American tone to the conclusion of a bitterly contested
contest made no difference to the 5,000 backers crammed into a local
recreation center. The returns showed Mulroney and his Conservative
Party had won an election that centered on the free trade pact with
the United States.
   ``We knew he was going to do it,'' paper worker Maurice Tougas
said of Mulroney's win between gulps of beer. ``Now that he's put
Baie-Comeau on the map, it's never going to come off.''
   Mulroney, who at the midpoint of his first term was third in the
polls behind opposition leaders John Turner and Ed Broadbent, fought
a tough campaign to come back and win a second majority government.
   Mulroney likes to portray himself as a statesman and Canada's
most competent leader, but he thrives on old-fashioned politicking.
   The 49-year-old prime minister comes from a working-class family
in Baie-Comeau, on the north shore of the St. Lawrence River. He was
ambitious and built a successful legal and corporate career in
Montreal.
   He first tried for the Conservative Party leadership in 1976 but
was not successful until 1983, the first year he was elected to the
House of Commons.
   Mulroney is the first bilingual native of Quebec to lead his
party, and he has used that fact skillfully in expanding the
Conservatives' base in that critical, largely French-speaking
province.
   Support for cronies was charged during his first years in office,
dropping his popularity drastically in the public opinion polls.
   Eight Cabinet ministers resigned in separate incidents, but by
the time he called the election Oct. 1 Mulroney had distanced
himself from the controversies and was able to point to an
experienced management team.
   But then Turner put Mulroney on the defensive during televised
debates in late October by charging the trade pact in effect would
sell Canada off to American business interests.
   National campaign chairman John Tory said two events helped the
Conservatives recover two weeks later: Mulroney's impromptu debate
with three free-trade hecklers in Victoria, British Columbia, and
former justice Emmett Hall's statement on free trade.
   Hall, considered the father of Medicare, said the free-trade deal
would not threaten the medical insurance plan. His comments dampened
opposition claims that the deal would hurt social programs.
   Mulroney had planned to stage the campaign on competency and the
prosperity that lasted through his term to create 1.3 million jobs
in Canada.
   By the campaign's closing days, however, Mulroney was exuberantly
telling crowds at his rallies that they had a choice between ``John
(Turner) the Ripper or Brian the Builder.''
   He described the opponents of the trade agreement he signed last
January with President Reagan as jittery, negative defenders of past
traditions that could not survive in the modern world.
   Mulroney, by contrast, saw himself as a ``nation builder,'' ready
to lead a competent Canada into full competition with the much
larger and more powerful United States.
   The phrase surfaced in the last of six hours of a debate last
month, when Turner accused the prime minister of selling out Canada
with the free trade agreement.
   Mulroney replied that he carried through on the agreement to
build Canada, just as his father had gone to northeastern Quebec 55
years ago where he and hundreds of other laborers built a small town.
   ``I believe that in my own modest way, I am nation building
because I believe this benefits Canada, and I love Canada,'' the
prime minister said.
   The prime minister is a Roman Catholic. He is married and has
four children.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
