<HEAD>Former Soviet Paratrooper In Boston For Possible Transplant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 20-year-old former Soviet paratrooper has been
hospitalized here for tests to determine if he can receive a bone
marrow transplant to treat his leukemia.
   Alexander Muchnik of Klaipeda in the Lithuanian republic was
scheduled to undergo tests today at Brigham and Women's Hospital.
   Soviet doctors gave him little chance of surviving the illness
when his condition was diagnosed in July.
   Doctors in the Soviet Union couldn't perform the necessary
transplant, said Muchnik's aunt, Rosa Muchnik.
   Muchnik left his country Sunday on a trip set up by an uncle who
arranged for the international medical help.
   Meantime, the family raised only a few thousand dollars toward
the cost of the transplant.
   Muchnik's only source of bone marrow for the transplant is his
15-year-old sister, Viktoria, who accompanied Muchnik on the trip
along with their mother and stepfather. Muchnik's grandmother lives
is Brighton.
