<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-88 0542EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChicagoMayoral     11-22 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chicago Mayoral,0524</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Supreme Court Sets Chicago Mayoral Vote Next Spring</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chicago's mayoral race moves into high gear now,
with an Illinois Supreme Court's ruling that the election must be
held early next year.
   At least two of the seven hopefuls began running radio
advertisements on Monday. And the court's decision drops a political
barrier to the expected announcements that Mayor Eugene Sawyer and
State's Attorney Richard M. Daley will run.
   ``This starts the positioning phase of the race,'' said Don Rose,
a strategist for Alderman Timothy Evans, one of the contenders to
fill out the last two years of the late Harold Washington's term.
   ``The public is still not fully involved at this point,'' Rose
said, ``so it becomes a period of jockeying and preparing for the
hard decisions, such as whether to continue.''
   Most of the candidates have said they are in the contest to the
end, but because of racial issues involved, it's become commonplace
to assume some will drop out.
   Political observers seem to agree that there can be no more than
one black candidate if the black voting bloc that made Washington
the city's first black mayor is not to be split.
   Likewise, a fragmented white vote probably would mean a
continuation of blacks controlling City Hall.
   Sawyer, who was appointed by City Council after Washington's
death of a heart attack on Nov. 25, 1987, had been hoping for a
ruling that would allow him to serve out the full term, through 1991.
   But the court on Monday sided with city officials who scheduled a
Feb. 28 primary and an April 4 general election next year.
   The seven justices ruled that state laws governing vacancies in
office were designed to ensure that an appointed official would not
serve such a long portion of an unexpired term.
   Although Sawyer had hoped for a different ruling, he indicated he
was prepared to run and said he was ``pleased that this decision has
been made and that the people in Chicago are no longer in limbo.''
   ``We are ready for the upcoming election and look forward to
winning it,'' said Sawyer, who has raised nearly $3 million in less
than a year against the possibility of a spring election.
   Daley, widely reported to be planning a second bid for the job
his father held for two decades, said he would make an announcement
``in the next two weeks.''
   ``This is a serious decision,'' Daley said, adding that ``the
public is happy that the Supreme Court finally rendered a decision''
on the election question.
   Evans and Danny Davis, both considered leading contenders for
Washington's mantle of black political leadership in Chicago, also
praised the ruling.
   According to a recent Chicago Sun-Times@ABC-TV poll, Daley is
supported by 37 percent of all voters; Evans by 22 percent, Sawyer
by 10 percent, and Alderman Lawrence Bloom 9 percent.
   The remaining 22 percent was undecided or divided among the other
announced candidates _ Davis and white Alderman Edward Burke, former
Chicago Parks District Superintendent Edmund Kelly.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
