<DOCNO> AP881122-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-88 0559EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SniperAttack     11-22 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sniper Attack,0524</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mexican Police Believe Raft Assailants May Have Been Drug Dealers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOLDEN LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAJITAS, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexican police believe that snipers who
fired on a three-member Rio Grande rafting party, killing one, were
drug traffickers who resented the Americans' unwitting intrusion
into a drug deal.
   U.S. and Chihuahua state police searched the rugged area Monday
and enlisted a top tracker to find the attackers who killed Michael
Heffley, 40, as he tried to drag his wounded wife, Jamie, 32, to
safety.
   Police have not identified suspects or made any arrests in the
attack, which occurred Saturday during a rafting excursion outside
Big Bend National Park on the southwestern Texas border between the
United States and Mexico.
   Authorities later combed the area on horseback and discovered
tracks that indicated the assailants fled on horses toward Mulato, a
Mexican town about 15 miles from the shooting scene.
   Heffley was shot in the back with a .30-30 caliber rifle as he
tried to help his wife from the raft under a barrage of gunfire,
authorities said. She had been wounded in the left side and left
shoulder.
   The couple's guide, Jim Burr, 36, an employee of Terlingua-based
Far Flung Adventures, was shot in the right thigh with a .22-caliber
rifle, said Jesus Porras Vega of Mexico's Chihuahua state judicial
police.
   Mexican police theorize the snipers, who fired from atop
300-foot-high bluffs in Mexico overlooking the Rio Grande, were drug
traffickers who resented the boaters' unwitting intrusion into an
illegal drug transaction.
   ``The assailants didn't want them to see,'' said state police
officer Jesus Porras Vega.
   Smuggling has been an economic cornerstone of the area for years.
Horses and guns were the first contraband; later, smugglers took
candelilla leaves from the United States back into Mexico to boil
and turn into candle wax.
   Marijuana is now smuggled across the border, though little of it
passes through on the ground in the Big Bend region. Most marijuana
crossing into Texas is flown in by large-scale traffickers.
   Presidio County Sheriff Rick Thompson said he doubts the
smuggling theory. He and Porras said the area near the ridge had
been a marijuana field in the past, but was not used for that
purpose this year.
   ``It's not like they (the assailants) were out there tending
their marijuana or cutting or harvesting it or whatever,'' Thompson
said. ``So there was no provocation.''
   Residents of the isolated area along the river think the
assailants might have been under the influence of drugs.
   ``I think they were drunk or something and said, `Hey, let's see
if we can hit the raft,''' said Ed Allen, assistant manager of
Lajitas-based Big Bend River Tours.
   The two injured were in stable condition Monday at Brewster
Memorial Hospital in Alpine. ``My wound's pretty minor. I just got a
hole in my leg,'' Burr said.
   At the time of the shooting, the assailants were in Mexico and
the victims were in the United States, meaning the attackers could
be tried in either country, officials said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
