<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-88 0730EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel-Politics     11-22 0656</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Politics,0677</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Labor-Likud Talks Break Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Talks aimed at forming a broad-based coalition
government with the right-wing Likud and leftist Labor parties broke
off today over what post Labor leader Shimon Peres might have in a
new Cabinet.
   A Labor Party statement broadcast by Israel radio said there
appeared to be ``no basis'' for continuing exploratory talks about
joining Likud.
   Officials said the talks broke down over Labor demands for senior
Cabinet posts and an active search for peace negotiations with the
Arabs, who have revolted against Israeli rule in the occupied
territories since Dec. 8. At least 314 Palestinians and 11 Israelis
have died in the unrest.
   A spokesman for the Foreign Ministry, which is headed by Peres,
left open the possibility talks could resume later.
   However, some Labor Party officials said it was likely Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir would now form a narrow government with
small religious and right-wing parties.
   A Peres aide said the talks broke down over Labor's demand for
parity in top Cabinet posts and the peace issue. He said Likud would
not give a definite answer.
   ``(Likud leaders) didn't say no, but they didn't say yes. Most of
all they didn't convince Labor this would be a government that would
put Israel on the right track toward peace,'' he said on condition
of anonymity.
   Shamir's Likud, which won 40 seats in the 120-member parliament
in the Nov. 1 elections, secured the majority needed for a coalition
by allying with seven religious and far-right parties.
   But Shamir, seeking to blunt the power of the small parties,
heeded a call from President Chaim Herzog to try to include Labor in
a national unity government.
   Shamir spokesman Yossi Ahimeir said even if the breakdown in
talks with Labor proved permanent there was a possibility that Labor
would join the government in a narrow capacity at a later date.
   Shamir has 13 days before he needs to report to the president on
his efforts to form a new government. Herzog could grant him a
three-week extension.
   Another Shamir aide who demanded anonymity said the talks
deadlocked over Labor demands that it get two of the four major
portfolios _ prime ministry, defense, foreign affairs and finance.
   Israel radio said agreement was reached that Shamir would stay as
prime minister and Labor's Yitzhak Rabin would remain as defense
minister. But there was an impasse over the remaining two posts, one
of which Peres sought for himself.
   The Shamir aide said Likud refused to grant a Labor demand for
veto power in the inner Cabinet, a group of senior ministers who
make key policy decisions.
   In the outgoing coalition government, formed after the 1984
elections ended in stalemate, each party has five seats in the inner
Cabinet, and no major decisions are taken without a consensus
between the two major parties.
   Shamir aides said talks continued with the small religious
parties.
   Israel radio quoted Labor officials as saying they believed
Shamir faced a difficult task in working out an agreement to satisfy
ultra-Orthodox without alienating Jewish supporters of Israel abroad.
   If Shamir forms a government without Labor, he will likely face
increased pressure from the far-right to launch a campaign to
establish new Jewish settlements in the occupied territories and
perhaps annex occupied territory.
   He may also face new pressure from Jewish fundamentalists to
enforce the observance of the Sabbath by closing restaurants and
soccer stadiums and to tighten laws against the sale of pork.
   But promises to the religious have already raised the ire of
North American and European Jews, who warn they may cut political
and financial support to Israel if the new government approves the
so-called ``Who Is A Jew'' legislation.
   The change would make ineligible for immigrant status any Jew who
was converted by non-Orthodox rabbis. Jews abroad see the proposal
as an attack on the Reform and Conservative movements in Judaism.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
