<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BrooklynBridge 1stLd-Writethru a0496 11-22 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brooklyn Bridge, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0496,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Men Caught Dismantling Brooklyn Bridge For Scrap Metal</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to RECAST, move up damage estimate, closing
of walkway. Minor editing and deletion of now-redundant material
throughout. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ultimate con _ selling the Brooklyn Bridge _
is no joke to city authorities who accused two men of prying off
pieces of the historic span and selling them to a scrap metal dealer.
   Damage was estimated at $37,000. The theft severely weakened the
walkway and catwalk of the bridge, and both were closed temporarily
for repairs.
   ``People joke about selling the Brooklyn Bridge, but what these
guys did is not funny, it's dangerous,'' Samuel Schwartz, city
Department of Transportation chief engineer, said Monday.
   Ruffino Sauco and John Berisi were caught dismantling aluminum
pieces of the 105-year-old suspension bridge's pedestrian walkway
Saturday, said Officer Joseph Gallagher, a police spokesman.
   The material was apparently sold as scrap, Gallagher said.
   Transportation officials had been watching the walkway after they
found large pieces missing earlier this month.
   Sauco, Berisi and a third man were seen climbing the historic
span early Saturday evening. Police called to the scene caught Sauco
as the three were using burglary tools to pry supports loose from
the walkway and from a catwalk used by ironworkers, Gallagher said.
   The other two men fled. However, Berisi was arrested an hour
later when he returned to a stolen van, Gallagher said. Sauco told
police the vehicle was used to carry away the pieces of the bridge,
the spokesman said.
   Police were still searching for the third suspect.
   Sauco, 37, and Berisi, 36, were charged with grand larceny,
criminal mischief, reckless endangerment, criminal trespass and
possession of burglary tools, Gallagher said. Berisi also was
charged with stealing the van, possession of a hypodermic needle,
and several previous, unrelated burglaries.
   ``We are pressing the district attorney to see this is treated
very harshly and not just as a prank, particularly the charge of
reckless endangerment,'' Schwartz said.
   ``First, they were flinging these heavy pieces of metal onto the
ground by the bridge,'' he said. ``And for our ironworkers, who
sometimes are called out for emergency repairs in the middle of the
night, it could have cost them their lives.
   ``They're lucky they were caught by police, and not by
ironworkers.''
</TEXT>
