<2ND_LINE>PM-EEC-PLO, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0466,0554</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEC Welcomes PLO Statehood Declaration, Urges Peace Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with Israel criticizing EEC
endorsement. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, `In a...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 12 European Economic Community
nations have welcomed the PLO parliament-in-exile's declaration of
an independent Palestinian state as containing ``positive steps''
towards Middle East peace.
   In Jerusalem today, Israeli officials criticized the EEC
endorsement.
   ``We don't see eye to eye with our European friends,'' said a
Israeli Foreign Ministry official who requested anonymity. ``They
see the declaration as a denunciation of terrorism, and we don't.''
   The EEC nations on Monday repeated their call for an
international peace conference on the Arab-Israeli conflict under
U.N. auspices. Israel opposes such a conference, which King Hussein
of Jordan first proposed in 1987.
   In a statement, the EEC foreign ministers welcomed the Palestine
National Council's indirect recognition of Israel's right to exist
and said they were pleased that the PLO body ``explicitly condemned
violence'' in its Nov. 15 declaration of an independent Palestinian
state with Jerusalem as its capital.
   ``The (EEC nations) attach particular importance to the decisions
adopted by the Palestine National Council in Algiers, which reflect
the will of the Palestinian people to assert their national identity
and which include positive steps towards the peaceful settlement of
the Arab-Israeli conflict,'' said the EEC statement.
   It urged ``all parties concerned ... to take this opportunity and
contribute to the peace process in a positive way with a view to a
just, global and lasting solution to the Arab-Israeli conflict.''
   Israel has rejected the Algiers declaration as neither
recognizing the Jewish state nor renouncing terrorism.
   Greek Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias, the chairman of the
ministers meeting, called the Palestinian proclamation ``a
historical contribution towards peace in the Middle East,''
   He said Greece would like to see a meeting between the EEC
ministers and Palestine Liberation Organization chairman Yasser
Arafat.
   ``It is very important for the Twelve to have a direct dialogue
with Arafat, to hear him repeat his Algiers declaration.''
   Papoulias has raised the issue of such a meeting before but the
other EEC nations, notably Britain, oppose this.
   ``We must have an international conference. That is what counts.
That is what's important,'' Foreign Minister Leo Tindemans of
Belgium said after the meeting. ``It's from that conference that a
solution must come.''
   Foreign Minister Giulio Andreotti of Italy said the EEC states
``must all defend this statement. We must not take diferent
positions.''
   He referred to Greece, which is considering recognizing the
independent Palestinian state along with Israel. Greece now
recognizes neither.
   ``Greeks are satisfied with the statement,'' said Papoulias.
   Paloulias said his government was still discussing the issue of
recognizing the Palestinian state and Israel. ``This problem has
occupied us and continues to do so,'' he said.
   Egypt, Turkey and Cyprus are the only three countries with
diplomatic ties to Israel that have so far recognized the declared
Palestinian state.
   In their statement, the EEC nations expressed concern about
continuing violence on the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip, the scene of a Palestinian uprising that began almost a year
ago and has claimed the lives of more than 310 Palestinians and of
11 Israelis.
</TEXT>
