<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Bush-TransitionChoices 1stLd-Writethru a0439 11-22 0842</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-Transition Choices, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0439,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says Boskin May Be Economic Adviser, No Decision on Tower</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 4 grafs with Bush on Tower and Boskin, picking
up 4th graf pvs, On Monday; Subs grafs 13-15 pvs with 1 graf on
Tower</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect George Bush said today that
Michael Boskin ``might well prove'' to be the next chairman of the
president's Council of Economic Advisers but that no decisions have
been made for that position or for secretary of defense.
   Bush told reporters traveling with him to Alabama that reports
saying former Sen. John G. Tower of Texas is in line to become the
next defense secretary were premature.
   ``The Tower story is not right,'' Bush said. ``No decision has
been made.'' He indicated he would not name his new Pentagon chief
until next week at the earliest.
   As for Boskin, a Stanford University professor, Bush said: ``I
haven't sat down and talked to Mike and I want to do that.'' But he
said Boskin is a ``very good man. He might well prove to be the
economic adviser.''
   On Monday Bush announced that Attorney General Dick Thornburgh
and Education Secretary Lauro Cavazos would remain in their posts.
He also selected Richard Darman, a former Treasury official, to head
the Office of Management and Budget.
   In the two weeks since he was elected, Bush has filled four
Cabinet jobs. In addition to Cavazos and Thornburgh, Bush said
Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady would stay on, and former Treasury
Secretary James A. Baker III would become secretary of state. New
Hampshire Gov. John Sununu was selected the White House chief of
staff.
   That still leaves a slew of other top jobs vacant. Here, in no
particular order, are the Cabinets positions as well as the top
agency and executive posts that are still open.
   _ Agriculture. Still in the running is Robert Delano, former
president of the American Farm Bureau Federation. Also mentioned are
Clayton Yeutter, the U.S. trade representative, Sen. Dan Evans,
R-Wash., and Rep. Thomas Coleman of Missouri.
   _ Energy. Former Rep. Thomas Loeffler, who ran Bush's campaign in
Texas, has the inside track, according to the latest purveyors of
gossip. Also talked about are formmer White House aide Fred Khedouri
and former deputy secretary William Martin.
   _ Interior. Gov. Garrey Carruthers of New Mexico has taken
himself out of the running. That leaves Nathaniel Reed, a former
assistant secretary, and Evans high on the list.
   _ Environmental Protection Agency. A new name surfaced Monday:
Jay D. Hair, executive vice president of the National Wildlife
Federation. Still in the running are Michael Deland, an EPA regional
administrator in Boston, and former agency general counsel Francis
Blake.
   _ CIA. There is some thinking that Bush may keep CIA Director
William Webster on as an interim appointment, but others are still
thought to be in the running. They include James Lilley, the
ambassador to Korea, and former national security adviser Brent
Scowcroft.
   _ NSC adviser. Lilley and Scowcroft are also in the competition
for this key spot, along with Winston Lord, the ambassador to China,
and Richard Burt, the ambassador to West Germany.
   _ Defense. Tower, former chairman of the Senate Armed Services
Committee, is the most often-mentioned person for the job, but other
names have surfaced, including Paul O'Neill, the chairman of Alcoa.
Norman Augustine, author of a book which critiqued the Pentagon
procurement system, also is said to have a shot at the job.
   _ Health and Human Services. The same names keep cropping up for
this huge agency. They include Dorcas Hardy, the Social Security
commissioner, former Rep. William Gradison of Ohio, Sen. Lowell
Weicker of Connecticut and Deborah Steelman, a campaign aide to Bush.
   _ Transportation. Matthew Scocozza, a private lawyer who worked
as an assistant secretary, has emerged as a candidate. Others
possibles are Rep. Guy Molinari of New York; Peter Schabarum, an
urban transportation expert, and James Burnett, former head of the
National Transportation Safety Board.
   _ Labor. Rep. Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania is a leading contender,
as is William Kilberg, a Washington lawyer who worked in the
department in the Nixon administration. Ann Dore McLaughlin, the
current secretary, could keep the job, but she'll have stiff
competition from Ridge, Kilberg and former Rep. John Ehrlenborn of
Illinois.
   _ Housing and Urban Development. No new names cropped up on
Monday. Still mentioned as possibilities are Cleveland Mayor George
Voinovich, Indianapolis Mayor William Hudnut, businessman Robert
Woodson and campaign official Thaddeus Garrett.
   _ Commerce. Houston oilman Robert Mosbacher, a longtime friend of
Bush, is the odds-on favorite. Others on the list are former
Delaware Gov. Pete du Pont, former baseball commissioner Peter
Ueberroth and James Robinson, head of American Express Co.
   _ Veterans. Rep. Sonny Montgomery, a Mississippi Democrat, says
he has taken himself out of the running for this job, which has
recently been ungraded to a Cabinet-level slot. Ridge has been
mentioned, as has Everett Alvarez, a former deputy administrator of
the Veterans Administration.
</TEXT>
