<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Marcos, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0532,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marcos Petitions Court To Reconsider Ban On His Return</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RECASTS first two grafs; PICKS up 3rd graf pvs, `The court ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Ferdinand Marcos has
asked a Philippine court to allow him to return to his country.
   Marcos filed a petition Monday asking a Manila court to
reconsider a decision last month that banned the exiled leader from
returning to his country to answer testimony against him. Previously
lawyers for Marcos have said he was too ill to travel from Hawaii to
New York to hear U.S. charges against him.
   The court ruled the issue was a ``political matter'' that could
be resolved only by President Corazon Aquino, who refused to allow
Marcos to return for security reasons. Mrs. Aquino came to power
after Marcos was ousted in a civilian-military uprising in February
1986.
   Marcos and his wife, Imelda, were indicted in New York last month
on charges they diverted $103 million of Philippine government funds
to purchase New York real estate.
   Mrs. Marcos was arraigned on Oct. 31 before a New York federal
court and pleaded not guilty. Her husband's arraignment was
postponed indefinitely after his lawyers claimed he was too frail to
make the 10-hour flight from his exile in Hawaii to New York.
   Doctors have said Marcos, 71, has calcium deposits in his knee
joints, making it hard for him to walk and forcing him to use a
wheelchair. His aides also have said Marcos suffered from chest
pains, severe headaches and an eye ailment.
   Officials at the Sandiganbayan court in Manila said the latest
Marcos petition was filed on his behalf by his sister, Fortuna
Marcos-Barba.
   In the petition, Marcos asked the court to block the scheduled
Dec. 11 deposition by former Public Works and Highways Minister
Baltazar Aquino unless it is done in Marcos' presence. The former
minister is not related to Mrs. Aquino.
   Government lawyers say former minister Aquino has agreed to
testify in the Dec. 11 proceedings about alleged kickbacks Marcos
received from Japanese companies during his 20-year term in office.
   Marcos said that unless he is allowed to return to Manila for the
deposition, the court and the Philippine government ``would be
guilty of trial by publicity.''
   Government lawyers say they plan to use Aquino's testimony
against Marcos when Philippine criminal charges are filed against
him and he is eventually allowed to return to face them. The lawyers
say the former minister's testimony has to be taken soon because he
is ill and may die before Marcos is brought to trial.
   In his petition, Marcos argued that unless he is allowed to
cross-examine Baltazar Aquino, the testimony of the latter will not
be valid.
   The court has given no indication if it will hold hearings on the
latest Marcos petition or dismiss it.
</TEXT>
