<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MissingTeen-Agers     11-22 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Missing Teen-Agers,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Of Four Young Adults In New Haven Crash Legally Drunk</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK SEAVY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FARMINGTON, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials say the finding that four
young adults had been drinking, and two were legally drunk, when
their car plunged into a New Haven river does not end the
investigation into their deaths.
   Deputy Chief Medical Examiner H. Wayne Carver II said Monday that
it was not yet possible to determine what role alcohol played in the
accident.
   The tests found blood-alcohol levels ranging from 0.06 and 0.11
in the four. Under state law, a person is legally drunk with a
blood-alcohol level of 0.10.
   The four 1987 graduates of East Lyme High School _ Michael R.
Gallo, 20, Jill S. Sawyer, Christy S. Stevens and Laura M.
Lagrotteria, all 19 _ drowned early Nov. 13 after the car they were
riding in plunged into the Mill River at a swing bridge that was in
its open position.
   They were missing for several days, prompting a nationwide
search, before the submerged car was found last Thursday.
   The bridge, which pivots on a central axis, has been out of use
since August 1987 and is locked in its open position _ perpendicular
to the road _ to allow boat traffic to pass by.
   Carver declined to say which victims had the higher blood-alcohol
level readings, and authorities have said they haven't determined
who was driving the car. The car was owned by Stevens.
   The blood-alcohol levels correspond roughly to consumption of
between 1{ and five drinks, state Associate Medical Examiner Edward
T. McDonough said. Police have said that a case of beer, most of it
consumed, was found inside the sunken car.
   The youths, all of East Lyme, were reported missing by their
parents in the evening of Nov. 13, about 24 hours after they left
their homes for a night out in New Haven.
   City officials have conceded that there was a gap in concrete
barriers at the bridge the night of crash. Officials have said there
was a time when the two-ton concrete barriers completely blocked the
road, but they have been unable to say why or when the blocks were
moved.
   Robert I. Reardon Jr., an attorney for Stevens' family, said the
blood-alcohol levels were ``inconsequential.''
   ``Virtually anyone driving down that road at night would have
driven off the bridge,'' he said.
</TEXT>
