<HEAD>Five Young People Killed in House Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ELIZABETHTON, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five children from two families died
early today when they were trapped upstairs in a burning house,
officials said.
   The five, including 3-year-old twins, tried to flee the fire, but
were apparently overcome by smoke, according to Fire Chief Bill
Carter.
   ``They were all in the bed, and the fire went up some stair steps
and the children were just trapped up there.'' he said. ``They all
had attempted to escape through one route or another. Usually smoke
gets them first.''
   The blaze started downstairs, where the parents of two of the
children were sleeping, Carter said. Samuel and Eleanor Todaro were
able to escape unharmed, he said, but they could not rescue the
children because the fire blocked the only staircase.
   He said firefighters arrived quickly, but were also unable to get
upstairs to save the victims, who were ages 3 through 15.
   Carter said it appeared the fire began in a room with a
fireplace, but the cause was still under investigation.
   Carter identified the victims as Stephen and Stephanie
Baumgartner, the twins; Christopher Baumgartner, 15; Amy Todaro, 12;
and Guy Todaro, 7.
