<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LaRouche 1stLd-Writethru a0447 11-22 0923</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-LaRouche, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0447,900</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 7 grafs new with testimony; picks up 5th graf pvs,
LaRouche also.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Connecticut woman, testifying at the
conspiracy trial of political maverick Lyndon H. LaRouche Jr., said
today a LaRouche fundraiser deceived her by telling her $2,000 in
political contributions were loans.
   As defense lawyers tried to show that prosecution witness
Elizabeth Sexton was a willing supporter of LaRouche, the woman who
loaned nearly $113,000 to a LaRouche-affiliated organization that
was never repaid insisted she was misled by fundraiser Joyce
Rubenstein.
   At the opening of the trial of LaRouche and six associates
Monday, Ms. Sexton said Ms. Rubenstein repeatedly promised her the
loans would be repaid at interest rates of up to 17.5 percent.
   Today, Ms. Rubenstein's lawyer, Ed Williams, showed the
75-year-old witness two $1,000 checks made out to campaign
organizations of the minor-party presidential candidate in May 1985.
   Ms. Sexton said those checks were written at the request of Ms.
Rubenstein, adding, ``It was not explained to me that these were
political contributions. I thought they were loans.''
   Asked by Williams why she did not write the promised interest
rate on the memo section of the checks _ as she did with the nearly
$113,000 in loan money _ Ms. Sexton said she did so, but it was
``whited out.''
   LaRouche is charged along with six associates with mail fraud and
conspiracy to commit mail fraud for allegedly raising more than $30
million in loans with no intent of repaying them.
   LaRouche also is charged with conspiracy to defraud the Internal
Revenue Service by filing no returns since 1979, while having all
personal expenses paid from funds of various corporations he
controls.
   Conviction on all counts could carry a prison term of 65 years
and fines of $3.25 million.
   Defense lawyers told jurors in opening statements Monday that
there was no intent to defraud those lending money to LaRouche
organizations. But they contended repayment became impossible when
LaRouche and associates were forced to divert funds toward resisting
attacks from the government and news media.
   Prosecutors began to carefully lay out their case by calling Ms.
Sexton, a gray-haired, matronly looking woman who said the series of
loans she made in 1985 came from ``money my husband left me, my
working capital.''
   Speaking in a firm voice that occasionally rose in anger as she
recounted the loss of $112,800, Ms. Sexton said she repeatedly told
LaRouche fund-raiser Joyce Rubinstein, a defendant, that ``I could
not afford to live without'' the investment money.
   But Ms. Sexton admitted she willingly loaned the money to Caucus
Distributors Inc. _ described by prosecutors as a LaRouche
organization _ because Ms. Rubinstein said it was needed to publish
a book against drugs.
   ``Nancy Reagan asked everyone to get involved,'' Ms. Sexton said,
adding she thought she was doing just that _ and helping her three
grandchildren, too _ by financing the book project.
   She acknowledged under cross examination the book was published,
in Spanish, for distribution in Latin America. Ms. Sexton said she
thought her money would get the book translated into English.
   As Assistant U.S. Attorney John Markham guided her through the
story, he asked the witness if she considered the loan risky.
   Sitting ramrod straight in the witness chair, Ms. Sexton shot
back, ``Joyce assured me my money was safer than with my bank or any
of my investments.''
   Ms. Sexton related how Ms. Rubinstein kept pressing her to lend
more money, and when ``the barrel ran dry,'' the witness said she
complied with the fund-raiser's request to get a bank loan.
   In his opening statement, Assistant U.S. attorney Kent S.
Robinson told jurors ``we are not here to judge'' the politics of
LaRouche, whose views are often described in published reports as
extreme.
   Robinson said that during the alleged loan scam, lasting from
1983 through 1987, LaRouche imposed quotas on fund-raisers and told
them people who didn't give ``were not morally fit to survive.''
   Robinson said the fund-raisers promised lenders high interest
rates and repayment on a quarterly basis, and sent promissory notes
through the mail.
   Defense attorneys countered that LaRouche and the co-defendants
had no intention of defrauding those who loaned the more than $30
million but only received about $3 million in repayments.
   Odin Anderson, LaRouche's attorney, told jurors tat LaRouche had
ordered that loans made to his organization be fully repaid and told
his staff that it would be ``political suicide'' not to pay back
supporters.
   Anderson admitted his client failed to file income tax returns,
but argued there was no intent to evade the law.
   The attorney said LaRouche had no personal income, and ``had a
good-faith belief'' that he was not obligated to file.
   Another defense attorney, Michael Reilly, blamed the inability to
pay back the loans on attacks on LaRouche by ``the most powerful
forces in the country'' _ including the FBI, Internal Revenue
Service, the news media, state law enforcement organizations and the
Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith.
   LaRouche was indicted in October on 13 counts of mail fraud,
conspiracy to commit mail fraud and conspiracy to defraud the IRS.
Conviction on all counts could carry a prison term of 65 years and
fines of $3.25 million.
   Six of his associates face lesser sentences if convicted of the
mail fraud and conspiracy charges.
   LaRouche's co-defendants are William Wertz, chief fund-raiser;
his chief legal adviser, Edward Spannaus, and four fund-raisers:
Michael Billington, Dennis Small, Paul Greenberg and Ms. Rubinstein.
</TEXT>
