<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Sun-TimesTalks     11-22 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sun-Times Talks,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sun-Times Talks Resume As Union Delays Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiators for the Chicago Sun-Times and its
editorial employees returned to the bargaining table today, with the
union saying that a strike threat is still in force.
   ``We're not that far apart,'' said Daniel J. Lehmann, spokesman
for Local 71 of the Chicago Newspaper Guild, which represents 250
newsroom employees.
   But he said a company offer presented Monday _ calling for no pay
increase in the first year of a new contract, followed by 3 percent
raises the next two years _ was ``not received favorably'' by guild
members who met Monday afternoon.
   Michael Soll, a Sun-Times spokesman, said: ``I really don't know
that that's the final offer. They're at the negotiating table. It's
difficult to know what's going to come out of it.''
   The union had set a strike deadline of 2:30 p.m. Monday, but
froze the deadline as negotiations continued Monday and resumed this
morning.
   Lehmann, the newspaper's religion writer, reiterated that the
guild negotiating committee could call a strike at any time, and
Soll said again that the newspaper would continue to publish
regardless.
   ``There are people in place to step in in the event they're
needed,'' Soll said.
   Before making the new offer Monday, newspaper management had
sought a 3 percent pay cut for 18 months, followed by restoration of
current pay for the balance of a three-year pact. The guild had been
seeking yearly raises of 6 percent to 7 percent.
   The newspaper's pay scale ranges from $625 a week for starting
reporters to $895 for reporters with five years of experience.
   Union members have been working without a contract since June 1.
A strike would be the first by Sun-Times editorial workers in the
newspaper's 40-year history.
   The Sun-Times says it must control costs to remain competitive
with the larger Chicago Tribune.
  
</TEXT>
