<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Carter-Prisoner     11-22 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Carter-Prisoner,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carter Says He'll Press For Release Of Friend In Iranian Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Jimmy Carter says he will not
stop pressing for the release of a friend held in an Iranian prison
despite the revelation that the man is wanted on a 10-year-old
federal indictment.
   Terrence B. Adamson, Carter's lawyer, said the former president
has been trying to help free Erwin David Rabhan for several years
and just recently learned of the indictment.
   ``It will not deter us from our effort to help him,'' Adamson
said Monday.
   Carter confirmed Saturday that he has written to the Ayatollah
Khomeini on behalf of Rabhan, a 61-year-old Savannah native. Carter
has not received a reply, Adamson said.
   Rabhan has been held in Iran since 1981 on charges of spying for
the Central Intelligence Agency.
   Rabhan was indicted on Sept. 21, 1978, in Missouri on six counts
of federal securities violations involving the financing of nursing
homes, said Timothy Wilson, an assistant U.S. attorney in St. Louis.
   ``He has been a fugitive for 10 years,'' Wilson told The Atlanta
Constitution in a story published in today's editions.
   Rabhan has been acquainted with Carter since the 1960s, when he
volunteered his services as a pilot during Carter's second
gubernatorial campaign. He later lived for a short time in a
basement room at the Governor's Mansion.
   Carter, in his statement Saturday, gave no information about
Rabhan except to describe him as a friend.
   Adamson said the federal government has been apprised of Carter's
activity.
   Wilson said Rabhan had been involved in numerous business
ventures, and was living in Iran when the indictment was handed up.
He described Rabhan as ``one of the more bizarre people I've ever
run across.''
</TEXT>
