<DOCNO> AP881122-0079 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-88 1145EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-CubanDetainees     11-22 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cuban Detainees,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Says Lawsuits Must Be Consolidated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. District Judge John H. Pratt ruled today
that a lawsuit filed here to block the deportation of 13 Mariel
boatlift detainees to Cuba must be consolidated with a similar one
brought earlier in Alabama.
   Pratt signed an order to transfer the case to Birmingham after
hearing arguments and rejecting a request for a temporary
restraining order to block the Justice Department from returning the
13 detainees, now in a penitentiary in Talladega, Ala., to Cuba.
   ``I'm satisfied that this case should be transferred to
Alabama,'' Pratt said from the bench. ``There is a similar but not
identical case in the Alabama jurisdiction. We have to have these
cases decided by a single judge in a single jurisdiction.''
   Laurence Eisenstein, representing the 13 detainees, had argued
that the case in Birmingham was based on different issues than the
lawsuit he filed in the District of Columbia.
   Eisenstein said the Birmingham case, involving 15 individual
detainees, involved immigration issues while his class-action suit
filed here dealt with the constitutionality of the Justice
Department's administrative procedures on deportation, such as a
denial of judicial review of such an action.
   Pratt replied, ``I can tell you that if these two cases were
filed in this court, the judge in the first case would have received
the second one under consolidation.''
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Edith Marshall, representing the
Immigration and Naturalization Service, argued that the cases had to
be consolidated because many issues, such as harm to the public
interest, harm to the United States and U.S.-Cuban relations, were
the same.
   ``It is judicial inefficiecy for two courts to hear these
cases,'' she said.
   The Justice Department announced last week that panels
established in the wake of last year's prison riots by the boatlift
detainees had reviewed their first 28 cases and planned to send at
least 15 of the prisoners back to Cuba ``in the near future.''
   A suit on behalf of the 15 was filed in Birmingham in an attempt
to block the deportations. Two of the 15 declined to join in the
class-action suit filed here.
   The 15 the department said should be repatriated have convictions
ranging from petty larceny to second-degree murder. Most of them
have more than one conviction.
   The three-member Justice Department panels will undertake further
consideration of the remaining 13 detainees in the initial review
group to determine whether they should be returned to Cuba or be
released.
   The detainees are among 125,000 people who came to the United
States in 1980 in a boatlift from Mariel, Cuba. The vast majority of
them have been law-abiding U.S. residents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
