<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Onassis 1stLd-Writethru a0461 11-22 0606</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Onassis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0461,0630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Transfer Of Body Held Up Pending Determination Of Exact Cause Of
Death</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout with Onassis' mother dying of pulmonary
edema, funeral arrangements, other details. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The transfer of the body of
heiress Christina Onassis to a Greek island for burial has been held
up by judicial authorities pending the determination of the exact
cause of death.
   A preliminary coroner's report said Monday the cause of death was
acute pulmonary edema, or the accumulation of fluid in her lungs.
   Ms. Onassis, 37, died Saturday at the country home of her
friends, Albert and Marina Dodero. A doctor at Clinica del Sol
hospital in Buenos Aires, where the body was first taken, said the
cause of death was a heart attack.
   Heart attacks can cause an accumulation of fluid in the lungs,
but the coroner's report did not say what caused the build-up.
   Ms. Onassis' mother, Athena, died in 1974 at the age of 45 and
medical reports said at the time that she also had died from a
pulmonary edema.
   Forensic experts were analyzing Ms. Onassis' body tissue and
other evidence to determine whether drugs figured in her death.
   Juan Carlos Cardinali, one of three judges handling the case, was
quoted by the private news agency Noticias Argentinas as saying the
investigation was focusing on the possible overdose of barbiturates.
   Family members and friends ruled out suicide.
   They said Ms. Onassis, heiress to the fortune of shipping tycoon
Aristotle Onassis, appeared happy in her final days, and was
considering the purchase of an apartment in Buenos Aires.
   Unconfirmed local news reports said Ms. Onassis planned to marry
Jorge Tchomlekdjoglou, the brother of Marina Dodero. Ms. Onassis'
first four marriages ended in divorce.
   Family members declined to comment. ``I know nothing about that
(wedding),'' said Alberto Dodero, Marina's father-in-law.
   The full coroner's report was expected this week. It was unclear
whether the report would be publicly disclosed.
   A determination that Ms. Onassis died of natural causes would
allow the transfer of her body to the family-owned island of
Skorpios off Greece for burial beside her father and brother,
Alexander, who died in a 1973 plane crash.
   Her fourth husband, French industrialist Thierry Roussel, arrived
from Geneva on Monday to help resolve legal proceedings.
   Roussel is the father of Ms. Onassis' only child, 3-year-old
Athena, who will inherit her entire fortune, estimated at $1 billion.
   In Athens, Greece, a source close to the Onassis family said Ms.
Onassis will be buried on Saturday if Argentine authorities releases
her body within the next 48 hours.
   The source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said Ms.
Onassis' body will be flown to Athens for public funeral service
tentatively scheduled for Friday. Roussel is expected to accompany
the body, the source said.
   The source said Ms. Onassis' daughter Athena would probably not
be flown from Switzerland for the funeral.
   The public will be able to pay respects to Ms. Onassis in a Greek
Orthodox church in the Athens suburb of Nea Smirni. On Saturday, the
body is to be flown to northwest Greece, where it will be placed
aboard a launch for the short trip to Skorpios, said the source.
   The burial service on Skorpios ``will be strictly private, with
only relatives and very close friends in attendance,'' said Ioannis
Georgakis, a business advisor to the Onassis family.
   Ms. Onassis will be buried next to her father and brother in a
mausoleum adjoining a tiny chapel on a hill in the center of the
island.
   Aristotle Onassis died in Paris in 1975.
</TEXT>
