<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BoardinghouseSlayings 1stLd-Writethru a0503 11-22 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Boardinghouse Slayings, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0503,0573</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Victim Identified, But Cause of Deaths Still Unknown</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 4th graf pvs, `Puente, 59, ...', to
UPDATE with detail from court documents on results of search of
house. Picks up 5th graf, `Simmons said...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUG WILLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the seven bodies found buried
outside a boardinghouse was identified as that of an alcoholic who
spent most of his life on the streets, but authorities don't know
how he or the others died.
   The body of Benjamin Fink, 60, a former resident of Dorothea
Puente's Victorian boardinghouse in downtown Sacramento, was
identified Monday through fingerprints, said Sacramento County
Coroner Charles Simmons.
   No further information was released on Fink. His brother, Robert,
told reporters last week that Fink had been a chronic alcoholic
since age 17 who spent most of his life on the streets in
Sacramento, and had moved into the Puente boardinghouse earlier this
year.
   Puente, 59, remained in jail without bail on a murder charge.
Authorities said they expected to file further charges soon.
   In sworn statements filed Monday in Sacramento Municipal Court,
police said that searches of the boardinghouse have turned up carpet
stained with blood and a handwritten book that may be Puente's diary.
   During two searches of the two-story, wood-frame house, police
seized papers, photographs and books, including a paperback titled
``The Smell of Evil,'' according to the court documents. Among the
seized papers are some ``pertaining to funeral plots.''
   Police Detective Les Murphy said last week in an affidavit to
support a warrant to search the house for a second time that a
former boardinghouse tenant told investigators Puente kept a
personal biography inside the house. Court documents don't say who
owns the handwritten book seized by police.
   The statements filed Monday to show what was found as a result of
the searches, the first Nov. 15 and the second over last weekend.
   Murphy said blood and body fluids found on carpeting during the
first search appear ``to be similar to carpeting recovered from one
of the graves of the bodies found in the yard.''
   Simmons said his office had completed autopsies on six of the
seven victims and would finish the seventh autopsy today. He said a
final report including toxicology studies would not be completed
until sometime next week.
   Despite the extreme decomposition of most of the bodies, good
fingerprints were obtained from at least three and there are still
``better than 50-50 chances'' of determining the cause of death, the
coroner said.
   The sixth victim, whose autopsy was completed Monday, was a woman
more than 50 years old whose body was fully dressed and wrapped in a
sheet, Simmons said. He said she had been buried for ``several
months, at least.''
   With the seventh autopsy pending, that brings the victim total to
three men and three women.
   Simmons said authorities working from a list of about 25 missing
people known to have lived in Puente's home at one time or another
have found six or seven people, and removed them from the list.
   Detectives say they believe Puente killed elderly boarders and
hid their bodies in order to collect their Social Security checks.
   In a television interview after her arrest Wednesday, she said
she didn't kill anyone, but admitted ``the checks I cashed, yes.''
</TEXT>
