<2ND_LINE>PM-EPA-Thomas,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EPA Chief Leaving; Plans Uncertain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Environmental Protection Administration chief
Lee Thomas said today he will leave the agency on Jan. 20 when the
new president takes office.
   Thomas, administrator since January 1985, did not say in his
announcement what his plans were. In a recent interview, however, he
said he did not know what he would do when he leaves.
   There had been speculation that President-elect George Bush would
ask Thomas to stay, but Thomas' associates have been discouraging
such talk.
   Thomas was associate director of the Federal Emergency Management
Agency when he was assigned to coordinate the federal government's
1982 buyout of homes at Times Beach, Mo., a town contaminated by
dioxin.
   His performance won him a transfer to EPA to bolster the sagging
Superfund toxic waste cleanup program the next year. Shortly after
his arrival, he was tapped to succeed Rita Lavelle as assistant
administrator overseeing Superfund when she resigned amid
accusations of lying to Congress. She later served a prison term.
   William Ruckelshaus recommended Thomas as his successor when he
left the top job in the agency in December 1984.
</TEXT>
