<1ST_LINE>r a PM-InsuranceExemptions     11-22 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Insurance Exemptions,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>California Insurers Seek Exemptions From Proposition 103</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eleven insurance companies, including five of
California's 10 biggest auto insurers, have requested exemptions
from rate cuts mandated by Proposition 103, state officials reported.
   Department of Insurance officials identified the 11 companies,
but declined to release copies of the exemption requests.
   Proposition 103 mandates that such copies be made public, but
Reid McClaran, staff attorney for the State Department of Insurance,
said Monday that the law is not in effect because it has been stayed
by the state Supreme Court pending a review.
   Insurers are eligible for an exemption from Proposition 103's
rate rollbacks if they can prove the reductions will force them out
of business. In addition to seeking exemptions, insurers are trying
to get the entire law thrown out.
   The 11 companies filing for exemptions include Farmers Insurance
Group Co., Northern California Automobile Club (California State
Auto Association), Automobile Club of Southern California
(Interinsurance Exchange), 20th Century and Mercury Insurance, which
are five of the state's 10 biggest auto insurers.
   The other six companies are Williamsburg National Insurance Co.,
National Automobile and Casualty Insurance Co., California Casualty
Group, Contractors' Surety Co., Surety Co. of the Pacific and
Wawanesa Mutual Insurance.
   The decision to withhold information on the filings was blasted
by Proposition 103 campaign manager Bill Zimmerman.
   ``Insurers who have gouged the public for so many years refuse to
accept the will of the people and want to function as if the old
rules still apply, which is not the case,'' he said.
   State Sen. Alan Robbins, chairman of the Senate Insurance
Committee, said he would subpoena Insurance Commissioner Roxani
Gillespie for the records if she refuses to release them.
   Meanwhile, the Los Angeles Times reported today that Ms.
Gillespie plans to add 300 employees to her 515-member staff and
increase her office's annual budget by $18 million to enforce
Proposition 103 if the insurance initiative is upheld in court. The
initiative allows the department to charge insurers for added
enforcement costs.
</TEXT>
