<1ST_LINE>u a PM-GOPGovernors 1stLd-Writethru a0445 11-22 0825</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-GOP Governors, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0445,800</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: New with Bush speech, editing throughout</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KENDAL WEAVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>POINT CLEAR, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect George Bush said today
that as soon as he becomes president he will name administration
officials to negotiate solutions to the budget deficit and will talk
to members of Congress himself on the problem.
   ``On the first day of my presidency, I will name negotiators to
represent the executive branch in deficit talks with the Congress.
I, too, will be `hands-on' in talking directly with members of
Congress, on both sides of the aisle,'' he told Republican governors.
   He reiterated, however, that the vote in the presidential
election endorsed his stand that ``the solution to the federal
budget deficit is not taxes.''
   The president-elect spoke to the National Republican Governors
Conference in a crowded ballroom of the Grand Hotel resort on the
Alabama coast. The GOP governors earlier had stressed that close
ties already have been formed between the new White House team and
Republican statehouses.
   Bush said the 1990s can be the ``the decade of cooperation'',
with the party offering compassion along with leadership. ``This is
a time for bringing people together,'' he said.
   ``Simply put, I mean to continue what Ronald Reagan and I began
in 1980 _ to stop the flow of power to Washington and return it
where it belongs, to the states. I mean to continue this tradition
because it has worked and because it is consistent with our party's
philosophy,'' Bush said.
   ``I believe all of us share the same goal: a land of limited
government and unlimited opportunity,'' he said.
   Bush called on the GOP governors to work with the administration
``to provide compassionate and responsible leadership. As
Republicans, let's work together, and I mean this, to be the party
of all the people. Our ideas are right.''
   He also touched on themes expressed earlier in the four-day GOP
governors conference by members of the new White House team,
including the goal of expanding the Republican Party at all levels
of government.
   ``My point is that we are on our way to becoming the majority
party in America _ if we don't lose sight of what is driving our
success,'' he said.
   At the start of his speech, he mentioned the conference's host
governor, Alabama's Guy Hunt, who in 1986 became the first
Republican to win the state's governor's office this century.
   Bush has tapped one GOP chief executive, New Hampshire's John
Sununu, as his chief of staff. And on Monday he said Attorney
General Dick Thornburgh, the former Pennsylvania governor who once
was chairman of the GOP conference, will hold the top Justice
Department job in the new administration.
   Sununu and Thornburgh both spoke to the conference Monday,
stressing close relations with the states on a range of issues
including fighting drugs. Bush campaign manager Lee Atwater also
promised a full-scale battle on behalf of GOP candidates at all
levels in his new job as chairman of the Republican National
Committee.
   Atwater told governors that in the last three presidential races
the party has won enough key states and geographic territory that it
``could and should win the presidency right on through the next
century.''
   Sununu said Bush has begun forming his economic team with his
initial Cabinet selections and will be developing a defense team,
probably after a break for the Thanksgiving holiday.
   Atwater, accused by Democratic critics of lowering the level of
the presidential campaign and giving it an element of racial
divisiveness, said the party has ``an opportunity in the black
community,'' which has voted heavily Democratic. In the conference
hall as he spoke Monday there were only a couple of blacks in the
crowd of perhaps 400.
   ``Black outreach is a top priority,'' Atwater said, along with
``Hispanic outreach.''
   As for his own role, Atwater said, ``I'm not going to try to be a
national celebrity. I'm not going to try to be a statesman. That
ain't me.''
   Thornburgh said his office will have a ``full agenda'' in the
Bush administration, which has labeled the drug trade as ``publice
enemy No. 1.'' He said the statehouses are in the ``front line'' of
the fight and that his office will be working with state drug
directors as well as law enforcement personnel.
   Thornburgh also said there must be major change on the demand
side of the drug problem to begin resolving it. He said programs in
the nation's schools should ``make sense'' to young people about
living a drug-free life.
   Education Secretary Lauro Cavazos, tapped by Bush to hold his
post in the new Cabinet, spoke to the conference in a session on
education. He stressed the importance of addressing the dropout
problem in America's schools.
   Taking part in the conference sessions Monday were 20 of the
nation's 23 Republican governors, along with two governors-elect.
The GOP suffered a net loss of one statehouse in the November
election.
</TEXT>
