<1ST_LINE>u a PM-StormKeith 2ndLd-Writethru a0519 11-22 0591</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Storm Keith, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0519,0603</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Florida Prepares For Weakened, But Still Potent, Storm Keith</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with storm slightly weaker,
preparations in Florida, other detail from 11 a.m. advisory. Picks
up 6th graf pvs, `If Keith's...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A slightly weakened Tropical Storm Keith churned
over the Gulf of Mexico toward an expected Florida landfall after
drenching a stretch from Mexico to the Florida Keys and forcing the
evacuation of 2,500 people in Cuba.
   Forecasters said the storm still packed winds near 65 mph, and
emergency planning officials urged people along Florida's Gulf Coast
to batten down and brace for heavy rains and winds today.
   However, forecasters at the National Hurricane Center said a cold
front from the north was mingling with Storm Keith in the Gulf of
Mexico, keeping it from strengthening to hurricane status.
   ``It's extremely unlikely it would strengthen,'' said forecaster
Colin McAdie. ``It will lose strength as it crosses land.''
   Earlier today, Keith's winds were put at 65 mph, but the 11 a.m.
EST advisory from the hurricane center said the winds had slightly
eased, to near 65 mph. Winds would have had to go up to 74 mph for
the storm to be reclassified as a hurricane.
   Tropical storm warnings were extended today from Cape Sable to
Cedar Key on the Gulf Coast and hurricane forecasters issued a
tropical storm watch from Jupiter Inlet to Savannah, Ga., on the
Atlantic Coast. Rainfall of up to 5 inches was forecast.
   ``The outer fringes of the storm are already over them,'' McAdie
said. ``The rainfalls will increase throughout the day, with the
heaviest rains tonight.'
   ``We're advising the public to sit and ride it out,'' said
Stephanie Riley, emergency planner for Sarasota. She said the area
was experiencing strong wind gusts late this morning, and shelters
were being prepared but not immediately opened.
   ``We're going on what the people need, if they feel uncomfortable
where they are or if they get high water or flooding,'' she said.
   Planners advised residents to take stock of emergency supplies of
canned foods, water and candles.
   ``Basically, we're saying there's no life-threatening
situation,'' said David Saniter, emergency coordinator in Fort
Myers, farther south along the Gulf Coast. ``We're going to get some
rains _ much-needed rains _ and some high winds.'' He advised
residents to prepare their houses for a strong storm.
   At 11 a.m. EST today, the storm was centered near latitude 25.3
north and longitude 85.7 west, about 250 miles west-southwest of
Fort Myers. It was traveling northeast at 12 mph and was expected to
make landfall early Wednesday.
   If Keith's winds did reach more than 74 mph, it would be the
sixth hurricane of the six-month Atlantic season, which ends Nov. 30.
   Monday's rains didn't do major damage to Yucatan Peninsula resort
of Cancun, Mexico, which was among the areas hardest hit in
September by Hurricane Gilbert.
   On Cuba, civil defense authorities reported at least 2,500 people
were evacuated from low-lying areas in the island's westernmost
province of Pinar del Rio.
   While still a depression, Keith passed south of Jamaica late
Friday and early Saturday, pouring almost 4 inches of rain on
Kingston in 24 hours. It also dumped rain on Honduras before heading
north into the gulf.
   Tropical depressions are upgraded to tropical storms when their
sustained winds reach 39 mph. Keith reached tropical storm status
Sunday.
   Keith is the season's 11th named storm. Since 1980, there have
been four November hurricanes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
