<1ST_LINE>u w PM-DangerousToys 1stLd-Writethru a0440 11-22 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dangerous Toys, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0440,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Safety Commission Defends Efforts to Rid Market of Dangerous Toys</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Top 15 grafs new with CPSC comment; Picks up 9th graf pvs,
Look for.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Consumer Product Safety Commission today
defended its efforts to rid the market of toys that can be dangerous
to children, one day after a consumer group accused the commission
of ``pitiful ineptitude.''
   ``I clearly don't agree with their allegations. We spend 12
months out of every year trying to address toy safety,'' said Anne
Graham, commissioner of the safety commission.
   ``On the other hand, I'm appreciative of the ADA for bringing the
toys that they're concerned about to our attention. Our compliance
unit will be looking at them immediately and determining if they're
safe or not. If they're not, we'll take measures to get them off the
market,'' she said.
   The Consumer Affairs Committee of the Americans for Democratic
Action issued its 17th annual report on Monday and criticized the
commission, the federal agency charged with overseeing consumer
goods.
   A ``major reason for the abundance of dangerous toys'' is ``the
pitiful ineptitude'' of the CPSC, the ADA report said.
   At today's news conference, the commission displayed some of the
toys it had recalled in 1988. It also emphasized that parents should
heed the cautionary labels on some products, including warnings on
balloons.
   The commission said that in the 15 years since the agency's
inception, 115 deaths have been associated with balloons. Some
children have suffocated when they picked up broken balloons,
inhaled the pieces and choked on them.
   Toys caused 131,000 injuries last year, including 105,000 to
children under 15, according to the safety commission.
   Two types of toys to avoid, the ADA said, are baby walkers and
crib gyms. The walkers can tip over or fall down stairs, while the
gyms are responsible for a dozen deaths and 662 other injuries in
the past five years, the report said.
   Accidents involving baby walkers occur when steps or stairways
are not blocked or doors are not closed, John Preston, a mechanical
engineer with the commission, told reporters at the agency's annual
holiday safety news conference. He encouraged close parental
supervision.
   ``As far as baby walkers are concerned, there aren't any specific
defects,'' Ms. Graham said.
   Commission spokeswoman Elaine Tyrrell demonstrated how a crib gym
could become dangerous for a child who is able to stand, usually
about the age of six months.
   A child could get entangled in the toy which stretches across a
crib and strangulation deaths have occured. She urged parents to
remove the toy once a child becomes more active.
   The commission said parents shopping for children's presents this
holiday season ``must consider the play environment as well as
skills and abilities of the child when toy purchases are made.''
   The ADA report recommended some basic safety guidelines for
Christmas-shopping parents:
   _Look for sharp edges, small parts, projectiles and potential
danger if the toy breaks. Toys with fabric in them should say the
material is flame retardant or flame resistant. Painted toys should
be non-toxic.
   _Read the directions. Avoid toys with instructions that are too
complicated.
   _Consider the child's age. Good toys should not require constant
supervision to ensure safety or correct use. Also, watch for
inadequate or misleading age labels.
</TEXT>
