<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CrockerProfile     11-22 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crocker Profile,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Angola Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Architect of Angola-Namibia Pact Succeeds After 8-Year Quest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chester A. Crocker, a principal architect of
the agreement to remove foreign forces from Southwestern Africa, has
pursued that objective virtually from the day he joined the Reagan
administration almost eight years ago.
   His perseverence began to pay off this past spring when he
persuaded the governments of South Africa, Cuba and Angola to begin
a negotiating process under his mediation.
   Now, with South African acceptance of a plan approved last Friday
by the governments of Angola and Cuba, Crocker's patience has paid
off.
   The plan basically calls for Namibian independence from 73 years
of South African colonial rule and the phased withdrawal over 27
months of the more than 50,000 Cuban troops from Angola, Namibia's
northern neighbor.
   Crocker has long believed that achievement of these two
objectives could usher in a period of stability and harmony in a
region that has known neither for years.
   Another Crocker aim has been to free the area from superpower
competition, but that goal apparently will elude him. The agreement
does not resolve the Angolan civil war, in which the United States
and the Soviet Union have been arming opposite sides.
   It was no small achievement for an American diplomat to be
accepted as mediator by three countries with which the United States
has relations ranging from poor to non-existent.
   U.S. ties with South Africa have been strained for years and the
United States has no diplomatic relations with Angola. Washington
and Havana have only small diplomatic missions in each other's
capital and disagree on almost everything.
   But Crocker felt all along that his approach offered something to
each participant in the area's protracted struggles and gently
prodded them toward agreement.
   For South Africa, Namibian independence will mean an end to a
long and costly colonial rule by Pretoria.
   For Angola, the withdrawal of South African forces from Namibia
means an end to South African support for anti-communist rebels in
Angola.
   As for Cuba, President Fidel Castro can claim a major role in
extricating Namibia, Africa's last colony, from South African rule.
It also will bring an end, by early 1991, to a foreign adventure
that has claimed thousands of Cuban casualties since Cuban troops
first began arriving in Angola in 1975.
   Crocker, who turned 47 in October, joined the State Department
after administration talent scouts were impressed by an article he
wrote on South Africa policy in Foreign Affairs magazine in 1980.
   He had spent the previous eight years associated with Georgetown
University, the last five of which he served as director of African
studies at the university's Center for Strategic and International
Studies.
   Since then, Crocker has acquired a reputation for, among other
things, durability. While the four other regional bureaus at the
State Department _ Latin America, the Middle East, Europe and Asia _
each have had three assistant secretaries during Reagan's tenure,
Crocker has been the only head of the Africa bureau in that period.
   His scholarly demeanor reflects his long years of academic
pursuits, which include a doctorate from Johns Hopkins University.
At the State Department, he was recognized early on by his
colleagues as one of the few bona fide intellectuals holding high
government office.
   Crocker is married to a Rhodesia native and has three daughters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
