<HEAD>Mayor Koch Testifies Against Old Friend, Bess Myerson</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A subdued, unsmiling Mayor Edward I. Koch barely
glanced at former Miss America Bess Myerson today as he began
testifying for the prosecution at the corruption trial of his
one-time friend and political ally.
   But Miss Myerson _ the city's former cultural affairs
commissioner, now charged in an alleged divorce-fixing scheme _
stared intently at Koch.
   Under questioning by Assistant U.S. Attorney David Lawrence, Koch
said he ``had and has a high regard'' for Miss Myerson, whom he
described as ``very important in the (mayoral) race I won in 1977.''
   Koch said nothing to reporters when he arrived in his limousine
at the federal courthouse shortly after 10:30 a.m. He was
accompanied by his counsel, Hank White, and by mayoral advisor Dan
Wolf.
   He appointed the Myerson as city cultural affairs commissioner in
1983.
   Miss Myerson, 64, is accused of giving a $19,000-a-year city job
to the daughter of the judge who was hearing the divorce of Miss
Myerson's lover, Carl ``Andy'' Capasso. Prosecutors argue that in
return, the judge lowered Capasso's alimony payments to his
estranged wife.
   The federal court trial of Miss Myerson; Capasso, 43; and former
state Supreme Court Justice Hortense Gabel, 75, entered its eighth
week today.
   The mayor's testimony was expected to center on a letter he
received from Miss Myerson on Oct. 19, 1983, explaining the hiring
of Mrs. Gabel's daughter, Sukhreet.
   In the letter, written the day after a newspaper report about
Sukhreet Gabel's hiring, Miss Myerson contended that nothing
improper was done and that most of the decisions in the Capasso
divorce case were already made when Miss Gabel was hired.
