<HEAD>Ten Killed in Passenger Train Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A passenger train heading from Moscow to a city in
Central Asia caught fire, killing 10 of the 48 people on board,
media reported.
   The train, heading for Kustanay, about 1,000 miles east of Moscow
in Kazakhstan, pulled into the Zayatskaya station just after
midnight Nov. 19 with smoke pouring from the fifth car.
   ``In the ensuing panic, the awakened people rushed to the exit.
Out of 48 passengers in the car three died from carbon monoxide
poisoning and seven perished in the flames,'' Tass said.
   Station and train staff tried to put out the fire, but fire
engines arrived late and the fire spread, the official news agency
said.
   Reports said the fire started in the compartment of the car's
conductor, but did not say what caused it.
   A government commission headed by Kazakhstan's premier, Kadyr
Baikenov, was appointed to look into the fire.
