<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Cocaine Seizure,0166</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Traffic Arrest Leads to Cocaine Seizure in Louisville</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police who made a routine traffic arrest
later found cocaine worth $1.2 million in the car, in one of the
largest narcotics seizures in Kentucky history.
   Authorities said the 10 kilograms, about 22 pounds, were found
Monday in a secret compartment under the car's trunk.
   ``There will be a lot of people upset for Thanksgiving,'' joked
Louisville police officer Willie Ball, whose dog sniffed out the
drugs.
   Investigators were still searching today for the driver,
identified as Glenn Anthony Hughes, 32, of Louisville.
   Hughes failed to appear at his arraignment Monday on speeding and
reckless driving charges. A warrant has been issued for his arrest
charging him with trafficking cocaine, said Sgt. Carl Yates, a
police department spokesman.
   Hughes was stopped about 1 a.m. Monday, but he had no prior
warrants and was released on a $90 bond before police found the
drugs four hours later.
</TEXT>
