<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-88 1319EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MilitaryStrength     11-22 0205</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Military Strength,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Personnel Rolls Down by 8,000 in October</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The active-duty strength of the nation's armed
forces dropped by almost 8,000 last month as a major reduction in
the size of the U.S. military continued.
   The new strength total as of Oct. 31 was almost 42,000 fewer than
a year ago.
   All told, the Army, Navy, Marine Corps and Air Force reported
2,130,216 men and women on active duty as of Oct. 31. That compares
with 2,138,213 on Sept. 30 and 2,172,184 on Oct. 31, 1987.
   The reduction was ordered nine months ago for budgetary reasons.
Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci has set a combined strength goal
of 2,138,000 for the next year.
   Most of the cuts were made through changes to recruiting goals,
tighter re-enlistment standards and early-discharge incentives.
   Three of the four services reported declines in strength during
October while the Air Force reported a tiny increase.
   As of Oct. 31, the Air Force reported active-duty strength of
576,794, up 348 from Sept. 30.
   The Army said it had 769,369 men and women on active duty, down
2,478 over the month. Marine Corps strength totaled 196,861, down
489, while Navy personnel rolls declined by 5,378 to 587,192.
</TEXT>
