<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Thailand-China     11-22 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Thailand-China,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thai Army Chief to China to Buy Arms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thailand's army chief left Tuesday for
China for talks expected to focus on buying more arms and the
possibility of stockpiling Chinese-supplied arms in Thailand,
military sources said.
   Gen. Chavalit Yongchaiyudh was accompanied by navy
Commander-in-Chief Adm. Prapas Krisnachan for the visit during which
Thailand and China are expected to sign a major arms deal involving
sales of 30 Chinese-built tanks, 800 armored personnel carriers and
spare parts, the sources said.
   Also up for discussion is the possibility of setting up a war
reserve stockpile from which Thailand could draw Chinese-supplied
weaponry in event of a threat to its national security. A similar
arrangement has been set up with the United States.
   The Thai military has said arms purchases from China are
necessary to bolster Thailand's defense capabilities against
Vietnamese troops across the Thai-Cambodian border. The Vietnamese,
who invaded Cambodia in late 1978, are regarded as Thailand's main
external security threat.
   Although Thailand buys most of its weaponry from the United
States, it has recently obtained tanks, armored personnel carriers
and anti-aircraft guns from Beijing.
   In July, the navy bought four Chinese-made frigates and is
considering buying small submarines for operations in the shallow
Gulf of Thailand, the Thai newspaper The Nation reported Sunday.
   A commentary in Vietnam's official Communist Party newspaper Nhan
Dan on Nov. 20 attacked military cooperation between China and
Thailand and the support of the two countries for Cambodian
resistance groups fighting the Vietnamese in Cambodia.
   China is the main supplier of weapons to the three-party
resistance forces that include the communist Khmer Rouge.
   Thai Foreign Ministry spokesman Saroj Chavanaviraj called the
statements ``interference'' in Thailand's affairs, adding: ``To buy
(Chinese weapons) or not is a Thai military decision.''
</TEXT>
