<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY44, LA3</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mother Teresa, a perennial favorite in Good
Housekeeping magazine's annual poll of the world's most admired
women, held her No. 1 spot in its 1988 survey, but Nancy Reagan was
edged out of her second position.
   Talk show host Oprah Winfrey moved up two notches from last
year's survey to claim the No. 2 spot and drop Mrs. Reagan down to
third in the magazine's 20th annual poll, the magazine said Tuesday.
Two years ago, the first lady topped the list.
   Margaret Thatcher, Pat Nixon, Betty Ford, Jeane Kirkpatrick,
Katharine Hepburn, Corazon Aquino and Phyllis Schlafly round out the
top 10 list, which will appear in Good Housekeeping's January issue.
   The eighth annual most admired men poll was topped by the same
face that was No. 1 in the previous seven surveys: President Reagan.
   Preacher Billy Graham stayed at No. 2.
   The other most admired men, according to the survey were: Bob
Hope, Pope John Paul II, Oliver North, Norman Vincent Peale, George
Bush, Bill Cosby, Tom Selleck and Lech Walesa.
   Magazine readers received their ballots in the September issue,
and some 13,700 were returned for each of the polls, the magazine
said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Cybill Shepherd decided she wanted
to buy a townhouse overlooking the Mississippi River, but the
co-op's board of directors turned down the Memphis native.
   ``I tell you, I was so hurt. I couldn't believe this could
happen, particularly in my hometown,'' Ms. Shepherd said. ``You tell
yourself these things don't matter, but it made me feel really bad.''
   Ms. Shepherd said she got word of the board's action last week
through Henry Turley Jr., who developed the townhouses and lives in
the co-op.
   Board members apparently were concerned that Ms. Shepherd did not
plan to spend much time in Memphis, and they worried about who she
might allow to use the home she proposed to purchase.
   But Ms. Shepherd took the refusal personally, as an insult to her
character.
   ``I think anywhere else in the world I could understand someone
not knowing me or knowing the kind of person I am,'' she said. ``I'm
a very upstanding person.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Moonwalker,'' a 94-minute video celebration
of the weird and wonderful world of Michael Jackson, is being
released early next year.
   The video will be an amalgam of Jackson's musical performances,
his reflections on media pressures and a narrative film in which he
transforms himself into a robot and then a spaceship to battle a
drug pusher named Mr. Big, said CBS Music Video Enterprises.
   The release of the video on Jan. 10 comes at the end of Jackson's
15-month world tour, which was seen by 4 million fans in 15
countries.
   Songs on the video include Jackson's ``Man in the Mirror,'' his
version of the Beatles' hit ``Come Together,'' and ``The Moon is
Walking,'' a song written and performed by the South African vocal
group Ladysmith Black Mombazo.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hollywood's legendary cowboy Gene Autry
whooped it up with a host of celebrities at a party celebrating the
film star's Western Heritage Museum.
   Several hundred guests packed the $54 million, three-story Gene
Autry Western Heritage Museum built on a 13-acre site in Griffith
Park to celebrate its formal dedication.
   Mayor Tom Bradley joined veteran Western film stars Roy Rogers,
Dale Evans and longtime Autry sidekick Pat Buttram at the party
honoring Autry and the realization of his dream to build the cowboy
museum.
   Also attending Monday night were former President Gerald Ford and
actor Charlton Heston.
   The facility houses a saddle owned by ``Wild Bill'' Cody, a rifle
owned by former president Teddy Roosevelt, Wyatt Earp's revolver and
a 225-seat theater.
   Bradley and Autry were scheduled to open the museum Tuesday by
cutting a ceremonial lariat with a Bowie knife.
