<DOCNO> AP881122-0112 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-88 1416EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Gorbachev     11-22 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Gorbachev,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets OK Single Meeting Between Gorbachev And Reagan and Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Kremlin has agreed to a single luncheon
meeting Dec. 7 between Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev and
President Reagan and President-elect George Bush in New York, but
the precise location remains uncertain, a U.S. official said Tuesday.
   Two sites are under consideration, the Metropolitan Museum of Art
and Governors Island in New York Harbor. Reagan and French President
Francois Mitterrand held a discussion of East-West relations on the
island during the celebration in July 1986 of the 100th anniversary
of the Statue of Liberty.
   Governors Island offers some security advantages. American,
Cuban, South African and Angolan diplomats met there last spring
outside the glare of publicity to negotiate over the future of
Angola and Namibia.
   ``It's a tossup right now,'' said the U.S. official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity. Except for the location, the two sides have
agreed on logistics, he said.
   Gorbachev will meet with the retiring and incoming U.S presidents
after addressing the U.N. General Assembly.
   Reagan and Bush are projecting the meeting as not on the level of
a summit. They are expected to seek confirmation from the Soviet
president that in conducting superpower relations the leaders of the
two countries will continue to stress arms control, human rights and
settling regional disputes.
   Gorbachev is expected to promote the idea of a human rights
conference in Moscow, while the U.S. side is looking for
reaffirmation of Soviet intentions to remove all remaining troops
from Afghanistan by Feb. 15.
   The Soviet leader will remain in New York after the meeting and
do some sightseeing as well as see a group of American intellectuals
at the Soviet U.N. mission, the official said.
   In contrast to the ornate Metropolitan Museum and its art
treasures, Governors Island is a modest Coast Guard base that was
built up with dredge and rock excavated from New York subway
construction.
   It has been a sheep farm, a quarantine station, a game preserve
and the site of a race track. Initially, it was set aside for the
English king's governors in 1698 and later for the governors of the
American colonies. It was converted into a military fortification in
the War of 1812 and remained under the jurisdiction of the U.S. Army
until 1966.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881122-0113 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-88 1417EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TrainAccident     11-22 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Train Accident,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ten Injured When Train Hits Log Truck</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRENADA, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Amtrak train carrying 138 people hit a
log truck at a highway crossing Tuesday, injuring 10 people and
slicing the truck in half, authorities said.
   ``The train did not derail,'' Amtrak spokeswoman Debbie Hare
said. ``We terminated the trip at the site of the crash and
chartered buses for the remaining passengers.''
   The truck was headed into the Louisiana Pacific paper mill when
the accident occurred at the U.S. 51 crossing about three miles
south of Grenada, a central Mississippi town of 20,000 people, said
Grenada County sheriff's deputy James Webb.
   The truck driver, identified as Clayton J. Jenkins, 43, of
Noxapater, ``failed to yield from what we can tell,'' Webb said.
There are no lights at the crossing, he said.
   ``The train cut the truck in half, and that's probably what saved
his (Jenkins) life,'' Webb said. Jenkins was among the injured,
however.
   Hare said the train was headed from Memphis, Tenn., through
Jackson to New Orleans.
   Grenada Lake Medical Center spokeswoman Cathy Smith said seven of
the injured were admitted. A 6-year-old girl was transferred to the
Mississippi Delta Medical Center Burn Center in Greenville; and the
other two people were released, she said. None of the injuries was
described as critical.
   Smith said the girl, whose family did not want her name released,
reportedly suffered second- and third-degree burns when coffee
spilled on her. A spokeswoman at the Greenville burn center said the
girl was in stable condition.
   Injured were eight passengers, a train crew member and the truck
driver, Hare said.
</TEXT>
