<1ST_LINE>u a PM-US-Canada     11-22 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Canada,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Congratulates Mulroney</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Canada-Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan phoned Canadian
Prime Minister Brian Mulroney today to congratulate Mulroney on his
party's victory in the Canadian parliamentary elections.
   ``In recent years, relations between the United States and Canada
have been marked by cooperative dialogue and a remarkable record of
mutually beneficial achievement,'' Reagan said in a statement
released by the White House press office here.
   Reagan, who is in the second day of a six-day Thanksgiving
vacation at his mountaintop ranch about 35 miles from this seaside
city, said the United States ``looks forward to working together
with Canada to further strengthen the ties of friendship and
cooperation between Canada and the United States.''
   ``In particular, we look forward to the early implementation of
the Free Trade Agreement which, we believe, will be a positive
factor in the economic future of both countries and on the Uruguay
Round negotiations,'' the president said in the statement.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater told reporters at a
briefing that Reagan had phoned Mulroney at 11:47 a.m. EST, to
extend ``his personal congratulations.''
   Asked whether Reagan had seen the victory of Mulroney's
Progressive Conservative Party as a reaffirmation of the free-trade
policies pursued by his administration, Fitzwater said ``we wouldn't
try to term (the reasons for Mulroney's victory) ... the Canadian
elections.''
   ``We are hopeful tht the Free Trade Agreement will be implemented
by the (Canadian) Parliament and then that the president will be
able to take the next step, which is to issue a diplomatic note to
put the agreement into effect by January (1989),'' the spokesman
said.
   The agreement was sealed in this country by congressional
approval earlier this year, and it would commence a program of
gradually removing all trade barriers and tariffs affecting the
estimated $160 billion worth of trade between the two countries each
year.
   On Capitol Hill, Sen. Richard G. Lugar, R-Ind., a former chairman
of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, said it is impossible to
overestimate the importance of the Conservative victory and what it
portends for world trade.
   ``The U.S.-Canada trade agreement came at a time when many
countries had to make a choice between either increasing world trade
and overall world wealth or adopting protectionism and attempting to
secure diminishing prospects _ thus increasing poverty in the midst
of potential overall world economic decline,'' Lugar said.
   ``It was vitally important that the election resolution make it
possible for the treaty to be ratified by Canada,'' he said. ``We
know that free men everywhere rejoice with us.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
