<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Principal-Drugs,0174</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arrested Principal Plans Drug Rehab</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A public school principal who was arrested two
weeks ago while allegedly trying to buy crack plans to enter a drug
treatment program, his lawyer told a judge Tuesday.
   Matthew Barnwell, 55, did not speak in his five-minute appearance
before Criminal Court Judge Thomas Donati. His lawyer, Philip
Foglia, said, ``Mr. Barnwell's present intention is to enter an
in-patient substance abuse program.''
   Assistant District Attorney Paul Shechtman told the judge that
laboratory analysis showed Barnwell was carrying two vials of
cocaine totalling two grains when he was arrested Nov. 9 near his
home in Manhattan.
   Barnwell, a principal for 16 years at P.S. 52 in the Bronx, was
charged with illegal possession of a controlled substance, a
misdemeanor punishable by up to a year in jail. Shechtman said that
when Barnwell was arrested he told police he was a ``lowly school
aide.''
   Donati scheduled motions for Jan. 10 and allowed Barnwell to
remain free on his own recognizance.
