<HEAD>Amtrak Train Hits Truck; 10 Injured</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout to recast, add detail. CORRECTS that train
originated in Chicago sted Memphis. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>GRENADA, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Amtrak passenger train hit a log truck
at a crossing south of here this morning, injuring 10 people
including eight passengers, authorities said.
   There were no fatalities and the train did not derail. The
southbound City of New Orleans train, en route from Chicago to New
Orleans, carried 138 passengers and crew members.
   The accident occurred about 7:25 a.m., according to Amtrak
spokeswoman Debbie Hare in Chicago.
   In addition to the eight passengers, Hare said, the injured were
a train crew member and the driver of the log truck.
   Cathy Smith, spokeswoman at Grenada Lake Medical Center, said
seven people were admitted, none with critical injuries.
   Two other people were treated and released, she said, and a
6-year-old girl was transferred to the Delta Medical Center burn
center in Greenville, where she was in stable condition.
   Smith said the girl apparently suffered second- and third-degree
burns when hot coffee spilled on her.
   The accident occurred at the U.S. 51 crossing about three miles
south of Grenada, a town of 20,000 in central Mississippi.
   Grenada County Sheriff's Department Deputy James Webb identified
the truck driver as Clayton J. Jenkins, 43, of Noxapater.
   Webb said the truck was headed into the Louisiana Pacific paper
mill when the accident occurred. He said Jenkins ``failed to yield
from what we can tell.'' There are no lights at the crossing, he
said.
   Uninjured passengers were transferred to buses for the remainder
of their trip to New Orleans, Hare said.
</TEXT>
