<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Unrest     11-22 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0533</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supreme Soviet Session Interrupted by Reports of New Unrest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Kremlin's representative in a troubled southern
region interrupted a session of the Armenian legislature Tuesday
because of mass ethnic protests in neighboring Azerbaijan, official
and dissident sources said.
   Arkady Volsky interrupted the Armenian Supreme Soviet and flew
immediately to Stepanakert, the capital of the Nagorno-Karabakh
region, which has been the focus of a dispute between the republics
of Azerbaijan and Armenia, said an editor of the official Armenpress
news agency.
   Reports from Baku, the capital of Azerbaijan, said a crowd of
more than 100,000 people carried banners saying, ``Free the Heroes
of Sumgait.''
   The editor, who spoke on condition of anonymity, reported
anti-Armenian rallies in Baku and several other Azerbaijani cities.
   Ethnic rioting broke out in the Azerbaijani city of Sumgait at
the end of February in which at least 32 people, 26 Armenians and
six Azerbaijanis were killed.
   On Saturday, Armenian activists in Moscow reported that Akhmed
Akhmedov, an Azerbaijani, had been sentenced to death by a Moscow
court for leading a gang that killed seven people during the riots.
   Alexei Mannonikov, an editor with the dissident journal Glasnost
in Moscow, said large protests were reported in Kirovabad and
Nakhichevan as well.
   Mannonikov said a strike at factories and public transportation
was under way in Baku, and that demonstrators had marched to the
Armenian quarter of the city.
   The Armenpress editor said the Supreme Soviet of Armenia had
approved a proclamation officially recognizing a massacre of
Armenians by Ottoman Turks in 1915 be officially recognized by
authorities as genocide.
   Armenian activists said that was important because it laid open
for review a series of historical questions including territorial
matters such as control over Nagorno-Karabakh.
   Nagorno-Karabakh is a predominantly Armenian area that was made a
part of Azerbaijan in the 1920s.
   The residents began agitating in February for annexation by
predominantly Christian Armenia, leading to mass protests and
strikes in Armenia and counterprotests in Azerbaijan, which is
mostly Moslem.
   Mannonikov said the Armenian parliament adjourned without
discussing a proposal to approve amendments challenging Moscow's
authority over the republic's affairs similar to one approved in
Estonia last week.
   The session was broadcast live on local TV. It considered the
republic's 1989 budget first, and then listened to complaints about
the republic's ecology situation from Deputy Khachik Stambultsyan, a
member of the Karabakh Committee that is pushing for annexation,
said Armenian activist Rafael Popoyan.
   Stambultsyan specifically complained about a nuclear power
station built near Yerevan, the capital of Armenia, that officials
since have acknowledged was constructed on a geological fault. The
drive to annex Nagorno-Karabakh, which began in February, has
spilled over to include complaints about too much control from
Moscow, economic problems and the environment.
   Armenians gathered in the city's Opera Square, where a television
set was broadcasting the session, and outside the Supreme Soviet
building, Popoyan said.
   Moscow has turned down demands to unite Nagorno-Karabakh with
Armenia, opting instead for a long-range financial development plan.
The refusal has not quieted unrest, however, and another strike was
reported in Yerevan last week.
</TEXT>
