<HEAD>Israeli Air Raid on Sidon, 6 Killed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with three more dead, more
detail; PICKS up 6th graf pvs, `Nine others ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli warplanes today blasted guerrilla
bases near the southern port city of Sidon, killing six Palestinians
and wounding nine, police said.
   In Jerusalem, a military spokesman confirmed the attack and said
the targets were guerrilla headquarters that served as launching
points for attacks against Israel. It was the 22nd attack on Lebanon
this year.
   Police said fighter bombers rocketed guerrilla bases in the Ein
el-Hilweh refugee camp in four sorties that lasted five minutes. Two
helicopter gunships pounded the camp's western entrance 10 minutes
later, police said.
   Smoke billowed from the camp as the jets and gunships fired eight
rockets, hitting a PLO checkpoint and two guerrilla jeeps, police
reported.
   Three PLO guerrillas were killed in one of the jeeps, said
police. They identified them as belonging to the Popular Front for
the Liberation of Palestine, the Marxist group led by George Habash.
The other jeep belonged to PLO chairman Yasser Arafat's mainstream
Fatah faction, police said.
   A Fatah gunner was killed when a rocket slammed into a a nearby
artillery base, where a woman and her 4-year-old daughter also died,
police said. Rescuers were searching the rubble for more victims,
according to police.
   Nine others were wounded in the raid on the teeming shantytown
that houses 60,000 Palestinians, the largest among Lebanon's 11
refugee camps.
   The Israeli spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
all the Israeli jets returned safely after making accurate hits.
   The warplanes struck the outskirts of Lebanon's third-largest
city as the country marked the 45th anniversary of its independence
from France.
   Police said smoke billowed from the teeming camp as ambulances
raced from Sidon to evacuate casualties.
   By police count, 108 people were killed and 309 wounded in the 21
previous air strikes since Jan. 3.
   It was the first air strike said the PLO declared an independent
Palestinian state Nov. 15. The declaration came at the end of a
meeting of his movement's parliament-in-exile, the Palestine
National Council, in Algiers, Algeria.
   The last Israeli air raid on Lebanon was on Israel's election
day, Nov. 1.
</TEXT>
