<2ND_LINE>AM-Video Burglary,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Owner Trains Camera on Parrot, Records Burglars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roy Ohse figured his reluctant parrot was
probably talking behind his back, so he rigged up a video camera to
see if he could catch the bird in action while he went to the store.
   But in addition to the parrot's chatter, Ohse's camera recorded
two burglars making off with some of his possessions.
   Fortunately, the camera was not among the items they carried off.
And police used the videotape to arrest the youths and a third
teen-ager, one of whom is awaiting sentencing this week in the May
burglary.
   Ohse, 57, a retired sign painter, said he had been trying to
expand the vocabulary of his 3-year-old African gray parrot for
months.
   ``I figured I'd catch him on a recording,'' Ohse said Monday. ``I
was just curious. I wasn't gone 35 minutes.''
   When he got back, Ohse didn't know he had been burglarized until
he played the videotape to see what his bird had said.
   The burglars could be heard rummaging through things and asking
each other whether they should take various items.
   One distinctly human voice said, ``See anything worth taking?''
Another said, ``You take the bag and stuff and I'll take this.''
   Two teen-agers also passed in front of the camera and their faces
could be clearly seen. At one point, the 13-year-old said to the
older one, ``There's a video camera, you want to chance it with
that?''
   ``Nah,'' came the answer from the background.
   Police said they took a camera, BB guns, a wristwatch,
binoculars, cash and some remote-control cars.
   When Ohse played the tape back, a friend of his 17-year-old son
recognized one of the teen-agers, and deputies arrested Luis
Rodriguez, 18, along with a 13-year-old and a 17-year-old.
   Rodriguez pleaded guilty to a burglary charge and is scheduled to
be sentenced this week.
   The 13-year-old pleaded guilty to burglary charges and was
sentenced to community control, a form of supervised probation. The
third teen-ager pleaded guilty to dealing in stolen property and
also was sentenced to community control.
</TEXT>
