<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Australia-Missing     11-22 0187</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Australia-Missing,0193</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Canoes With 18 Crewmen Aboard Missing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DARWIN, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine log canoes with 18 people aboard
were missing Tuesday on an expedition from the Indonesian island of
Bali to Darwin, the expedition leader said.
   The canoes failed to rendezvous with the ship Alegrias on Monday
at Leti Island, about 300 miles northwest of Darwin, said expedition
leader Bob Hobman, who was aboard the ship.
   The missing crewmen are from the United States, Australia, New
Zealand, France, West Germany, Britain, Japan and Indonesia.
   Hobman said the canoes encountered strong headwinds and were last
seen Monday near Kisar Island, about 25 miles northwest of Leti.
   He said the fleet may have drifted south of Leti and been swept
ashore on the island of Timor, where rebels are waging a violent
anti-government campaign.
   Each canoe carried emergency food supplies, about 2{ gallons of
water and a radio that could transmit across six miles.
   The handcrafted boats left Bali five weeks ago for the 1,000 mile
``Great Junk Race,'' patterned after the voyages of ancient
Austronesians whose small craft conquered the Pacific more than
2,000 years ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
