<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GoodSamaritan 1stLd-Writethru a0644 11-22 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Good Samaritan, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0644,0433</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mugging Victim, Neighbors Ask Leniency For Convict-Samaritan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS last graf to CORRECT that fourth petition was from
hospital where alleged assailant was arrested, not where Miss George
worked.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mugging victim who says she was saved from
``certain death'' when a neighbor shot her two assailants has asked
a judge to be lenient when he sentences her rescuer for an earlier
drug conviction.
   ``I would like to see justice tempered with mercy for this
unselfish act of compassion shown by this man, a total stranger to
me,'' Gertrude George wrote to state Supreme Court Justice Joseph
Slavin in a letter delivered Monday.
   The judge also was given 50 letters with similar messages from
people who know the man, Clovis Fearon, and four petitions
circulated in his Brooklyn neighborhood.
   Slavin is to sentence Fearon, 29, on Monday, more than nine
months after he pleaded guilty to felony charges for ``steering''
two undercover police officers to a drug dealer, who sold them two
vials of crack cocaine.
   The judge had promised Fearon a sentence of one day in jail and
five years probation when he entered the plea in February.
   But Fearon never appeared for his March sentencing and
authorities did not learn his whereabouts until Nov. 2, when he
raced out of his apartment with an unlicensed revolver after hearing
Miss George's screams from the street.
   He shot each of Miss George's assailants once. One, Raymond
Plowden, 25, was found dead a block away, still clutching her
jewelry.
   The other, Timothy Lewis, 25, escaped but was arrested on
robbery, assault and weapons charges at a hospital where he sought
treatment for a gunshot wound to the back.
   ``I was rescued from certain death by a man, Clovis Fearon, also
known as Anthony Dixon, who by coming to my defense revealed his own
past for which he is being prosecuted,'' said Miss George, who was
attacked as she returned home from her job as a nurse.
   After the shooting, Fearon told police his name was Anthony
Dixon. But his true identity was discovered through fingerprints
taken when he was charged with illegal possession of a weapon, the
unlicensed gun he used in the shooting.
   Fearon was ordered jailed by Slavin until his sentencing for the
drug conviction.
   During his time as a fugitive, Fearon was a law-abiding citizen
who held as many as three jobs at once, said his attorney, Paul
Ascher.
   Two of the petitions to the court, signed by about 300
neighborhood residents, urged Slavin to give Fearon only probation,
Ascher said. A third petition was signed by area businessmen and
merchants, and the fourth by about 20 people who work at the
hospital where Lewis was arrested.
</TEXT>
