<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LostBoys     11-22 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lost Boys,0221</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Missing Youths Return Home After Night in Woods</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two teen-agers missing overnight in rugged
woods said they built a fire and slept on logs before following a
stream to safety Tuesday.
   ``I'm really glad to be back. I hope that never happens again,''
said Jeffrey Burrows, 15, of Elkins.
   Burrows and 15-year-old Paul Dandevener of Montrose, were found
about 11:45 a.m. Tuesday after emerging from the woods in the tiny
community of Bemis, about five miles east of where they were last
seen.
   The teen-agers became lost Monday while hunting.
   ``We started walking and got into a bunch of laurel,'' said
Burrows. He said both he and his companion were ``kind of scared''
and built a fire that lasted about an hour.
   Despite a heavy frost and a low temperature of 18 degrees, they
slept through the night on logs and set out for civilization Tuesday
morning.
   ``We knew once we followed the Shaver's Fork River we could find
our way back home,'' Burrows said.
   A search party gathered Tuesday morning, and Ray Mearns, a
Department of Natural Resources conservation officer in Elkins, said
he was just about to board a helicopter to begin an aerial search
when he received word that the boys had reached safety.
</TEXT>
