<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-88 1554EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ToySafety     11-22 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Toy Safety,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Consumer Safety Agency Defends Record, Urges Parental Vigilance
With Toys</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Consumer Product Safety Commission on
Tuesday defended its record on ridding the market of dangerous toys
but urged parents to consider safety when shopping for their
children this holiday season.
   ``While federal authorities have stepped up efforts to intercept
dangerous imported toys at the nation's ports, parents must still
practice safety,'' Anne Graham, commissioner of the safety
commission, told reporters at the federal agency's annual holiday
safety news conference.
   The commission said its joint effort with the U.S. Customs
Service, which was begun in 1987, has resulted in the seizure of
891,000 toys that failed to meet federal safety guidelines between
Oct. 1, 1987 and Sept. 30, 1988 and 162,668 toys since Oct. 1 of
this year.
   But commission officials urged parents to heed the age
recommendations and warning labels on toys, consider their child's
skill level and be aware of the play environment.
   Standing before a display of toys that had been recalled in 1988,
Ms. Graham also responded to charges from the Consumer Affairs
Committee of the Americans for Democratic Action, which on Monday
claimed that the ``major reason for the abundance of dangerous
toys'' is ``the pitiful ineptitude'' of the CPSC.
   ``I clearly don't agree with their allegations. We spend 12
months out of every year trying to address toy safety,'' Ms. Graham
said.
   ``On the other hand, I'm appreciative of the ADA for bringing the
toys that they're concerned about to our attention. Our compliance
unit will be looking at them immediately and determining if they're
safe or not. If they're not, we'll take measures to get them off the
market,'' she said.
   Toys caused 131,000 injuries last year, including 105,000 to
children under age 15, according to the safety commission.
   Two types of toys to avoid, the ADA said in its report Monday,
are baby walkers and crib gyms. The walkers can tip over or fall
down stairs, while the gyms are responsible for a dozen deaths and
662 other injuries in the past five years, the report said.
   Accidents involving baby walkers occur when steps or stairways
are not blocked or doors are not closed, John Preston, a mechanical
engineer with the commission, said at the news conference. He
encouraged close parental supervision.
   ``As far as baby walkers are concerned, there aren't any specific
defects,'' Ms. Graham said.
   Commission spokeswoman Elaine Tyrrell demonstrated how a crib gym
could become dangerous for a child who is able to stand, usually
about the age of six months.
   A child could get entangled in the toy which stretches across a
crib and strangulation deaths have occured. She urged parents to
remove the toy once a child becomes more active.
   The commission said two pamphlets, titled ``Which Toy for Which
Child: A Consumer's Guide for Selecting Suitable Toys,'' are
available to those seeking guidance on what toys to buy.
   One pamphlet is for ages birth through 5; the other is for ages 6
through 12.
   They describe the types of activities children enjoy at specific
ages and the toys they prefer. They suggest types of toys, without
providing trade names, for ``active play, manipulative play,
make-believe play, creative play and learning play.''
   Another pamphlet, titled ``For Kid's Sake,'' recommends that
parents:
   _Keep in mind the child's age, interests and skill level. Look
for quality design and construction in all toys for all ages.
   _Be a label reader. Look for and heed age recommendations and
other safety labels.
   _Keep toys for older children away from younger children.
   The pamphlets are available by writing the U.S. Consumer Product
Safety Commission, Office of Information and Public Affairs,
Washington, D.C. 20207, or calling the commission's toll-free
number: (800) 638-2772.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
