<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Weinberger-Soviets     11-22 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weinberger-Soviets,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Calls Glasnost a Stunt, Says Soviets Still Seek World Rule</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Defense Secretary Caspar Weinberger says
glasnost is mostly a public relations stunt, and that the Soviets
are still intent on ruling the world.
   ``I have not yet seen any indication that they have given up
their idea of world domination,'' Weinberger said in an interview
published Tuesday by Jane's Defense Weekly.
   ``I think a very great deal of glasnost is a public relations
exercise on a very large scale and a recognition that the attempts
to change Western public opinion in the past failed, despite their
absolute confidence they could do that _ with peace marches and so
on,'' he said of Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of
greater openness on selected social topics.
   Gorbachev has tried ``to convince the West that he is a different
sort of person, that he is a Western type of man, that he likes
freedom and democracy and that he would like the Soviet Union to be
more like the West.
   ``It is very dangerous if we believe that.''
   Weinberger was quoted as saying the Soviet military ``has not
been cut back by one ruble'' and ``still keeps growing.''
   On the Soviet troop withdrawal from Afghanistan, Weinberger told
Jane's: ``They have started to withdraw in a very peculiar way... by
putting in more Scud missiles and more troops, so I worry very much
if they are going to carry out their withdrawal.''
</TEXT>
