<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-88 1507EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon     11-22 0571</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0593</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Bombs Bases, Shiites Battle As Lebanon Celebrates
Independence</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli warplanes blasted guerrilla bases,
killing six people and wounding nine on Tuesday, the 45th
anniversary of Lebanon's independence.
   Christians and Moslems marched in separate parades in Beirut
marking independence, underscoring fractured Lebanon's partition
into sectarian mini-states.
   As they celebrated, bursts of gunfire and grenade blasts
resounded across the capital when the Syrian-backed Shiite militia,
Amal, and the rival pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God, clashed
in gunbattles in south Beirut slums.
   The Israeli raid on the biggest refugee camp in Lebanon killed
six Palestinians, including a 4-year-old girl, and wounded nine. It
was the first air assault since the declaration of an independent
state of Palestine a week ago.
   Police said four Israeli fighter-bombers thundered in on
Palestine Liberation Organization targets on the outskirts of
Lebanon's southern port of Sidon. They staged four rocket runs in
five minutes on a PLO checkpoint at Ein El-Hilweh refugee camp,
police said. The camp of 60,000 Palestinians is the largest of the
11 in Lebanon.
   Two helicopter gunships followed 10 minutes later, police said.
They hit two jeeps racing to help wounded guerrillas at the burning
checkpoint.
   The bodies of three guerrillas from George Habash's Marxist
Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine were retrieved from
one jeep. The other vehicle belonged to PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat's
mainstream Fatah, police said.
   A Fatah gunner was killed when a rocket slammed into a nearby
artillery base, where a woman and her 4-year-old daughter also died.
Rescuers were searching rubble for more victims.
   Guerrillas unleashed a screen of Sam-7 Strella missiles at the
helicopters, but made no hits, police said.
   A Israeli command communique said its warplanes struck targets
serving as guerrilla headquarters and launching points for attacks
against Israel.
   It was Israel's 22nd air raid in Lebanon this year. By police
count, 108 people have been killed and 309 wounded in 21 air strikes
since Jan. 3.
   Syrian troops in Beirut's Moslem sector sent loudspeaker vans
blaring calls for an immediate cease-fire into the embattled slums
of Chiyah and Ghobeiri. There was no quick report of casualties.
``We have not been able to take stock of the losses yet,'' said an
Amal spokesman.
   The fighting erupted a day after four senior leaders of the
fundamentalist Hezbollah escaped assassination by a
remote-controlled car bomb.
   The two factions are vying for dominance of the 1 million Shiites
who form Lebanon's biggest sect.
   In Beirut, Moslem and Christian units of Lebanon's 42,000-member
army staged separate parades to mark independence from France in
1943.
   Acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, a Sunni, and the rival head of
the Christian Cabinet, Gen. Michel Aoun, delivered separate speeches.
   The split celebrations reflected the ongoing political crisis
that has left Lebanon without a president for two months,
threatening to formalize the de facto partition after 13 years of
civil war.
   ``Lebanon is in the throes of collapse,'' said Syrian-backed
Hoss. ``We cannot recover our unity through further dismemberment.
If reunion is difficult, partition is impossible.''
   Aoun lashed out at Syria and Israel as ``occupiers and usurpers.''
   An estimated 40,000 Syrian troops are stationed on 70 percent of
Lebanon's territory under a 1976 Arab League mandate to end the
civil war. Israel controls a 6-to-10 mile enclave in south Lebanon
as a buffer zone against cross-border guerrilla raids.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881122-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-88 1703EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TearGas     11-22 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tear Gas,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>70-Year-Old Man Says He Won't Pay Fine For Tear-Gassing Youths</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROGER MUNNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 70-year-old man said Tuesday he was
within his rights when he sprayed tear gas on a group of threatening
youngsters, and said he will appeal a judge's order to pay a $100
fine.
   ``These kids came at me with violence and said they had knives
and said they were going to carve out my liver and fry it,'' said
Edward White of Cedar Rapids.
   Associate District Judge Michael Newmeister found White guilty of
assault, a misdemeanor, and fined him the maximum $100 on Monday. A
county prosecutor said an effort would be made to require White to
pay the youths' hospital bills.
   Several of the youths said in court that one boy, who couldn't be
located for trial, had threatened to kill White and that he had a
knife. However, the youths had varied recollections about whether
the threat came before or after White sprayed the group with tear
gas.
   Seven children aged 8 to 14 were taken to a hospital for
treatment of irritated eyes and skin after being sprayed in the
Sept. 18 incident.
   ``I was only protecting myself, and now they say I have to pay
hospital costs,'' White said in a telephone interview from his home.
``Things have quieted down since I put the tear gas on 'em. There
hasn't been any problem next door since then. I guess I settled it.''
   White said he and other neighbors had trouble with neighborhood
children for some time before the incident.
   On the night in question, White and his 94-year-old mother were
sitting on their porch. A group of teen-agers was in the area, and
White said they flew into a rage when he asked them to stop making
so much noise.
   ``The officer said I should have called police, but I know that
wouldn't have done any good,'' White said.
   White said he displayed his tear gas canister and warned the
teen-agers what he would do if they didn't disperse.
   ``I'm not a violent man,'' he said. ``I don't have a gun. I told
'em you either settle down or else. They said, `We got knives.' So I
give 'em a couple of squirts. If you're being attacked, what do you
do?''
   He said that in addition to the threats, the teen-agers struck
him with a rake handle.
   White said he had ``four or five drinks'' before the incident,
but was not drunk.
</TEXT>
