<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-Politics Bjt   11-22 0573</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Politics, Bjt,0588</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shamir's Bid to Religious Parties Faces Complictions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir renewed the task
of tying together right-wing and ultra-Orthodox religious parties in
a government after talks broke off Tuesday with the left-leaning
Labor Party.
   Shamir's spokesman Yossi Ahimeir said the premier was confident
he could form a majority government in Parliament by next week.
   Other officials, including some in Shamir's right-wing Likud
bloc, admitted the prime minister faces a complicated chore and
might have to turn again to Labor, headed by his archrival, Foreign
Minister Shimon Peres.
   Labor halted the talks after being refused two key Cabinet posts,
equal representation in the decision-making inner Cabinet, and
assurances Israel will press for a Middle East peace, Labor party
officials said.
   Without Labor Shamir must please seven small parties and faces
lobbying by American and Canadian Jews objecting to Orthodox dhe current
break-off was partly a bargaining
tactic.
   Shamir is faced with having to form a coaltion government because
Nov. 1 elections to the 120-seat Knesset, or parliament, gave his
Likud only 40 seats and Labor 39. The rest went to leftist, rightist
and religious parties.
   In his efforts to attract religious parties, Shamir is becoming
entangled in an argument between Orthodox Jews and the Reform and
Conservative branches of Judaism, which are dominant overseas.
   A dozen American and Canadian Jewish leaders are lobbying Shamir
to reject Orthodox demands for the ``Who is a Jew'' law that would
mean conversions to Judaism would be accepted in Israel only if they
were done by Orthodox rabbis.
   The foreign Jewish leaders, who represent the Reform and
Conservative movements, say the new law calls into question their
Jewishness.
   Ahimeir said Shamir told U.S. and Canadian Jews on Tuesday he
would stick to the promise to put the law before the Knesset despite
opposition by North American Jews.
   ``He explained to them that the matter was a formal, internal
Israeli matter that should not create a rift or misunderstanding
with diaspora Jewry,'' Ahimeir said in a telephone interview.
   The four religious parties submitted the bill to the Knesset
Tuesday, but some Likud members said Shamir will find it tough to
get the legislation approved.
   Meir Shitreet, a Likud lawmaker, told Israel television the law
could cost Israel up to $100 million in annual contributions from
U.S. Jews.
</TEXT>
