<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Baltics 2ndLd-Writethru a0623 11-22 0609</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Baltics, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0623,0623</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Latvia's Legislature Meets to Consider Autonomy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with to 6 grafs to fix wording of Estonian declaration;
PICKS up 7th pvs, `The Supreme ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers in Soviet Latvia met today to consider
declaring more self-rule for their republic from Moscow, as
neighboring Estonia did last week in a vote that provoked Kremlin
opposition.
   Latvia's Supreme Soviet convened in the capital, Riga, to adopt a
1989 budget. It was expected this evening to consider constitutional
reforms proposed by Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Mikhail Bonden, who is affiliated with the Moscow-based human
rights journal Express-Khronika, said by telephone from Riga that 50
pickets stood outside the Supreme Soviet carrying signs opposing the
constitutional changes. Many Latvians claim they would reduce the
rights of their republic.
   Deputies from a special legal commission of the Supreme Soviet
national parliament have recommended some changes in amendments
proposed by Gorbachev to limit the powers of a new national council,
which originally would have been able to strike down laws adopted by
legislatures of the 15 Soviet republics.
   Andrei Tsirulis, a Latvian youth newspaper editor, said leaders
of a local grassroots political organization, the People's Front,
asked their deputies to take legal steps ``so the republic will have
sovereignty inside the Soviet Union.''
   Last Wednesday, Estonia's parliament declared itself
``sovereign,'' saying it had the right to override all federal
legislation with the exception of that pertaining to foreign policy
and defense.
   The Supreme Soviet in the third Baltic republic, Lithuania,
balked at taking a similar step Friday.
   Latvia's legislature, whose session was being broadcast live on
two local radio stations, was to vote on the constitutional changes
after considering local economic issues, Tsirulis said.
   ``The entire Latvian people is listening attentively,'' the
editor said. ``The Latvian people support the proposals of the
People's Front and want them adopted.''
   The legal commission of the Moscow-based Supreme Soviet, which
met Saturday, said the Estonian decision to make Soviet laws
subordinate to local control violates the 1977 Soviet constitution.
   They forwarded their decision to the Supreme Soviet Presidium,
the nation's top executive body, possibly presaging a striking down
of the Estonian action.
   Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania were independent after the 1917
Bolshevik Revolution until 1940, when they were absorbed by the
Soviets under a 1939 agreement with Nazi Germany.
   In the southern Soviet republic of Armenia today, the Kremlin's
representative to the region today interrupted an Armenian
legislative session because of ethnic protests in neighboring
Azerbaijan, official and dissident sources said.
   Arkady Volsky, sent by the Kremlin to oversee its policy in the
area, broke up the Armenian Supreme Soviet and then flew immediately
to Stepanakert, the capital of the Nagorno-Karabakh region, which is
disputed by Azerbaijan and Armenia, said an editor of the official
Armenpress news agency.
   Volsky and Armenian officials presumably felt that debate of
several issues pertaining to Nagorno-Karabakh on the agenda of the
Armenians parliament could increase tensions further.
   The editor, who spoke on condition of anonymity, reported
anti-Armenian rallies in the Azerbaijani capital of Baku, and
several other Azerbaijani cities.
   Reports from Baku said a crowd of more than 100,000 people
carried banners saying, ``Free the Heroes of Sumgait.''
   Strikes and demonstrations about the demands sparked rioting in
which at least 32 people were killed in the Azerbaijani city of
Sumgait at the end of February and beginning of March.
   The mainly Christian Armenians claim Nagorno-Karabakh is
historically part of Armenia, but was attached to Azerbaijan, which
is Moslem dominated, in the 1920s.
   Moscow has turned down demands to unite Nagorno-Karabakh with
Armenia, opting instead for a long-range financial development plan.
</TEXT>
