<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Inflation Bjt   11-22 0977</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Inflation, Bjt,950</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Clothing Costs Power Consumer Inflation to 5 Percent Range</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sharp increases for fall and winter clothing
put consumer price inflation back in the 5 percent annual range last
month despite the smallest monthly increase in food costs since
February, the government said Tuesday.
   Consumer prices rose 0.4 percent in October _ or at an annual
rate of 5.1 percent _ with more than half of the gain coming from a
1.8 percent boost in apparel prices and sharp increases in auto
insurance and financing charges, the Labor Department said.
   Inflation had slowed to an annual rate of 4.1 percent in
September as a 1.7 percent drop in gasoline prices offset
drought-caused spikes in grocery prices. Overall cost increases were
held to just 0.3 percent for that month.
   Economists also had anticipated smaller price increases in
October, believing that merchants would not mark up their fall and
winter clothing lines as much after already boosting them by 2
percent in September.
   ``It's still fundamentally in line with an inflation rate of 4.5
percent to 5 percent that we've seen over the past year or so,''
Larry Chimerine, chairman of the WEFA Group, a Bala Cynwyd, Pa.,
forecasting firm, said of the overall October numbers.
   Chimerine's view represents the center in a range of opinions
among analysts. Some say the U.S. economy is on the verge of an
inflationary spiral of wage and price increases; others believe it
is nowhere near that danger point.
   Inflation has creeped up from last year's rate of 4.4 percent. It
rose from an annual rate of 4.2 percent in the first quarter of 1988
to 4.5 percent in the second quarter and to 4.8 percent in the third
quarter.
   But the White House predicted Tuesday that inflation will slow
dramatically in November and December to finish the year with only a
4.3 percent increase over 1987, compared with a 4.6 percent annual
rate for the first 10 months.
   For 1989, the administration is forecasting consumer price
inflation of only 3.7 percent, compared with predictions of 5
percent or more by private analysts.
   Allen Sinai, chief economist for the Boston Co., a New York
consulting firm, said the nation has an ``unacceptable inflation
problem'' even if policymakers do not recognize it yet.
   ``Five percent inflation may be alright for some segments of the
economy, but it induces a greater inflation psychology where it
doesn't take much to push it up to 5.5 or 6 percent,'' he said.
``Any shock _ higher oil prices, a falling dollar, another drought,
higher wages _ can run it up more.''
   Weekly earnings, after adjusting for inflation, rose a seasonally
adjusted 0.5 percent in October, the same increase as September, the
Labor Department said.
   But in August, they had fallen 1.3 percent, the worst drop in
four years. And even though the $329.81 average weekly pay check
last month was 4.1 percent higher than in October 1987, workers
still had slightly less buying power than they did a year ago, the
department said.
   Price figures for the month showed that the first round of
aftershocks from the 1987 drought, the driest summer in decades for
the country, are about over.
   Food costs rose only 0.2 percent, compared with a 0.8 percent
jump in September. And fruit and vegetable prices fell 1.1 percent
after rising 12.9 percent the preceding three months because of
drought-related shortages.
   Prices for beef, pork and poultry also fell in October, by 0.3
percent, 0.8 percent and 3.0 percent, respectively. Offsetting the
declines was the biggest monthly price increase for dairy products
since December 1980 _ 0.9 percent.
   Cereal and bakery product costs rose 0.7 percent, roughly the
trend of monthly increases they have followed all year and stemming
largely from a drought-induced erosion of grain stockpiles stored
from past surpluses.
   Gasoline prices fell 1 percent in October after the 1.7 percent
drop in September and home heating oil costs were down 3.2 percent.
But a 1.4 percent increase in home electric and natural gas rates
eroded the overall energy savings.
   While crude oil prices have plummeted by more than 30 percent
over the past year, gasoline prices over the same period have
dropped less than 2 percent and home heating prices have fallen only
5 percent.
   Excluding food and energy, prices rose 0.5 percent for the month.
   The 1.8 percent apparel cost gains in October atop the 2 percent
increase in September reflected the introduction of higher-priced
fall and winter fashions, particularly for women's and girls'
clothing and shoes.
   ``Those prices are going to give pretty quickly if the past few
years are any precedent,'' said Sandra Shaber, an analyst for the
Futures Group, a Washington economic consulting firm.
   Ms. Shaber said retailers have changed their pricing policies in
recent years, marking up prices more upon the introduction of new
lines and models to ``make the discounts later look that much
better.''
   Sticker prices on new 1989 model autos, for example, are 7.5
percent over comparable 1988 models, the Labor Department said. But
seasonally adjusted new car prices in October were just 0.2 percent
higher than in September, even though '89 models accounted for
one-fourth of the new cars sold in the government's October survey
and none in the September tally.
   Meanwhile, auto insurance and finance charges rose 1.4 percent
and 3.4 percent, respectively, last month.
   Medical care costs rose 0.5 percent, halfway between the
respective 0.4 percent and 0.6 percent increases in August and
September. In the last year, medical costs have risen a total of 6.7
percent.
   The October increases raised the Consumer Price Index to 120.2.
That means a basket of goods costing $100 on average from 1982
through 1984 would have cost $120.20 last month, 40 cents higher
than in September and up from $115.30 a year ago.
</TEXT>
