<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Anti-Drug Shooting,0179</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Goes On Spree Against Crack Dealers, Police Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who said he was angry about crack
dealers going unpunished fired as many 100 rounds from his machine
gun into a suspected drug-infested neighborhood, police said.
   James Harold Wilkerson, 55, was arrested Monday with an AK-47
assault rifle and a .44-caliber revolver after he drove his car into
a ditch during a chase with police.
   ``He was loaded down for big game,'' said Detective Ron Smith of
the Jacksonville Sheriff's Office. ``He said he wanted to scare some
drug dealers off.''
   No one was injured, but police said shots were fired randomly
through the Northside neighborhood, where Wilkerson told police
crack dealers were operating openly.
   ``He says the police aren't doing anything about it,'' Smith said.
   Wilkerson, a self-employed merchant, told police that one of his
nine children had become addicted to crack, he said.
   Wilkerson was jailed on charges of possession of a machine gun,
carrying a concealed firearm and resisting arrest, police said.
