<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Goetz     11-22 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Goetz,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High Court Upholds Weapons Possession Conviction For Goetz</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL STASHENKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York state's highest court Tuesday upheld
Bernhard Goetz's conviction for illegal possession of a gun, the
only charge he was convicted of following his 1984 shooting spree on
a New York City subway car.
   The state Court of Appeals said in an unsigned, three-paragraph
ruling that the judge at Goetz's trial, Manhattan state Supreme
Court Justice Stephen Crane, did not make an error in his
instructions to the jury that found Goetz guilty of criminal
possession of a weapon.
   The unanimous decision means Goetz now faces resentencing on the
third-degree weapon charge in state Supreme Court, New York's
trial-level court. The first sentence that included six months in
jail he received from Crane was later overturned by the Appellate
Division of state Supreme Court.
   Gerald McKelvey, a spokesman for Manhattan District Attorney
Robert Morgenthau, said officials in that prosecutor's office were
pleased that Goetz won't get off scot-free.
   ``We're gratified that the New York Court of Appeals has upheld
our position in the appeal of this case,'' McKelvey said.
   Barry Slotnick, Goetz's chief attorney, called Tuesday's ruling
``short, not sweet and obviously disappointing.'' He said Goetz's
court fight will continue.
   ``We have a preliminary determination to go to the federal courts
in the continuing saga of removing that one conviction from Mr.
Goetz's record,'' Slotnick said.
   A new sentencing date will be set after consultation with Goetz's
attorney, McKelvey said.
</TEXT>
