<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-88 1851EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Terrorism     11-22 0449</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Terrorism,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Department Specialist Criticizes Palestine Liberation
Organization</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Accusing some radical Palestinian groups of
cold-blooded terror, a top State Department official on Tuesday
dismissed as ``nonsense'' any suggestion that the Palestine National
Council had renounced terrorism.
   ``It is simply incorrect to assert that by its recent declaration
the PLO renounced terrorism,'' L. Paul Bremer III, who heads the
department's counterterrorism office, said.
   In a speech at a George Washington University conference, Bremer
also reported that terrorist attacks on U.S. targets were running 31
percent above 1987 levels.
   And 1987, he said, was the bloodiest year for terrorist incidents
since the State Department began compiling statistics in 1968. ``We
cannot expect completely to eradicate terrorism. But we can aim to
reduce significantly terrorism's status on the international
agenda.''
   The Palestine National Council, the quasi-legislative arm of the
Palestine Liberation Organization, meeting last Tuesday in Algiers,
declared the establishment of an independent Palestinian state
without defining its boundaries.
   The council also adopted a declaration that the European
Community, among others, subsequently concluded was a renunciation
of terrorism.
   But Bremer said the council specifically endorsed the 1985 Cairo
declaration in which the PLO, while condemning terrorism, also
affirmed ``its adherence to the Palestinian people's right to resist
the Israeli occupation of their land in any way possible.''
   Also, Bremer said, the PLO group endorsed a ``highly
objectionable'' resolution by the U.N. Security Council that ``used
all the code-words terrorists use to justify their acts.''
   For instance, the State Department official said, the resolution
reiterates ``the inalienable right to self-determination'' and
upholds ``the legitimacy of their struggle, in particular the
struggle of national liberation movements.''
   So, Bremer said, while ``some people, some press reports and even
some governments have concluded that in its declaration the PNC
denounced terrorism, this is nonsense.''
   The State Department official said the first immediate concern of
U.S. counterterrorism experts was ``the likely increase in radical
Palestinian terrorism.''
   In May, he said, terrorists from the Abu Nidal organization used
machine guns and grenades to attack a Sudanese hotel and club
frequented by foreign visitors and in July attacked a Greek
passenger ship.
   Last month, Bremer said, West German police arrested members of
the Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine-General Command
before they could carry out a terrorist attack.
   Otrher violent and fanatical Palestinian groups recently
proclaimed their intention to step up their terrorism against
Israel, he said.
   ``Combining a deep, visceral hostility to the West with
cold-blooded terror,'' Bremer said, ``these radical Palestinian
groups receive financial, logistical and weapons support from Syria
and Libya. They are responsible for some of the most vicious
terrorist operations on record.''
</TEXT>
