<1ST_LINE>u a AM-US-Canada     11-22 0588</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Canada,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Officials Elated With Mulroney's Success</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Canada Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan on Tuesday
congratulated Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney on his election
victory, saying he thought it would ``further strengthen the ties of
friendship'' between their nations.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Reagan, who is
vacationing at his nearby mountaintop ranch, had telephoned Mulroney
``to personally congratulate him on him on the victory'' of his
Progressive Conservative Party over the Liberal and New Democratic
parties.
   The president said in a statement that relations between the
United States and Canada ``have been marked by cooperative dialogue
and a remarkable record of mutually beneficial achievement'' in
recent years.
   Reagan and Mulroney had got along well personally as well, and
the two men often kidded one another about their Irish ancestry.
   The president said he considered Mulroney's winning 170 of the
295 seats in the House of Commons as a go-ahead signal on the
U.S-Canada free trade agreement, which has been approved by Congress
but must still be accepted by the Canadian Parliament.
   The agreement is aimed at phasing out all barriers and tariffs on
trade between the two North American neighbors, which do about $160
billion worth of business with each other annually.
   Reagan's statement said ``we look forward to the early
implementation of the free trade agreement which, we believe, will
be a positive factor in the economic future of both countries and on
the Uruguay Round negotiations.''
   The latter reference was to the bargaining that the United
States, Canada and some 95 other nations are undertaking, under the
auspices of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, to open new
markets and remove trade barriers. A mid-term review of the GATT
negotiations is scheduled to begin in Montreal on Dec. 5.
   Speaking to Republican governors meeting in Point Clear, Ala.,
President-elect George Bush called Mulroney's victory an endorsement
of the free trade pact by the Canadian public. ``That indeed was a
referendum on whether we're going to have more markets and freer
trade, both ways,'' he said.
   Bush also telephoned his congratulations to Mulroney.
   At a news briefing, Fitzwater was asked to say to what extent
Reagan considered Mulroney's victory a vindication of the
president's strong support for the free trade agreement.
   ``We wouldn't try to interpret the Canadian elections beyond the
obvious, that it was an election between two parties, and presumably
general support for Prime Minister Mulroney's policies,'' the
spokesman replied.
   ``We are hopeful that the free trade agreement will be
implemented by the Parliament, and that the president will then be
able to take the next step, which is to issue a diplomatic note that
then puts the two agreements into effect by January of 1989.''
   Mulroney has promised to call the House of Commons into session
as soon as possible to ratify the agreement.
   U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter also expressed pleasure
at the outcome, saying in a statement in Washington that with
expected Canadian approval of the pact, ``we will now have the
largest economic trading partnership in the entire world, making
both U.S. and Canadian firms more competitive with our other foreign
trading partners.''
   ``The free trade agreement will bring prosperity to both
countries for years to come,'' Yeutter said.
   On Capitol Hill, Sens. John Heinz, R-Pa., and Bill Bradley,
D-N.J., also said the victory of Mulroney's party would strengthen
the relationship between the United States and Canada and lend
momentum to opening markets around the world.
</TEXT>
