<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary     11-22 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Central Committee Chooses Candidate For Premier</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Central Committee on Tuesday chose a
candidate to replace outgoing Premier Karoly Grosz, who announced he
would resign to concentrate on his duties as leader of the Communist
Party.
   The policy-making Central Committee did not release his name,
party spokesman Laszlo Major said. The candidate first must be
presented to Parliament on Thursday for approval.
   Grosz announced last month he intends to resign as premier by the
end of December in order to concentrate on his position as Communist
Party chief. He was appointed to the post in May and replaced
longtime leader Janos Kadar.
   Among those who have been considered top contenders for premier
were Miklos Nemeth, Central Committee secretary for economic
affairs, and reformists Rezso Nyers and Imre Pozsgay.
   Nemeth, 40, the youngest member of the ruling Politburo,
reportedly is the preferred choice of Grosz.
   Since becoming premier in June 1987, Grosz has set Hungary on a
course of economic reform aimed at reducing its $17 billion foreign
debt.
   Nemeth, like Grosz, reportedly advocates political and economic
changes aimed at developing a market economy and closer ties to the
European Economic Community. He also, however, advocates stringent
austerity measures to counter the $17 billion foreign debt.
   Last month, Parliament adopted legislation to ease the flow of
hard currency into the country and loosen restrictions on
establishing joint ventures with foreign companies.
   On Jan. 1, Hungary became the East European nation to introduce
personal income and value-added taxes, but they have contributed to
the 18 percent annual inflation rate and a drop in personal
consumption.
   Hungarian and Western analysts say the new premier must be able
to rally the country's 10.6 million people as dissatisfaction grows
with inflation, unemployment and sinking living standards.
   Nyers, considered the father of Hungary's economic reforms of
1968, also advocates political and economic reforms within the
framework of a socialistic society.
   Nyers was removed from the ruling Politburo in 1974 after his
economic reforms stalled and was re-appointed to the ruling body in
May.
   Pozsgay, a champion of political pluralism, gained wide
popularity as head of the Patriotic People's Front, an umbrella
organization for officially recognized cultural, intellectual and
trade union groups. He was named to the Politburo in May.
   Other names mentioned as possible candidates for premeir were
Budapest Mayor Pal Ivanyi and Ilona Tatai, head of the Taurus rubber
factory.
</TEXT>
