<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Nielsens     11-22 0694</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nielsens,0712</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ABC's `War and Remembrance' Draws Disappointing Ratings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ABC's 30-hour series ``War and Remembrance''
is not living up to forecasts that it would dominate the Nielsen
ratings, trailing regular series for the week ending Nov. 20.
   Three NBC comedies took the top spots and NBC won the week. One
episode of ``War and Remembrance'' made the Top 10, placing 10th.
   The first 18 hours of the World War II epic based on Herman
Wouk's book was widely acclaimed by critics, but fell in the A.C.
Nielsen Co. ratings after its opening night. The first episode was
in fourth place the week before.
   ``War and Remembrance'' is the sequel to ``The Winds of War,''
which got a 38.6 rating and a 53 share over 18 hours in 1983. The
final 12 hours of ``War and Remembrance'' is not expected to be
telecast until May.
   ABC won't comment on the ratings until the final episode of the
first 18 hours is telecast this week, according to Bob Wright, a
vice president for public relations.
   The fate of ``War and Remembrance'' does not bode well for longer
miniseries. The miniseries cost $104 million to make, and even prior
to the disappointing ratings ABC had forecast a loss of $20 million.
   NBC, although it had predicted victory for ``War and
Remembrance,'' won the week by counterprogramming and with vigorous
promotion campaign against the ABC miniseries. ABC placed second for
the week.
   The three NBC comedy shows at the top of the ratings were ``The
Cosby Show,'' ``A Different World'' and ``The Golden Girls.''
   ``Our calculated plan of youth-oriented counterprogramming,
coupled with aggressive and creative promotion, had the absolute
right effect with the viewing audience,'' said Brandon Tartikoff,
president of NBC Entertainment. ``I'm happy NBC has kept its
prime-time win streak alive in the heart of the November sweeps.''
   ABC reportedly told its advertisers the first 18 hours of ``War
and Remembrance'' would get an average rating of 20.2. Only the
opening episode has exceeded that so far with 21.8. The next highest
rated episode, Part III, had a rating of 19.9 and a 31 share. Two
more chapters were to be telecast this week.
   Here are the rankings, ratings and shares for three other
episodes telecast this week: Part II, in 11th place, 19.0 rating, 29
share; Part V, 17th place, 17.0, 26; Part IV, tied for 18th place
with NBC's ``Unsolved Mysteries,'' 16.8, 25.
   The fifth episode beat Vanna White's debut as an actress in the
NBC Sunday movie, ``Goddess of Love,'' which came in 20th.
   NBC won the week with an average rating of 15.8. ABC was second
with 14.9 and CBS was third with 12.4.
   Each ratings point equals 904,000 homes with television. The
share is a percentage of the sets in use.
   NBC remained in the lead for the season to date with an average
of 15.5. ABC was second with 13.8 and CBS third with 12.3. NBC also
had a good lead in the Nielsens for the November sweeps. The
ratings: NBC 15.4, ABC 13.6 and CBS 12.2.
   Here are the shows in the Top 10: ``The Cosby Show,'' ``A
Different World,'' ``The Golden Girls,'' ``60 Minutes,'' CBS;
``Cheers'' and ``Empty Nest,'' both NBC; ``Growing Pains,'' ABC;
``Murder, She Wrote,'' CBS; NBC Monday Night Movie, ``Too Good To Be
True,'' NBC; ``War and Remembrance,'' Part III, ABC.
   Fox Broadcasting's ``Married ... With Children'' scored the
highest prime-time rating in the history of the fledgling fourth
network. It got a 10.0 rating and a 14 share. Immediately behind it
was Fox's ``America's Most Wanted.'' Both shows did better than 12
series from CBS and ABC.
   ABC won the week for its ``ABC World News Tonight,'' which had an
11.3 rating. ABC premiered a nightly segment last week called
``American Agenda.'' ``The CBS Evening News'' was second with an
11.2 rating and ``The NBC Nightly News'' was third with 10.5.
   The lowest-rated show other than a Fox show was CBS' ``Simon &
Simon.'' The bottom five were CBS' ``High Risk,'' CBS' ``Dirty
Dancing,'' ABC's ``Knightwatch,'' CBS' ``Raising Miranda'' and CBS'
``Simon & Simon.''
</TEXT>
