<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Chess     11-22 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chess,0477</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Lead United States with Unfinished Game Remaining</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALONICA, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union defeated the United
States in the ninth round of the Chess Olympiad on Tuesday, but the
United States is likely to win an unfinished game.
   The Soviet Union, with 27 points out of 35 and one adjourned
game, has amassed a 3{ point lead. England, who defeated Sweden 3-1,
are placed second with 23{ points out of 36.
   A win scores one point and a draw a half.
   The first Soviet victory over the United States came on board
one, when world champion Garri Kasparov, playing white, defeated
top-ranked Yasser Seirawan of Seattle.
   Kasparov has scored a remarkable six wins here, conceding only
one draw. ``I'm a profesional and I'm doing my job,'' Kasparov said
after his victory.
   On board two, U.S. grandmaster Boris Gulko lost to former world
champion Anatoly Karpov. Gulko, who emigrated from the Soviet Union
in 1986 after a seven-year campaign for an exit visa, is
``Grandmaster in Residence'' at Harvard University.
   On board three Joel Benjamin of the New York City borough of
Queens, drew with Soviet Grandmaster Artur Yusupov.
   On the fourth board, however, Nick de Firmian of Berkeley,
Calif., built a strong advantage against Alexander Beliavsky. When
play was adjourned after six hours, de Firmian said he couldn't see
any way for Beliavsky to stave off defeat.
   The adjourned games will be completed Wednesday morning with the
10th round on Wednesday evening.
   While the United States did not repeat its celebrated victory
over the Soviets in the 1986 Olympiad, a win in the adjourned game
will push it into a three-way tie for third.
   Hungary and East Germany share third place with 23 points. The
Hungarians defeated East Germany 2{-1{.
   England, the second seeds, moved into the silver medal position
following victories from Nigel Short, the third ranked player in the
world, and Jonathan Speelman.
   The Philippines, seeded only 29th before the event, continued to
outstrip higher-ranked opposition and moved into fifth equal
position. They lead the Netherlands 2-1 with one game yet to finish.
   In the separate womens championship, Hungary has taken the lead
with 21.5 points out of 27. Their team includes a brilliant trio of
three Polgar sisters, who reject segregated competitions, but agreed
to play here in their first women-only event in a bid to end a run
of Soviet gold medals.
   But the Soviet Union, with 21 points and a favorable adjourned
game against Greece, are expected to regain the lead before the
start of the 10th round.
   The Olympiad, a biennial world team championship, is organized by
the 127-member World Chess Federation and features teams
representing 106 nations.
   The 14-round contest is scheduled to end Nov. 29.
</TEXT>
