<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-88 1927EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iraq-Scandal     11-22 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iraq-Scandal,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Committee Formed to Investigate Hussein's Son</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq's justice minister Tuesday appointed
three judges to investigate Iraqi President Saddam Hussein's eldest
son, Odai, for killing a presidential bodyguard last month, the
Iraqi News Agency reported.
   In his decree, Minister Akram Abdul Qader Douri also instructed
Public Prosecutor Dari Khalil Mahmoud to lead the prosecution, the
agency said in a dispatch monitored in Nicosia.
   It published the text of a letter which it said the minister sent
Tuesday to Hussein, assuring him that ``justice will take its
course.''
   Douri addressed Hussein as ``the man of great justice.'' But he
cautioned: ``Allow me, Mr. President, to say that my worry is that
you come down too harshly on your son because of your firm
commitment to justice.''
   In a letter carried by state media Monday, Hussein ordered Douri
to investigate his son's killing of Kamel Hana Gegeo.
   Hussein said it took place the night of Oct. 18 when Gegeo, a
trusted Christian bodyguard, was shooting his gun in a private villa
near the presidential palace.
   In an ensuing altercation after Gegeo refused to stop, Odai hit
him over the head with a bat. Gegeo died later in the hospital.
   Odai, 25, is the oldest of five children. Sources in Nicosia said
he has the reputation of a playboy, a regular denizen of Baghdad
nightclubs and discotheques.
   He was known to jaunt to a vacation resort outside Baghdad in his
helicopter _ taking his sports car along to drive while he was
there, they said.
   The sources, who are frequent travelers to Baghdad who requested
anonymity, said Odai fled to Amman, Jordan, after the shooting. They
said King Hussein of Jordan interceded and tried to reconcile father
and son, bringing Odai back to Iraq.
   The Iraqi leader said in his letter that his son has tried to
commit suicide three times, starting when he heard Gegeo had died.
   The bodyguard, believed to be in his 20s, was the son of the
president's male cook and the governess that raised his three
daughters, the Nicosia sources said.
   Odai resigned as head of Iraq's Olympic Committee after the
incident but retained his position as head of the board of Saddam
University, established earlier this year. His appointment at such a
young age was not popular, the sources said.
   The INA report did not specify when Odai's case will be reviewed.
It said the deputy president of the Cassation Court, Judge
Abdel-Wahab Hussein, was appointed chief of the committee that
includes Judge Abdel-Sattar Mohammed Bazarkan, also a member of the
Cassation Court's presidency, and Judge Akram Ahmed Khodar, chief of
Baghdad's Court of Appeal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
