<HEAD>Engineering School Asks Alumni For Donations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND FORKS, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The University of North Dakota School of
Engineering and Mines has written to 4,000 alumni seeking
contributions to help give the faculty a raise, the school's dean
said.
   ``I need your help!'' Engineering Dean Alan Fletcher says in the
appeal. ``We do not have the resources to adequately pay engineering
faculty. The future of the Engineering School is at stake.''
   The letters ask 4,000 alumni to contribute $100 a year for the
next 10 years in an effort to raise money for the school's 32
faculty members.
   The letter says the summer drought and low energy prices means
``little or no hope'' for salary increases from the 1989 Legislature.
   Fletcher said Monday that engineering salaries average $34,900 at
the university, compared with the national average of $48,000.
   Most of the engineering faculty members have taught at the
university 20 years or more, but their will begin to wane if
salaries don't go up, he said.
   ``The thing we're concerned about is not the past, but the
future,'' Fletcher said.
