<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland     11-22 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Director Andrzej Wajda Offers Services for TV Debate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Renowned filmmaker Andrzej Wajda has
offered his services for a proposed TV debate between Solidarity
leader Lech Walesa and the head of the official trade union alliance.
   Wajda, in a letter to Walesa made public by Solidarity on
Tuesday, suggested that he and his crew record the debate as a
safeguard to prevent its material from being distorted on state-run
television.
   He also proposed the setting up of equivalent camera angles for
Walesa and his debate opponent, Alfred Miodowicz, the Politburo
member who leads the All-Poland Trade Union Alliance.
   The alliance was set up to replace Solidarity when the East
bloc's first independent union movement was banned under martial law
six years ago.
   ``Let me explain why I consider such safeguards necessary,''
Wajda said in the letter dated Friday. ``Television in recent years
has been the main source of disinformation about the Solidarity
chairman. Why should it suddenly change its conduct?''
   Wajda's films include ``Man of Iron,'' an admiring look at the
rise of Solidarity in 1980 in which Walesa appeared briefly, and
``Man of Marble,'' about the disillusionment with the Stalinist
system of a worker-hero of the 1950s.
   Miodowicz proposed the debate covering trade union issues in the
Communist Party paper Trybuna Ludu on Nov. 15. Walesa tentatively
has agreed it should be held Nov. 30.
   It would be the first time Walesa has been given such an
opportunity to present his stands on state-run television. Advisers
to Walesa have proposed holding the debate in the Lenin Shipyard in
Gdansk.
   Walesa advocates making Solidarity legal again and allowing the
existence of more than one union in a plant. Miodowicz says
Solidarity supporters should join his union federation and express
opinions through it.
</TEXT>
