<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     11-22 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Week of Violence Kills 20 People</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New violence blamed on anti-government
Sinhalese extremists in the south has claimed the lives of at least
20 people in the past week, authorities said Tuesday.
   Gunmen belonging to the People's Liberation Front, a radical
Sinhalese group, ambushed a police jeep in the village of Hiniduma,
about 50 miles south of the capital, said a police spokesman. Two
officers died and three were wounded, said the spokesman, who
demanded anonymity.
   Suspected Tamil rebels fighting the Sinhalese killed two Indian
peacekeeping soldiers and injured three others, said officials, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The dates of the attacks were not given.
   The People's Liberation Front, a radical Sinhalese group that has
vowed to disrupt next month's presidential elections, has been
blamed for more than 550 political killings in the past 15 months.
   The group is demanding the resignation of President Junius R.
Jayewardene for his peace overtures to Tamil guerrillas, who have
waged a five-year struggle for a homeland in the northeast.
   The Sinhalese extremists contend a peace accord Jayewardene
signed on July 29, 1987, makes too many concessions to the Tamils.
They also say the 47,000 Indian soldiers deployed to disarm the
guerrillas are violating this island nation's sovereignty.
   On Tuesday, a powerful time bomb exploded on a bridge over the
Kelani River north of Colombo as a train carrying four railroad
workers approached, but no one was injured, the officials said.
   The train derailed about 25 yards before the bridge. The 5:45
a.m. explosion was heard six miles away in the center of Colombo,
police said.
   The train was on its way to Mirigama, about 30 miles northeast of
Colombo, to pick up commuters who work in the capital.
   On Monday in the southern village of Angunakolpelessa, Sinhalese
radicals shot and killed a businessman believed to be a supporter of
the governing United National Party. The four gunmen were killed as
they tried to escape, police said.
   Eight other government supporters were killed in separate
incidents Monday in southern villages, authorities said.
   They said seven suspected Sinhalese extremists were shot and
killed by unidentified attackers Monday night in Hambantota
district, about 105 miles southeast of Colombo.
   The Sinhalese comprise 75 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million
people, while the Tamils make up 18 percent of the population and
say they are discriminateed against by the Sinhalese-dominated
government.
   More than 8,500 people, mostly Sinhalese, have been killed since
the Tamil rebellion began in 1983.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
