<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia     11-22 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia,0540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Serbs, Albanians Verbally Clash At Belgrade Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IVAN STEFANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Serb and ethnic Albanian officials
traded accusations Tuesday over unrest in the tense southern
province of Kosovo and what sparked the biggest protests there in
more than 40 years.
   Kosovo was reported calm, but authorities braced for more small,
sporadic protests later.
   On Monday, about 7,000 people defied threats of a crackdown on
demonstrations which erupted last Thursday after two ethnic Albanian
leaders resigned under Serbian pressure. Protesters swelled to
100,000 on Saturday.
   Strong pressure was applied to keep the province calm Monday.
Hundreds of Communist Party activists were dispatched to schools,
homes and factories throughout the backward province to urge
students and workers to stay off the streets.
   But Belgrade newspapers attacked ethnic Albanian leaders Tuesday
for failing to control the unrest.
   Serbian speakers at a Serbian Communist Party conference followed
the lead of party chief Slobodan Milosevic in accusing Kosovo's
ethnic Albanian majority of fomenting ``counterrevolution.''
   In Kosovo, a senior ethnic Albanian official said on condition of
anonymity that he feared renewed unrest could erupt on a massive
scale only if inflammatory statements were made at the conference or
by Belgrade media.
   Otherwise, he likened expected unrest to ``small tremors''
compared to the weekend's ``big earthquake.''
   At the Belgrade conference, delegate Tomislav Sekulic branded the
Kosovo protests outright ``anti-Serbian.''
   Demonstrators had seemed careful, however, not to chant
anti-Serbian slogans, shouting instead ``Yugoslavia! Yugoslavia!''
and ``Brotherhood! Unity!''
   Ethnic Albanian delegates appealed to Serbs not to judge hastily.
   ``What is happening now has nothing to do with the events of
1981,'' said delegate Sevdi Choroli.
   In 1981, both ethnic Albanian and Serbian communist leaders said
riots in which at least nine people died were sparked by 40,000
ethnic Albanians demanding their own republic in Kosovo.
   That would give the ethnic Albanian majority the right to secede
from the Yugoslav federation. Serbs feel strongly about their
ancient heartland of Kosovo and charge ethnic Albanians aim to
secede and unite with neighboring Albania.
   The recent unrest, however, appears to be a response to
Milosevic's campaign to make the Serbian language mandatory in the
judiciary, policing and education in Kosovo and to get more control
over the province.
   Kosovo adminstratively is part of Serbia but won broad autonomy
under the 1974 constitution, which Yugoslav leaders now are trying
to change so they can implement reforms to ease an unprecedented
economic crisis.
   The amendments have been approved by all six republics and both
provinces.
   In Albania, the leader Ramiz Alia criticized Yugoslavia for a
policy of alleged discrimination against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo,
but the absence of a strident attack signaled his interest in normal
relations.
   Alia pointedly avoided any reference to the demonstrations, but
vaguely referred to ``the great difficulties ... the turbulent
political situation and the national feuds'' in Yugoslavia.
   Restraint was also clear in the following comment: ``Socialist
Albania is developing successfully relations of good neighborhood
with Greece and Turkey, with Bulgaria and Romania, and is making
efforts to create the same positive atmosphere in its relations with
Yugoslavia.''
</TEXT>
