<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DriveFails     11-22 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drive Fails,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thanksgiving Food Drive Fails in Maryland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donations to a Thanksgiving food drive in
Maryland fell 70 percent this year, leaving thousands of needy
people facing bleak prospects for their holiday meal.
   The Maryland Food Bank's pre-Thanksgiving Bags of Plenty program
collected 20,000 bags of non-perishable goods last year. As of
Monday, only 5,500 bags of food had been collected, and a total of
7,000 were expected by Tuesday, when the program was to end.
   As a result, thousands of people who received food baskets last
year will not get them this year. Food Bank Director Bill Ewing
estimated that 30,000 to 40,000 people will benefit from this year's
drive, compared with 125,000 last year.
   ``I can't even imagine it being any worse,'' Ewing said.
   ``One woman was in tears,'' Erselle Datcher, a food bank worker,
said Monday after making dozens of phone calls to inform church,
shelter and senior center workers that the program failed this year.
``She runs a small church that doesn't have much money. She wasn't
able to get any turkeys or chickens, so she just purchased some
turkey wings. And we're not going to be able to help her fill her 40
baskets the way we'd like to.''
   Ewing had no explanation for why the food drive failed just weeks
after the United Way exceeded its fund-raising goal. ``Maybe our
advertising was too cutesy _ `stuff a bag this year' _ but it
shouldn't account for a 70 percent drop-off,'' Ewing said.
   The drive has now been extended through Sunday, with an eye
toward Christmas.
   ``We seem to have blown it for Thanksgiving. Any response we get
over the next few days we'll store and make available for a
Christmas basket,'' he said.
</TEXT>
