<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Hotdogs-Japan     11-22 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hotdogs-Japan,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Acquire Taste for Hotdogs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese consumers have a growing appetite for
hotdogs, and U.S. hotdog producers are encountering fierce
competition from Australia, Mexico and several other countries for a
share of the market, an the Agriculture Department said Tuesday.
   Total sausage sales in Japan, made up mostly of frankfurters and
weiners, have grown 26 percent in the last three years, the report
said. And imports more than doubled.
   Shipments by U.S. processors in 1987 totaled 699 metric tons,
representing 28 percent of Japan's total sausage imports, the report
said.
   Other competitors include: Australia, with a 22 percent of the
1987 Japanese sausage imports; Mexico, 15 percent; Taiwan, 9
percent; Denmark, 6 percent; Netherlands, 5 percent; West Germany, 5
percent; and others, 10 percent.
   ``Annual per capita consumption of sausage rose from 3.76 pounds
in 1983 to 4.83 pounds in 1987, fueled by a mushrooming demand for
Western-style meats and menus,'' said the report in Foreign
Agriculture magazine.
   Sausage as a main breakfast item is less common in Japan than in
the United States but this main change soon.
   ``McDonald's has introduced a sausage breakfast menu, and many
Western-style restaurants serve sausage for dinner,'' the report
said. Consumers tend to adopt such menus at home over time.''
</TEXT>
