<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NoChildren     11-22 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-No Children,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No-Children Condo Plans To Evict 9-Year-Old</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 9-year-old girl who has been
living in her father's adults-only condominium since her mother's
fatal cancer was diagnosed has until after the holiday season to
move out, the condo's attorney said Tuesday.
   Douglas Neway, representing the Viewpoint Condominium board of
directors, said Jamie Swartz must be out by Jan. 10. A letter he
sent to her family said they must show, by providing names of
real-estate brokers and other evidence, a good-faith effort in the
meantime to sell their condo unit.
   ``If the child is still in residence at the unit upon the
expiration of this latest extension, the Board of Directors will
have no choice but to ... file a lawsuit seeking an injunction
preventing the further violation'' of condominium rules, the letter
said.
   Jamie's father and stepmother, who own the condominium, say they
have been unable to sell the condo and cannot afford to move into
another home while still paying the mortgage on it.
   The extension was a relief to the family, but the decision will
cast a pall over their holidays, said Jill Swartz, Jamie's
stepmother.
   ``The holidays are not actually the time that people are actively
out looking for homes,'' she said. ``I think the time element is
working against us.''
   Jamie had moved in temporarily in April after her mother, Maye
Swartz, was hospitalized and later diagnosed as having cancer.
   The condominium association agreed in July to allow Jamie to stay
at the apartment while her mother underwent chemotherapy, but Maye
Swartz died in September. It had granted one extension before the
latest threatened eviction.
   Jill Swartz received a letter from the condominium association
Nov. 10 saying it would seek an injunction to force Jamie out.
   Neway said in a telephone interview that he and condo directors
realized some would say they sound hard-hearted.
   ``I'll admit that this is a great story,'' Neway said. ``However,
as I've tried to make clear, the condominium board has an obligation
to the entire community.''
   A federal open-housing bill that takes effect in March is
designed to protect families against discrimination in housing.
Under the law, buildings that are ``adult only'' could exclude
children only if the managers or owners adopted a policy to rent or
sell to the elderly only.
</TEXT>
