<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WildflowerDispute     11-22 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wildflower Dispute,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Debate Results In Revised Weed Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KALAMAZOO, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A four-month dispute over whether a
garden of cultivated weeds constitutes an eyesore or a living work
of art has resulted in a new weed ordinance for this southern
Michigan city.
   That means Ladislav Hanka won't have to take a lawn mower to the
wildflower meadow in his front yard _ to the dismay of his next-door
neighbor.
   Hanka protested an order from the city in July to mow the tall
weeds in his yard, claiming they are part of a wildflower garden he
and his wife began nurturing when they moved to their home in July
1987.
   Kalamazoo city commissioners sided with Hanka on Monday night and
adopted a revised weed ordinance that allows residents to grow weeds
up to 18 inches high.
   Hanka said the commission's action confirmed a resident's right
to deviate from the traditional English-style lawn when cutting
grass.
   ``It's really facing facts and what ... is a coming trend in the
country,'' said Hanka, who grows Queen Anne's lace and other tall
wildflowers in his garden.
   Opponents, including the Vine Neighborhood Association, contend
the revised leaves the law open to potential abuse by negligent
property owners.
   ``We have to be sensitive to others in our neighborhood and the
expectations they had about the appearance of their surroundings
when they made their decision to live in the city,'' said City
Commissioner Bruce Martin, who voted against the amended ordinance.
   Scott Kemple, Hanka's next-door neighbor, said the revised
ordinance is too vague.
   ``Essentially, he could do anything he wants to do over there and
call it a meadow,'' Kemple said.
</TEXT>
