<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-USJews     11-22 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-US Jews,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shamir Makes No Promises on `Who Is A Jew' Proposal</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel-Politics, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Canadian Jewish leaders said Tuesday
that Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir agreed to consult with them on
the proposed ``Who is a Jew'' amendment but will not move to block
the controversial bill.
   ``We have received no assurances, nothing whatsoever,'' Jewish
Agency chairman Mendel Kaplan said after a meeting with Shamir.
   The proposed legislation would modify Israel's Law of Return,
giving Orthodox rabbis exclusive authority to approve conversions to
Judaism. Jewish converts would be granted automatic Israeli
citizenship only if converted by Orthodox rabbis.
   Most American and Canadian Jews are members of the Reform and
Conservative movements and see the amendment as a threat to their
legitimacy as Jews.
   The amendment has become a bargaining chip in forming Israel's
next government.
   The 12 delegates said Shamir agreed to set up a joint committee
with the Jewish Agency to air the views of North American Jews on
the issue.
   ``It's a serious matter. There are so many people who feel that
with a change in the Law of Return, millions of Jews would be
disenfrachised,'' said Walter Hess, executive vice president of the
Canadian branch of the United Israel Appeal.
   Shoshana Cardin, chairman of the U.S.-Canadian coalition on ``Who
is a Jew,'' said: ``There is a tremendous sense of pain, anguish and
rejection. There is a sense of being subjected to second-class
Jewishness.''
   Four ultra-Orthodox religious parties have demanded passage of
the ``Who is a Jew'' amendment in exchange for supporting Shamir's
right-wing Likud bloc in forming a coalition government. Shamir has
pledged to back passage.
   ``Mr. Shamir has an ongoing commitment to the religious parties
as he tries to forge a government,'' Ms. Cardin told reporters. ``He
said he'll see if there's a way to remove this as a burning issue of
the day.''
   But Shamir aide Yossi Ahimeir said Shamir told the Jewish leaders
he would stick to his promise to the religious parties.
   ``He explained to them that the matter was a formal, internal
Israeli matter that should not create a rift or misunderstanding
with diaspora Jewry,'' Ahimeir said.
   In a separate meeting Tuesday, Foreign Minister Shimon Peres
assured the U.S. and Canadian delegation his left-leaning Labor
Party would vote against passage.
   Meir Shitrit, a Likud supporter and treasurer of the Jewish
Agency in Israel, said he feared passage could cost the agency $100
million in lost contributions next year.
   The visiting leaders said the United Jewish Appeal in the United
States raised about $300 million for Israel last year. The Canadian
contribution was estimated at about $25 million.
   Shamir must consider forming a coaltion government because Nov. 1
elections to the 120-seat Knesset, or parliament, gave Likud 40
seats and Labor 39. The rest went to leftist, rightist and religious
parties.
</TEXT>
