<1ST_LINE>r i AM-OPEC 1stLd-Writethru a0673 11-22 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-OPEC, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0673,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Soar, Then Slip Back in Confusion over Progress</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout with ministers backing away on chances for
agreement; longer version moved on financial wires</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices soared Tuesday after OPEC
ministers raised hopes the cartel might be near agreement on
curtailing production, but the market retreated when ministers
backed away from their optimism.
   The price swings centered around comments by Iranian Oil Minister
Gholamreza Aghazadeh, who said early in the day an agreement was
possible but then made a dramatic about-face.
   ``I'm ready to be here for several days,'' he said after emerging
from a closed-door meeting with other ministers late in the day.
   ``There has been no progress,'' said a senior member of an OPEC
delegation, who agreed to talk about the negotiations only if he was
not identified.
   The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries has been trying
to devise a new plan to limit the cartel's output, but it has been
snagged by a dispute over whether Iraq should have a quota equal to
that of Iran.
   Oil prices have been running nearly 25 percent below OPEC's
benchmark of $18 a barrel because of an oversupply of oil on the
world market.
   Aghazadeh's early optimistic comment electrified the oil markets,
sending the price of the January contract for West Texas
Intermediate crude soaring $1.42 a barrel on the New York Mercantile
Exchange. But when he changed his tone, the January contract fell
back and ended the day up 88 cents at $13.86.
   Ecuador's energy minister, Diego Tamariz, said the ministers from
OPEC's 13 member nations would resume formal talks Wednesday
afternoon.
   The ministers opened their winter conference Monday but adjourned
after 90 minutes so members could meet privately to try to resolve
the dispute between Iraq and Iran, who ended an 8-year war in August.
   Iraq wants the same quota in any new cartel accord as Iran, but
Aghazadeh has refused.
   ``I would never concede to parity,'' he told reporters after
meeting for nearly an hour with ministers from Nigeria, Indonesia,
Venezuela and Algeria.
   Issam Abdul Raheem al-Chalabi, the Iraq oil minister, was in the
hotel at the same time but apparently was not part of the
discussions with Aghazadeh.
   Earlier in the day, Aghazadeh had told reporters, ``I think we
can reach an agreement.''
   That remark was bolstered by an optimistic comment the Iraqi oil
minister, Issam Abdul Raheem al-Chalabi: ``We're working on an
agreement that will settle all the problems, including that of Iraq
and Iran.''
   OPEC President Rilwanu Lukman, who also is Nigeria's oil
minister, said the cartel's regular winter meeting would ``not end
without an agreement.''
   Those positive comments caught the oil markets by surprise and
triggered the runup in price, analysts said.
</TEXT>
