<1ST_LINE>r w AM-GasStudy     11-22 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gas Study,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Calls For New Production Incentives For Natural Gas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A modest package of natural gas production and
use incentives could more than pay for itself in benefits to the
economy, according to a study released Tuesday by two former Energy
Department officials.
   The former officials, William Martin and Scott Campbell, said
their proposals could boost the gross national product by $9 billion
annually by 1995 and $29 billion by 2010, and increase tax revenues
$1.4 billion a year within two years of enactment.
   The principal costs of their package would be $350 million lost
annual government revenue through a 10 percent tax credit for
drilling of both exploratory wells and wells aimed at finding
pockets of by-passed gas in old reservoirs.
   Certain other incentives, such as delaying royalty payments on
government lands, could cost an additional $50 million a year, they
said. They also called for spending $100 million a year for
increased research in geology.
   Martin, former deputy secretary, and Campbell, former director of
the department's Office of Policy, Planning and Analysis, resigned
their positions in the fall to join the presidential campaign of
Vice President George Bush.
   Both Bush and his unsuccessful Democratic opponent, Michael
Dukakis, said during the campaign they would make increased use of
natural gas the centerpiece of their energy policies.
   Campbell said the study was not aimed at the Bush transition team
or anyone in particular, but rather ``the marketplace of ideas.''
   Using computer models of the economy in a study paid for by
several gas companies, Martin and Campbell sketched two futures _
one a ``business as usual'' scenario and the other incorporating
their proposals. They assumed that the economy will grow at 2.5
percent per year and overall energy use will grow at slightly less
than 1 percent per year.
   Their proposals called for requiring urban buses to switch to gas
or other clean-burning fuels for the clean-air benefits those fuels
would bring, and use of gas by 5 percent of all cars in 2010. It
also calls for doubling the use of gas by electric utilities, in
part through modifications to clean air legislation that would
permit its intermittent use to reduce pollution; streamlined
procedures for building new gas pipelines and more use of gas to
power air large commercial air conditioners.
   They assumed energy prices would rise in the 1990s to about $4.50
per thousand cubic feet of gas and about $37.50 a barrel for oil
compared with about $1.50 per thousand cubic feet and $14 a barrel
today.
   Under the proposals, gas use would be 24.1 trillion cubic feet in
2010 compared with 18.2 trillion cubic feet under the ``business as
usual'' scenario and 17.7 trillion cubic feet last year. About 16
percent of the gas would be imported from Canada, Mexico, Algeria
and possibly others compared with about 5 percent from Canada last
year.
   Imported oil would be 10.9 million barrels a day or 67 percent of
U.S. consumption vs. 12.5 million barrels a day and 72 percent under
the ``business as usual'' forecast and about 5.9 million barrels a
day and 38 percent last year.
   Coal use would be reduced to 1,150 tons from 1,330 tons in the
``business as usual'' projection, but still 42 percent above last
year's 810 million tons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
