<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FreeTrade     11-22 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Free Trade,0588</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Economist: Border Cities Like Detroit Could Profit From Canadian
Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Canada, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the largest metropolitan area on the
U.S.-Canadian border, Detroit could evolve as a commercial center
under the free trade agreement that got a boost when Conservatives
won Canada's election, an economist said Tuesday.
   Business leaders in Michigan envision a developing
Chicago-to-Toronto trade area with Detroit in the middle, a center
for trade-related accounting, brokerage and other services.
   ``I would expect that there will be an increase in trade and
trade-related services. Consultants and other service providers in
Detroit will have access to the vast growing market in Ontario, and
by the same token Canadians will have better access to Michigan
markets,'' said Wayne State University economist David Verway, who
conducted a free trade impact analysis for the Greater Detroit
Chamber of Commerce.
   ``It will represent a brand new market for small businesses that
are able to see that potential, small consultants, architects,
people in the construction trades,'' he said.
   After Monday's victory, Canadian Conservatives are expected to
push the free trade agreement through Parliament next month.
   In 10 years, the pact would phase out tariffs on the 22 percent
of Canadian exports still subject to United States duties and on the
35 percent of U.S. exports still subject to Canadian duties.
   The immediate impact on the annual $25.7 billion in trade between
Canada and Michigan will be slight. Eighty percent of that trade
already moves duty free because of the Autopact, which lets vehicle
manufacturers ship new vehicles and parts across the border without
tariffs.
   But business leaders are hopeful the free trade agreement will
hold commercial benefits for border states like Michigan and cities
like Buffalo, N.Y., located 90 miles to the south of Toronto.
   Several developers have proposed trade centers that would help
alleviate congestion on the International Peace Bridge, a three-lane
bridge that connects Buffalo with Fort Erie, Ontario.
   On Tuesday, developers Robert and Peter Elia presented more
detailed plans for their proposed $200 million trade center near the
Peace Bridge. The complex would contain a 20-story office building,
two 15-story office buildings, an apartment-hotel and a huge
open-air truck processing facility. Financing and a completion date
have not been set.
   In far northern Michigan, Sault Ste. Marie, Mich., population
15,000, and Sault Ste. Marie, Ont., population 85,000, across the
St. Marys River, have been preparing for the agreement, Francis
Mansfield said.
   Mansfield, executive director of the Sault Ste. Marie, Mich.,
Chamber of Commerce, said the economic development commissions of
the two cities have been holding joint committee meetings.
   Robert Patterson, director of the Industrial Development Corp. of
Port Huron, Mich., said the trade agreement will facilitate
development in Michigan linked to Ontario's largest petrochemical
complex, in Sarnia, across the St. Clair River.
   Detroit Molded Plastics Co. already is building an area plant
that will use feedstocks from the Sarnia complex and supply material
for automakers in Detroit, one hour's drive to the south, and Flint,
one hour to the west.
   Patterson said the area has plants owned by Canadian companies,
also supplying the automakers with springs, door locks and the like.
``We have five or six Canadian companies located here now and we're
looking for more in the future,'' he said.
   The United States and Canada are the world's largest trading
partners, with two-way trade expected to reach $150 billion this
year.
</TEXT>
