<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Parliament, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0702,0782</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gov't Announces Formal Controls on MI5, New IRA Crackdown</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lede to Clarify that requirement covers any candidate
running for elected office. SUBS grafs 13-16 pvs `For Northern
Ireland...the election campaign.' with 5 grafs to conform. PICKS up
17th pvs: ``Further repression... </NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LON14</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government announced plans Tuesday to establish
controls on its secret service MI5, sell off billions of dollars of
state utilities, and require any political candidate in Northern
Ireland to renounce violence.
   The measures were part of a far-reaching legislative program for
the next year _ the 10th written by Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher's Conservative government _ read aloud by Queen Elizabeth
II at the glittering opening of Parliament.
   Despite immediate protests from the opposition and from pro-IRA
or moderate Roman Catholic groups in Northern Ireland, most of the
measures were virtually certain of passage by the 650-member House
of Commons, where Mrs. Thatcher has a huge 101-seat majority.
   By tradition, Mrs. Thatcher and other members of the House of
Commons stood at the back entrance to the unelected House of Lords
while the queen, in long white gown and jeweled crown, announced the
program to rows of ermine-robed peers and diplomats.
   ``A bill will be introduced to put the security service on a
statutory basis,'' said the queen, announcing that formal operating
rules will be drawn up for the first time for MI5.
   But Mrs. Thatcher later made it clear the shadowy service, which
deals with domestic security, will remain accountable only to
Cabinet officials and not Parliament as critics have demanded. MI5
currently reports to a Cabinet subcommittee.
   Officials said the measures would not apply to MI6, Britain's
other secret service agency, which gathers intelligence from abroad.
   Some analysts predicted the move will tighten agents' lifelong
secrecy oaths following the government's failed attempt through
courts in several countries to suppress ``Spycatcher,'' the memoirs
of retired agent Peter Wright.
   Wright claimed in his book that MI5 tried to destabilize the
1970s left-of-center Labor Party government, bugged foreign
embassies and plotted to assassinate Egyptian President Gamal Abdul
Nasser.
   The proposed new laws include a liberalization of the 1911
Official Secrets Act, although critics note the proposals still
would not allow civil servants who leak unauthorized documents to
argue they acted in the public interest.
   The 16 proposed bills included Mrs. Thatcher's plans to sell off
the state-owned water and electricity utilities.
   The sales, denounced by the opposition Labor Party, are the
biggest and most controversial of Mrs. Thatcher's massive
privatization program and will raise an estimated $55 billion.
   For Northern Ireland, where sectarian violence has been met by
increasingly controversial measures by the Thatcher government, any
candidate running for any elected political office would have to
sign an oath rejecting violence. Under the measure, such candidates
could be sued by other politicians _ Protestant opponents _ or
members of the public, and banned from office.
   The mainly Roman Catholic Irish Republican Army is fighting to
end British rule of the Protestant-dominated province.
   ``The government is determined never to give in to the
terrorist,'' Mrs. Thatcher declared later in the Commons, launching
a six-day debate on the queen's speech.
   Officials said despite the law providing for the proposed
non-violence pledge _ which is aimed at members of the outlawed
IRA's legal political front, Sinn Fein _ candidates can say what
they like during the election campaign.
   Sinn Fein has 59 elected members of local councils and one member
of the House of Commons, Gerry Adams.
   ``Further repression, the increasing erosion of our few remaining
civil liberties and British efforts to marginalize Sinn Fein are not
the way to resolve the conflict,'' said Sinn Fein spokesman Danny
Morrison.
   State investigators would also be able to demand from banks
details of accounts through which the IRA is suspected of moving
funds raised through legitimate businesses or racketeering.
   In another measure, the government outlined its first bill to
curb job discrimination _ mainly against the Catholic minority _ in
Northern Ireland.
   The new measure will force businesses with 10 employees or more
to monitor the religious makeup of the work force.
   The proposed laws also included a new attempt to curb Britain's
notoriously violent soccer fans by forcing clubs to register
members. Only card-carrying members will be allowed into stadiums
and spectators convicted of violence can be banned for up to five
years.
   The queen and her husband, Prince Philip, traveled to Parliament
from Buckingham Palace in a new horse-drawn coach, a bicentennial
gift from Australia.
</TEXT>
