<DOCNO> AP881122-0179 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-88 2027EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AnnePollard     11-22 0681</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Anne Pollard,0701</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wife Of Convicted Spy Struggles With Prison Life</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEAN GOLEMBESKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DANBURY, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wife of a naval intelligence officer
convicted of spying for Israel said in a prison interview Tuesday
she has never spied and complained that authorities are ignoring her
medical problems.
   ``I don't know classified information, this is well known in the
Justice Department and the Bureau of Prisons,'' Anne Pollard said.
``Yet for some unknown reason I am singled out, as is my husband, in
terms of our First Amendment rights.
   ``I've never committed espionage in my life. I never would,'' she
said.
   A Justice Department representative sat across from Mrs. Pollard
at the federal prison camp to guard against any leak of secret
information and to limit the interview to one hour.
   Her husband, Jonathan Jay Pollard, has admitted selling
classified information to Israel from 1984 until his arrest in
November 1985 for as much as $2,500 a month.
   Pollard, a Jew, said he began working as a spy after deciding the
United States wasn't providing Israel with the information it needed
to protect its security, according to court documents. He is serving
a life prison term.
   Mrs. Pollard, 28, was found guilty of conspiracy to receive
embezzled government property and possession of national defense
documents. The charges stem from her attempt to deliver a suitcase
containing government documents to her husband after his operation
was uncovered by federal authorities.
   He had called her and asked for her help, according to court
documents. She is serving a five-year prison term.
   ``When my husband called me I merely responded to his request.
That's what I felt ethically a wife should do,'' she said.
   Mrs. Pollard refused to answer when asked how long she had known
about her husband's spy activities, saying only, ``I have known
about my husband's ideology since the first day I met him.''
   She also refused to say if she knew her husband was being paid by
the Israelis, but denied that she benefitted from the arrangement.
   ``I have never made an illegal dime in my life,'' Mrs. Pollard
said.
   Once robust and healthy, she is now frail and nearly doubled over
from a number of maladies. She suffers migraine headaches, is
reliant upon laxatives and no longer can see clearly.
   Mrs. Pollard said she has uncontrollable bleeding caused by an
ovarian cyst; that she suffers from a rare disorder which prevents
her from properly digesting food; that she has an irritated bowel;
and problems with her intestines that keep her from sitting up or
standing up straight.
   She is seeking a medical furlough so that physicians at Yale
University can treat her, but she has been denied permission. Her
condition has caused many in Israel and the United States to
petition government officials to release her for treatment outside
the prison system.
   ``As far as the legal processes are concerned, I can vindicate
myself in a court of law. I'm not worried about that. That can come
up in the future. I'm worried about my medical condition. I'm 28
years old. I'd like to function like a normal 28-year-old. These are
problems which can be treated and have gone untreated,'' she said.
   Paul Lefebvre, the camp's administrator, said Mrs. Pollard is
receiving proper medical treatment.
   ``We have adequate resources to deal with her medical needs,'' he
said.
   The Pollards were sentenced in Washington, D.C., in March 1987
after both decided against a trial and agreed to a plea bargain.
   ``My husband and I were forced to sign a plea agreement. I would
elaborate on that, but I can't due to potential litigation,'' she
said.
   ``The legal term is they `wired' me and my husband together,''
Mrs. Pollard said, explaining she wasn't willing to sacrifice her
husband to make a better deal for herself. ``My husband is the most
important thing in the world to me. I wouldn't do anything to harm
or hurt my husband.''
   Justice Department spokesman John Russell, who attended Tuesday's
interview, said: ``There is no cabal against her or her husband.''
</TEXT>
