<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Haiti     11-22 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Decrees Day of Mourning For Massacre Anniversary</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ The government has designated Nov.
29 a day of mourning for people massacred when Haiti tried to hold
free elections on that date last year.
   At least 34 voters were shot, stabbed or hacked to death the
morning of Nov. 29, 1987, by thugs who were protected by soldiers.
The election was canceled and Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy, then Haiti's
ruler, dissolved the independent Electoral Council.
   ``The military goverment wants to pay public and national homage
to all the victims of the aborted elections on Nov. 29, 1987,'' said
the decree, issued by the Information Ministry and dated Monday.
   It said public services, schools, businesses and factories will
be closed Nov. 29 and flags at government offices will fly at half
staff.
   No one was ever charged with the killings.
   Soldiers ousted Namphy on Sept. 17, declaring themselves sickened
by state-sponsored violence, and chose Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril to
succeed him.
   Avril said in a letter to political leaders Saturday that all
Haitians were responsible for the massacre, not just the gunmen.
   ``The decree seems to be a correction of the letter,'' said
Arnold Antonin, co-director of the National Network for the Defense
of Human Rights. ``Avril wants to make clear his support for the
victims and not the criminals.''
   Sorel Jacinthe, assistant director of the Bishops Center for
Human Rights, supported the decree but added: ``What is fundamental
is to try the criminals.''
   The two human rights groups and three others said in a joint
statement they will hold a procession Nov. 29 commemorating the
massacre, Radio Haiti Inter reported. The other groups are the
Institute for Democratic Education, Haitian League for Human Rights
and Lafontant Joseph Center for Human Rights.
   Namphy assumed power in February 1986 after President Jean-Claude
Duvalier fled the Caribbean island nation, ending nearly three
decades of dictatorship by himself and his father, Francois ``Papa
Doc'' Duvalier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
