<HEAD>Grenade Attack on Police, Bomb Defused as Princess Anne Visits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDONDERRY, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An IRA hand grenade exploded
in the yard of a police station Tuesday, damaging a parked car but
causing no injuries, police reported.
   In Belfast, police defused a bomb under an officers car about two
miles from where Princess Anne was visiting. A police spokesman said
no one was injured, he said.
   Anne, daughter of Queen Elizabeth II, was accompanied by Northern
Ireland Secretary Tom King as she visited a high school, inaugurated
a sports trust and met members of a riding association for the
handicapped. She then returned to London.
   In Londonderry, the outlawed Irish Republican Army claimed
responsibility for the grenade attack at the Royal Ulster
Constabulary station on Strand Road. The IRA is trying to drive the
British from the Protestant-dominated province and unite it with the
Irish Republic, which is overwhelmingly Roman Catholic.
