<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Iran-Contra 1stLd-Writethru a0736 11-22 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Contra, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0736,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Will Rule on North's Bid to Prevent Censoring of Documents</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 3rd graf pvs, bgng: ``Independent counsel
...'' to include task force decision.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The judge in the Iran-Contra case agreed
Tuesday to consider Oliver L. North's objections to deleting
sensitive references from classified documents prosecutors want to
use as evidence.
   U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell scheduled closed hearings
beginning Nov. 30 ``and continuing thereafter from day-to-day as
long as necessary'' to discuss the proposed deletions of references
to sensitive matters, including the names of countries, foreign
officials and U.S. intelligence agents.
   Independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh has proposed deleting the
references from the 350 documents he wants to use as evidence
against the former presidential aide to protect U.S. intelligence
operations and relations with foreign countries.
   An interagency task force that reviewed the material has agreed
to allow Walsh to use the documents as evidence in a public trial if
the sensitive references are deleted.
   Gesell said North ``should be prepared to explain why a proposed
redaction (deletion) is relevant and material for his defense'' to
charges he conspired with former White House national security
adviser John M. Poindexter and two arms dealers to illegally divert
U.S.-Iran arms-sale profits to the Nicaraguan rebels.
   The closed hearings will be held under provisions of the
Classified Information Procedures Act, or CIPA, which regulates the
disclosure of secret documents as evidence in court.
   The judge's brief order made no mention of North's proposal to
disclose the contents of some 40,000 pages of classified material in
3,500 secret documents.
   Walsh has asked Gesell to declare the list of documents North
proposed as defense exhibits legally insufficient and bar him from
introducing any of these papers into evidence.
   The prosecutor contends that North proposed many of the documents
as exhibits simply to provoke the government to drop the charges to
stem disclosure of some of the nation's most sensitive secrets.
   At a hearing Monday, Gesell seemed to signal that he would grant
Walsh's motion, saying ``intervening events make it wholly
unnecessary to discuss any scheduling of in camera (closed)
proceedings on North's CIPA filing notice, and therefore I have no
intention of scheduling such hearings, and that's a moot matter.''
   In his order scheduling hearings on the prosecution documents,
Gesell said he had reviewed many of the papers Walsh wants to use as
evidence against North.
   Many of the deletions Walsh proposes ``appear designed to excise
the identity of countries mentioned and communications with named
individuals, including officials of such countries and United States
agents in the field.''
   ``Almost without exception, North objects to these categories of
redactions,'' the judge said, referring to a portion of the
defense's secret filing on classified documents.
   Gesell directed Walsh to devise alternative method to
substituting the names of countries and individuals with letters or
numbers. ``The court finds, upon examination of the papers, that
this masking technique appears unduly cumbersome and likely to
prevent easy reading of the text.''
   The 350 documents Walsh wants to use as evidence comprise between
1,000 and 2,000 pages of classified material.
   No date has been set for North's trial, but Gesell predicted at
Monday's hearing it could begin in late January.
   At that proceeding, Gesell appealed to President Reagan to decide
whether he wanted the case to go to trial, warning that he could
have ``very little control'' over the testimony of current and
former officials who will be questioned about covert operations.
   Poindexter and arms dealers Albert Hakim and Richard V. Secord
are to be tried separately.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
