<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pakistan     11-22 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bhutto, Rival Meet With President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Populist leader Benazir Bhutto and her
conservative rival met separately Tuesday with Pakistan's president,
who is to decide which one will lead a new government.
   Ms. Bhutto's party took 93 seats in last week's National Assembly
elections. The right-wing Islamic Democratic Alliance, a coalition
headed by Nawaz Sharif, took 55 seats.
   Each leader claimed to have the backing of enough independent
candidates and minor parties to form a majority in the 237-seat
legislature. If named prime minister, Ms. Bhutto would be the first
woman to lead an Islamic nation.
   Ms. Bhutto declined comment after meeting President Ghulam Ishaq
Khan. Sharif told a press conference following his meeting that ``we
will demonstrate our majority'' in a vote of the newly elected
National Assembly.
   Neither he nor Ms. Bhutto have revealed specifics of how they
would form a majority, however.
   Sharif said he told Ishaq Khan to let a vote of the Assembly
determine the majority before a prime minister is named.
   To nominate a prime minister ``simply because a group has more
seats is unfair,'' said Sharif. ``We want a natural majority rather
than a contrived majority.''
   In a meeting Monday with caretaker ministers, Ishaq Khan said the
transfer of power will occur ``in a matter of days,'' according to
the official news agency APP. Wasim Sajjad, the caretaker justice
minister, announced the National Assembly will convene Dec. 5.
   Pakistan's Constitution contains two clauses regarding the naming
of a prime minister.
   One gives the president discretion both in timing and selection
of a Cabinet leader. The other, intended to apply to elections after
1990, requires the assembly to convene first, then determine the
prime minister through a majority vote.
   Ms. Bhutto contends the 1990 provision should be applied now
because the polls scheduled for 1990 in effect were moved up to 1988.
   But Sajjad's announcement suggests that whatever course Ishaq
Khan takes, the naming of a prime minister will occur after Dec. 5.
   The full legislature will contain 237 seats _ 207 for Moslems, 10
for non-Moslems, and 20 exclusively for women. The women will be
elected by the assembly Dec. 5.
   It means Ms. Bhutto's party needs the votes of 26 more members
for a simple majority, compared with 64 more for Sharif's group,
which includes loyalists of late President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq.
   Zia died in an Aug. 17 plane crash only weeks after calling
elections, but on a non-party basis. Ms. Bhutto's party took its
case for party-based polls to the Supreme Court and won.
   Zia ousted Ms. Bhutto's father, Prime Minister Zulfikar Ali
Bhutto, in a 1977 coup. Bhutto was hanged two years later after a
court convicted him of conspiring to kill a political rival.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
