<1ST_LINE>u a AM-LaRouche 2ndLd-Writethru a0750 11-22 0868</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-LaRouche, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0750,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witnesses Tell of Inability to Recover Loans From LaRouche Group</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 5 grafs after 5th graf pvs, bgng: ``LaRouche and ...''
to add additional detail; DELETES 11th and 12 grafs pvs, bgng:
``LaRouche, a ...'' to remove extraneous matter.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former security aide for political
extremist Lyndon H. LaRouche Jr. told a federal jury on Tuesday that
LaRouche's chief fund-raiser ordered that loans to his organizations
not be repaid.
   In testimony that supported the heart of the government's case,
Charles Tate said fund-raising chief William Wertz told staffers
``there was no such thing as a loan.''
   Tate said LaRouche fund-raisers would try to have loans converted
to contributions and, if unsuccessful, not repay them unless they
was a ``political downside'' or threatened lawsuit.
   In testimony backing another count against LaRouche _ tax fraud
conspiracy _ Tate testified the security staff performed ``maid and
butler'' chores, serving food, cleaning LaRouche's residences,
caring for his wife's dog and horses, and handling grocery shopping.
   LaRouche and six associates are accused in the U.S. District
Court case of conspiracy and mail fraud, allegedly for raising more
than $30 million in loans with no intent of repaying them. LaRouche
also is charged with conspiracy to defraud the IRS by filing no
returns since 1979, while having all personal expenses paid from
funds of various corporations he controls.
   Tate quoted Wertz as saying the general population ``owed us the
money and we had to get it from them.''
   ``Who else said that?'' asked Assistant U.S. Attorney John
Markham.
   ``Mr. LaRouche,'' Tate said of the three-time unsuccessful
presidential candidate.
   Tate, who quit the LaRouche staff after the alleged remarks about
the loans in 1984, said Wertz _ a defendant in the case _ envisioned
himself as World War II Gen. George Patton.
   Wertz, according to Tate, constantly exhorted LaRouche staffers
to ``take the beachhead'' and ``capture the bridges,'' and sometimes
played the soundtrack of the movie ``Patton'' starring George C.
Scott.
   Earlier, prosecution witnesses testified that they lent a
LaRouche organization money for an anti-drug book but never got
their money back.
   Two witnesses, Elizabeth Sexton, 75, and Lita Witt, 87, said they
knew little aboutthe political maverick and his causes but wanted to
make an investment in the book, titled ``Dope, Inc.''
   A third witness, computer firm employee Gerald Lee Corbin,
testified he was a contributor to LaRouche before and after making
his loan.
   But all three said they were solicited by LaRouche fund-raisers
repeatedly for their loans and often were promised they would be
paid back with interest.
   Ms. Sexton said she was told by a LaRouche fund-raiser that her
money was safer with the LaRouche organization than with her bank
because ``the banks are our enemies.''
   The defendants contest the charges, saying they planned to repay
the loans but were prevented from doing so when government and news
media attacks on their operations forced them to divert money to
defend themselves.
   Corbin, of Irvine, Calif., testified that he lent $10,000 in
December 1985, to Caucus Distributors Inc., which prosecutors have
described as a LaRouche-controlled organization.
   Corbin said LaRouche fund-raiser Paul Greenberg, a defendant,
promised him 12 percent interest and agreed to repay the principal
and interest within seven days of a request from Corbin.
   But Corbin said that when he needed the money in January 1986,
for a down payment on some property, he was unable to get it back
and Greenberg did not return some 30 phone calls.
   ``It was never my intent for it to be a gift,'' he said.
   Corbin acknowledged he had contributed to LaRouche's political
movement before making the loan and continued doing so right through
this year, when LaRouche made his third try for the presidency.
   ``I wanted to keep on the good side of the LaRouche
organization,'' Corbin said in explaining why he continued to make
the contributions. ``I still had hopes of getting my $10,000.''
   Ms. Witt, who said she lent Caucus Distributors $10,500 in 1985,
testified that her sole purpose was to invest in the book.
   ``I didn't understand it was a political movement,'' she said.
``I was investing in their book. I am not a supporter (of LaRouche).
I have never been.''
   Ms. Witt, of Dallas, said she attempted repeatedly to get her
money back, but was unable to do so.
   Preceding Ms. Witt's testimony, Ms. Sexton said that in a
desperate attempt to get back the $112,800 she lent the LaRouche
organization, she wrote LaRouche himself and received a written
response in May 1986. ``He talked about their plight,'' she said.
``I wanted him to talk about my plight. I tried to explain my
plight, too.''
   LaRouche was indicted in October on 13 counts of mail fraud,
conspiracy to commit mail fraud and conspiracy to defraud the IRS.
Conviction on all counts could carry a prison term of 65 years and
fines of $3.25 million.
   The six other defendants face lesser sentences if convicted of
the mail fraud and conspiracy charges.
   The co-defendants are Wertz, chief fund-raiser; chief LaRouche
legal adviser Edward Spannaus and four fund-raisers: Michael
Billington, Dennis Small, Greenberg and Joyce Rubinstein.
</TEXT>
