<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Sun-TimesTalks     11-22 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sun-Times Talks,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tentative Settlement Reached at Chicago Sun-Times</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiators for the Chicago Sun-Times and its
editorial employees reached tentative agreement on a three-year
contract Tuesday without any of the pay concessions that had
prompted a strike threat.
   The union's executive committee unanimously recommended approval
of the pact, which includes a flat $500 payment in the first year
and 3 percent raises in the remaining two years for the
approximately 250 reporters, editors and photographers who are
members of the Local 71 of the Chicago Newspaper Guild.
   A ratification vote was scheduled for Nov. 29.
   ``It would have been unprecedented if we didn't get some type of
remuneration for the first year,'' said union spokesman Dan Lehmann,
who also is the Sun-Times' religion writer. ``It would have set a
pattern for accords across this country that the guild simply could
not let happen.''
   He declined to discuss other provisions of the proposed deal,
including such sticking points as an affirmative action plan and who
is exempt from the contract.
   ``I want our members to read the contract before they read
anything about it,'' he said.
   Sun-Times spokesman Michael Soll said the newspaper's management
was pleased with the settlement.
   ``We just want to get things back on track,'' he said.
   The union had set a strike deadline of 2:30 p.m. Monday, but
postponed any action while negotiations continued throughout the
day. The last management proposal put to the union late Monday
offered a wage freeze for the first year, followed by 3 percent
raises in the next two years.
   Following a 2{-hour meeting, union members voted to ask Sun-Times
bargainers to return to the table and make some improvements.
   ``I think that meeting made it clear that a substantial majority
was willing to walk out if that was the company's final offer,'' he
said. ``I think that's when the company sensed the seriousness of
the situation.''
   The Sun-Times' initial bargaining stance included a 15 percent
pay cut over two years, but that was modified to a 3 percent pay cut
for 18 months, followed by restoration of current pay for the
balance of a three-year pact.
   The pay scale at the newspaper ranges from $625 a week for
starting reporters to $895 for reporters with five years' experience.
   Union members have been working without a contract since June 1.
A strike would have been the first by Sun-Times editorial workers in
the newspaper's 40-year history.
   The Sun-Times said it must control costs to remain competitive
with the larger Chicago Tribune, which has an estimated circulation
of 765,000 daily and 1.11 million Sunday.
   The Sun-Times, whose circulation is estimated at 605,000 daily
and 614,000 on Sundays, was purchased from Rupert Murdoch for $145
million in June 1986 by a group of investors led by the New York
investment firm Adler & Shaykin.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
