<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0759,0670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mortar Shells Hit Police Headquarters; Other Attacks Kill 41</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs UPDATING with minister warning Lima of
contaminated water supply, recasts for clarity. PICKS up 9th pvs:
`Earlier violence ..' Minor editing thereafter.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT SEAVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru, (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist rebels launched a mortar attack
Tuesday on the Lima headquarters of the national security police and
raided an isolated mountain town, capping a four-day wave of
violence that has killed 41 people.
   Authorities said one policeman was killed, three were wounded and
two were missing in the raid on the mountain community of Cotahuasi,
335 miles southeast of Lima. They said rebels of the Maoist-inspired
Shining Path guerrilla movement carried out the raid.
   No one was reported injured in the Lima attack by the pro-Cuba
Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movemement.
   Shining Path guerrillas dynamited three power pylons late Monday
near Huancayo, 125 miles east of Lima, knocking out power and using
the cover of darkness to bomb three banks and a police station.
Police said no one was hurt.
   Power also was cut in Lima, the capital; parts of Lima state, and
sections of five other states on Peru's central coast and mountains.
The state power company Electro-Peru said power was restored to most
capital areas in minutes.
   The attacks followed one of the heaviest rounds of violence in an
eight-year insurgency that has killed more than 12,000 people.
   Health Minister Luis Pinillos warned residents in this city of
six million that Lima's water supply had become contaminated due to
``problems in the supply of electric energy'' late Monday.
   In a statement he said a power outage halted the operation of
purification equipment, allowing drinking water to mix with
contaminated water and rendering the entire supply unfit to drink.
   He said the problem would be solved soon but warned residents to
boil water at least 10 minutes before drinking. It did not
specifically refer to the rebel-caused power outage.
   Interior Minister Juan Soria said four Tupac Amaru rebels
directed mortar fire shortly after dawn Tuesday at the headquarters
of the national security police, Peru's main anti-guerrilla force.
   He said two shells gouged chunks from the outside wall of the
office building, which also houses the regional administrator's
office and a state police garrison. It is in a walled, block-square
compound in downtown Lima.
   He said a third shell exploded on the roof of a Chinese
restaurant.
   Earlier violence included:
   _Two firefights between troops and the Shining Path guerrillas
Sunday and Monday that left 10 of the Maoist guerrillas dead in the
rural countryside near Ayacucho, 230 miles southeast of Lima.
   _A Shining Path attack on the farming village of Tupe, 90 miles
southeast of Lima, before dawn Monday. Rebels killed five village
officials after accusing them of supporting the government in the
insurgency.
   _The deaths of 15 guerrillas and seven soldiers in a battle
Sunday near Abancay in the Andes Mountains 320 miles southeast of
Lima _ one of the bloodiest single clashes in the insurgency.
   _An attack by the Shining Path late Saturday that killed two
policemen near a hydro-electrical plant in the mountains near
Huancayo.
   _The death of Shining Path chieftain Ruben Dario Muelle Gongora
in a shootout with police Saturday in Sicuani, 420 miles southeast
of Lima.
   The mortar attack followed the arrest Monday of Saul Cantoral,
leader of a month-long mining strike that has paralyzed the mineral
industry. Union leaders said security police was holding Cantoral.
   Last week, Tupac Amaru guerrillas bombed the Lima headquarters of
the National Mining Society, an association of private mine owners,
in support of the striking miners.
   Soria said police and rebels traded shots moments after the
attack, but the insurgents escaped in a station wagon.
   Tupac Amaru is smaller and considered less violent that Shining
Path. It endorses Cuban-styled Marxism and has been active since
1984, mainly in cities.
</TEXT>
