<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Bush-Salinas     11-22 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Salinas,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Salinas Sees Better U.S.-Mexico Relations After Meeting Bush</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Carlos Salinas de Gortari, a
Harvard graduate, said Tuesday he expects Mexico to have better
relations with the United States when Yale graduate George Bush
takes over.
   The two men hit it off well, said to Salinas advisers who were
present at the first meeting of the two presidents-elect at the
Johnson Space Center in Houston.
   ``Based on the terms of this meeting,'' Salinas told reporters on
the flight back from Houston, ``I expect a much better
relationship.''
   After the meeting, both men termed good relations essential to
the two countries and acknowledged that the two most important
problems they must work on are drug trafficking and Mexico's foreign
debt.
   ``They (the United States) will work on the problem of
consumption and Mexico will fight trafficking,'' Salinas said.
   Drug trafficking has been a sore point in Mexican-U.S. relations.
U.S. officials often charge that corruption by Mexican officials
facilitates the drug trade, while Mexico says trafficking flourishes
because of the market for narcotics in the United States.
   Both men were accompanied by their economic advisers, underlining
the emphasis both place on economic matters, especially a Mexican
foreign debt that now stands at $102 billion.
   Salinas said he stressed that Mexico needs to renegotiate the
debt because it needs money for development. This year Mexico has
paid nearly $9 billion in interest alone on the debt.
   The Mexican president-elect said it is imperative for Mexico to
grow again and that growth will help solve several Mexican-American
problems, including the illegal migration of Mexicans to the United
States in search of jobs.
   In a joint communique, the two said they recognized that ``the
solidarity and understanding of the United States is essential for
Mexico'' to find ways to allow this country to develop.
   Salinas told reporters he and Bush agreed to start Cabinet-level
meetings between their treasury secretaries on the debt shortly
after Salinas takes office Dec. 1. Although Bush does not take
office until Jan. 20, he announced plans to keep Nicholas Brady as
treasury secretary.
   Bush said both he and Salinas were committed to improving their
relationship, which he said he considered essential for the United
States.
   Salinas said he found the U.S. president-elect's attitude
``positive and cordial.''
</TEXT>
