<HEAD>Parents Charged in Girl's Slaying</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf with 5 to UPDATE with explanation of arrests;
charges filed, CORRECT son's age and that he was placed in state's
custody, other details; picks up 4th graf pvs, `Jaclyn's body...';
DELETES now-outdated last graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIDLOTHIAN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parents of a 7-year-old girl were
arrested Tuesday and charged with murder in her strangling, more
than two months after they reported she had been stolen from her bed
while they slept.
   David Dowaliby, 31, Jaclyn's adoptive father, was arrested on his
way to work Tuesday; Cynthia Dowaliby, 26, was arrested at their
home, said Lisa Howard, a spokeswoman for the Cook County state's
attorney's office.
   The couple's 4-year-old son, David, was placed in custody of the
state Department of Children and Family Services, police said.
   The arrests were staggered to avoid traumatizing the boy, said
Paul Greves, chief of police in Blue Island, where Jaclyn's body was
found.
   Both parents were charged with first-degree murder, he said.
   Greves would not comment on evidence leading to the arrests.
   The Dowalibys were to appear at a pre-trial hearing Wednesday in
Cook County Criminal Court.
   Jaclyn's body was discovered in a patch of weeds on the edge of a
wooded area in nearby Blue Island a few days after she was reported
missing Sept. 10. Authorities say she had been strangled.
   Police at first believed the child had been abducted from her
home in this southwest Chicago suburb, but later said the
investigation had been expanded to consider other possibilities.
   Mrs. Dowaliby told police she had checked Jaclyn in her bedroom
late Sept. 9 and that her husband discovered the child missing about
8 a.m. the next morning. Police said a basement window was broken
and the front door of the home was ajar.
   ``The fact that there was nothing disturbed in the house, no
signs of violent struggle, nobody heard anything, that brings to
mind ... questions,'' Midlothian police Capt. John Bittin said at
the time.
   The investigation slowed when the Dowalibys ceased to answer
additional questions from authorities. Their attorney maintained the
family was being harassed and had told police all they knew.
