<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Panama-Banks     11-22 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Banks,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panama To Continue Bank Restrictions Through Mid-1989</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY ALINA GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Banking Commission
extended banking restrictions through the middle of next year, but
eased rules governing withdrawals during December, the government
announced Tuesday.
   A banking crisis here resulted from U.S. actions against the
Panamanian government controlled by Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega
after Noriega's indictment in the United States on drug trafficking
charges. Noriega denied the charges.
   Banking restrictions _ originally to last for three months after
banks shut down by the government reopened in May _ will continue
through June 30, 1989, a banking commission news release said.
   Customers will not be required to request withdrawals 30 days in
advance in December. The 30-day petition rule will go back into
effect in January.
   The commission, a governmental regulatory agency, permanently
eased restrictions effective Dec. 1, by raising the amount customers
can withdraw from savings accounts each month to 10 percent of the
account, with $100 as the maximum monthly withdrawal. Withdrawals
had been limited to 5 percent a month, up to a maximum of $50.
   Rules affecting checking accounts _ limiting monthly withdrawals
to 50 percent up to a maximum of $50,000 _ remain unchanged.
   The commission predicted that despite continued restrictions, the
National Bank of Panama and other official banks will disburse about
$28 million from Christmas savings accounts in December.
   The commission said it will continue to analyze the banking
system's actions with an eye to ``advancing toward the total
re-establishment of the normal functioning of the banking system.''
   Runs on banks began in late February when Noriega forced out
President Eric Arturo Delvalle hours after the president tried to
fire the general. As head of the Defense Forces, Noriega is Panama's
de facto ruler.
   A U.S. freeze on $50 million in Panamanian government funds
deposited in the United States left the National Bank of Panama, the
central bank, unable to cover large withdrawals.
   The government ordered banks shut March 3 and allowed them to
reopen May 9.
   The 115 banks operating under general licenses are affected by
the government restrictions.
   In July, the banking commission extended restrictions until the
end of the year. Under the latest commission decree, the
restrictions will continue through June 1989.
</TEXT>
