<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LouisianaDesegregation     11-22 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Louisiana Desegregation,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Dissolves Pact, Orders Special Master to Help Integrate
Colleges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET McCONNAUGHEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A three-judge panel ruled Tuesday Louisiana
has failed to set up an acceptable integration plan for its colleges
and universities and ordered that a special master put one together.
   The panel earlier this year ruled the state had allowed
``unlawful'' segregation to persist in the schools despite a 1981
consent decree that was to end racial bias.
   Tuesday's ruling dissolves the consent decree.
   ``The Court does not mean to preclude continuing settlement
discussions ... Thus, the parties are welcome to submit ... a
consensus plan,'' said the order.
   ``They bent over backward to let all parties work together,''
said Gov. Buddy Roemer.
   The judges scheduled a Feb. 15 trial unless an acceptable plan is
presented to the court before then. An acceptable plan likely will
include a single board to govern all the schools, the judges said.
   The state currently supports three systems, each with its own
governing board, which are controlled by a super-regulatory agency
known as the Louisiana Board of Regents.
   None of the four boards wants to relinquish authority.
   ``They said one of the best reasons for a single board is a
status conference like this one _ 14 lawyers instead of one. ... The
expense of what we're doing now could have hired countless faculty
members,'' Roemer said.
   Roemer said he expects the judges to appoint a special master in
the next few days.
   The panel consisted of Judge John M. Wisdom of the 5th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals and Judges Charles Schwartz and Veronica D.
Wicker of the U.S. District Court.
   The judges in August said that ``despite the slight increase in
black enrollment statewide, the racial polarization has increased as
a whole during the term of the consent decree.''
   The judges found that of Louisiana's 20 institutions of higher
education, those originally established as ``black'' schools _
Southern University-Baton Rouge, Southern-New Orleans,
Southern-Shreveport, and Grambling _ remain predominantly black.
   It said that with the exception of two community colleges,
Louisiana was continuing to operate an unlawful, dual system of
public higher education.
   The 1981 consent decree was intended to resolve a 1974 lawsuit
the Justice Department filed against the state.
</TEXT>
