<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-88 2320EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Missiles-Shuttle     11-22 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Missiles-Shuttle,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Plans to Fire Missiles Toward Shuttle in 1990 Star Wars
Experiment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Army plans to shoot missiles toward
the space shuttle during a 1990 mission to test key technologies of
the Strategic Defense Initiative, officials said.
   The Star Wars experiment, called Starlab, is designed to
demonstrate that sensors can distinguish between a rocket and its
exhaust plume and then point a laser and hit the missile, Lt. Col.
D. Voorhees told reporters on a tour of the Army Strategic Defense
Command in Huntsville Monday.
   The missiles will be designed to miss the shuttle by more than
100 miles.
   The Strategic Defense Command will supply five four-stage rockets
called Starbirds to be launched toward the shuttle during a
seven-day unclassified Defense Department mission scheduled for
Sept. 10, 1990, said Voorhees, chief of the Starbird project office.
   Low-power lasers aboard the shuttle will be trained on a flat,
3-by-6-foot target card on the fourth stage of the Starbird.
   The shuttle will carry a crew of seven, including two Air Force
payload specialists already selected. They will be trained at the
Marshall Space Flight Center in Huntsville.
   The Air Force Systems Division is in charge of the mission.
Others participating, in addition to NASA and the Army, are the Navy
and the Massachussetts Institute of Technology.
   Because it is the first time any object has been launched at the
shuttle, the Army missiles must fly a trajectory designated by NASA
and the Army must prove that trajectory in a demonstration flight to
insure safety, Voorhees said. One static firing has been completed
successfully and another is planned for December.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
