<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-88 0851EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i PM-Philippines-Miscues Adv28   11-22 0819</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Miscues, Adv 28,0842</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv28</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs Nov. 28 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Aquino Government Blamed for Things that Go Wrong in Philippines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Philippines has just gone through
a nightmare of storms, sinking ships, communist rebels escaping
captivity and foodstocks vanishing.
   Parts of the nightmare can be explained by bad luck, including
three tropical storms that killed more than 600 people in two weeks.
   But some Filipinos lay it at the door of President Corazon
Aquino's government, charging that it lacks organization, resources,
efficiency to keep things in order _ and accountability.
   ``It is not enough that the president sets the example,'' the
Philippine Daily Inquirer newspaper said recently on the issue of
accountability. ``She should also find the strength and conviction
to make examples of officials who do not measure up.''
   The most graphic example was the escape Nov. 12 of the alleged
chief of the Communist rebel army. The military says Romulo
Kintanar, 41, and his wife Gloria, 38, were allowd to attend a
birthday party for a former stockade commandant and they simply
walked away.
   The acting stockade commander, Maj. Benjamin Landrito, offered
maintained that he was unaware Kintanar and his wife were allowed to
leave their cells because he was asleep in his office at the time.
   It was not the first security problem at the stockade at Camp
Crame, which includes the headquarters of the Philippine
Constabulary.
   Kintanar's host, Lt. Col. Robelito Comilang, was suspended in
October when a rightist army officer, Lt. Col. Francisco Baula,
reportedly walked through three doors that were supposed to be
locked, climbed the stockade wall and was on his way when guards
finally shot and killed him.
   That followed an incident in June, in which dozens of armed men
tried to free former Gov. Orlando Dulay, jailed in the 1986 deaths
of several Aquino supporters. Raiders failed to free Dulay but made
off with armory weapons.
   Mrs. Aquino has demanded a full investigation into Kintanar's
escape. Three senior officers, including Landrito and Comilang, have
been relieved and restricted to quarters. But some Filipinos are
skeptical.
   ``There has not been any real investigation, much less real
punishment of people concerned,'' fumed Sen. Ernesto Maceda,
chairman of the Senate Defense Committee. ``There is a tendency to
cover up. In the spirit of comradeship, they just cover up the
incident to control the damage.''
   Maceda's doubts were based on the failure of previous
investigations to fix responsibility, punish those responsible and
implement changes.
   Commissions failed to solve the assassination in September, 1986,
of labor leader Rolando Olalia, the killing in August, 1987, of
Local Governments Secretary Jaime Ferrer and the slaying in
September, 1987, of leftist leader Lean Alejandro.
   Another commission organized after January 1987 killing of 13
land reform protesters by soldiers guarding the presidential palace
never established who gave the order to fire.
   The senior officer on duty during the shooting, Brig. Gen. Ramon
Montano, was furloughed as the capital's regional commander during
the investigation. But months later, he was promoted to major
general and given command of the Philippine Constabulary, the
country's national police.
   Three separate commissions investigated the December 1987
collision of the passenger ship Dona Paz with an oil tanker, in
which more than 3,000 people are believed to have perished.
   All three commissions found evidence of widespread inefficiency
in the maritime industry, including overloaded ships, lack of
adequate communications, poorly trained crew and the absence of
effective search and rescue procedures.
   But Commodore Carlito Cunanan, who as coast guard commandant was
responsible for maritime safety, was promoted to navy commander
after the Dona Paz disaster.
   In October, the Dona Marilyn, another passenger ship owned by the
same company, sailed into Typhoon Ruby and sank with 500 people
aboard, about half of whom are still listed as missing and feared
dead.
   Although the investigations into the second sinking have not been
completed, officials say they have found evidence of many of the
same shortcomings which led to the Dona Paz disaster.
   ``The country is one big Dona Marilyn sinking in the middle of a
storm while the captain snores on top of a mahjong table,'' wrote
Francisco Tatad, a frequent administration critic. ``Many (heads)
should roll.''
   In September, Emil Ong, chairman of the National Food Authority,
was furloughed and then fired after two investigating committees
found evidence of widespread incompetence.
   The committees cited, among other things, the disappearance of
$350,000 worth of rice, which Ong said sank on three barges. The
coast guard said it had no record of the sinking.
   Two days after Ong was dismissed, he was named presidential
adviser for regional government affairs.
   That prompted columnist Luis Beltran to joke in the
pro-government Evening Star newspaper that ``going on leave'' had
become a new civil service status ``in which incompetents are
prepared for promotions.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon PMs Nov. 28</NOTE>
</DOC>
