<NOTE>For Release PMs Wednesday Nov 23</NOTE>
<HEAD>The Question: To Tax or Not To Tax</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An effusion of post-election proposals to raise
taxes has created an illusion that only President-elect George Bush
and the American electorate are opposed.
   The proposals have come from such diverse sources as former
presidents, the financial community, the news media, organized
labor, academics, groups committed to social causes, members of
Congress, foreign interests and others.
   The avowed concerns of all center on the belief that the federal
budget cannot be balanced in the near future through economic growth
alone, but must have an assist from more austere tax policies.
   The proposals, including those of former Presidents Ford and
Carter, have developed relentlessly in the two weeks since Bush was
elected president on a platform that included a promise of no income
tax increase.
   So great has been the outpouring that some conservative groups
have begun reasserting their anti-tax increase philosophy.
   Summarizing an analysis issued this week, Stephen Moore of the
Heritage Foundation, which was influential in the Bush campaign,
stated: ``The facts are on Bush's side. ... there is no reason for
him to retreat from his pledge.''
   Moore, a Heritage fellow in federal budgetary matters, contends
that if Congress simply holds spending growth to a rate less than 4
percent a year the deficit will be eliminated by 1993 without a tax
increase.
   Among reasons for optimism, Moore said, is that the flow of red
ink already is subsiding from a peak of $220 billion in fiscal 1986
to $148 billion in fiscal 1989. Economic growth already is outpacing
the deficit, he said.
   More important, he said, was evidence that the deficit as a share
of total economic output is likely to fall to 2.9 percent of gross
national product in 1989 from 6.3 percent in 1983.
   In support of his argument, Moore said that federal taxes already
are at record-high levels, that new taxes mean higher spending
rather than lower deficits, and that a major tax hike would slow
economic growth and threaten recession.
   He said that taxes will consume 19.6 percent of GNP in 1990, a
level reached in only five years of this century and that federal
spending since 1948 has increased $1.58 for every dollar of tax
increase.
   The cleavage in views between those aggressively encouraging
higher taxes and those vehemently opposed produces something of a
comprehension gap for ordinary Americans. There is very little
moderate ground or agreement.
   Speaking for the American Agenda, a bipartisan group they headed,
Carter and Ford said they saw no prospect whatever of a balanced
budget by 1993 simply through spending cuts, even though they
searched assiduously for some hope.
   Bush, on the other hand, seems to have committed himself to
follow through on his promise of no major tax increases, presumably
relying on the prospect of healthy economic growth eventually
overwhelming the deficit.
   Convinced that such a scenario will unfold, Moore said members of
``the pro-tax lobby'' have been consistently wrong in their
predictions about the course of the economy during the Reagan
administration, and will be wrong again.
   In 1982, he said, they argued Reagan's tax cuts would cause high
inflation, but inflation declined; in 1983 they said deficits would
force interest rates higher, but rates fell sharply; during the 1984
presidential campgain they promised a recession unless taxes were
raised, but expansion continued.
   Most recently, he added, they insisted the federal debt would
cause the loss of U.S. business and jobs to foreign competitors, but
corporate profits and employment levels in the United States rose to
all-time highs.
   ``They seem completely unable to learn from their mistakes,''
Moore concludes. ``Bush should ignore them. Their advice is as bad
now as it has been during the past eight years.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Wed Nov 23</NOTE>
</DOC>
