<1ST_LINE>a e AM-APArts:Macchio ADV01   11-22 0819</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AP Arts: Macchio, ADV 01,0838</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv01</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thu AMs, Dec. 1 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Hollywood Turns Off Karate Kid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ralph Macchio is the kind of person who prefers
natural grass to artificial surface. No wonder the actor chooses to
live far away from Hollywood.
   ``I'm sort of locked away from it,'' said Macchio, a resident of
Long Island. ``I'm somewhat turned off by all the handshaking. You
play the game, everybody plays the game, but it gets old fast. I
just choose to be away from it.''
   But Macchio loves to act. His latest film, ``Distant Thunder,''
gives him a chance to play opposite one of the best, John Lithgow.
   ``When I work with an actor, I will rent his previous films,'' he
said. ``I saw `The World According to Garp'; he was incredible.
`Terms of Endearment,' he worked five days on that film and he gets
nominated for an Academy Award, that's my kind of deal!''
   Macchio, a very young-looking 27, plays a high school senior in
``Distant Thunder.'' Lithgow plays his father, a Vietnam veteran who
abandoned his infant son and now wants to re-establish a
relationship.
   ``It's not a true story about one person but it's based on a
group of real events, real veterans and their experiences. It's 1988
and the war still goes on,'' said the actor.
   Macchio had to research the part. ``I met with a kid who was 18
and hadn't seen his father for eight or nine years. His father was a
veteran. I talked to him a decent amount of time. He was very
helpful.''
   And he tried to find motivation from his own father as well.
``I'm very close to him and I tried to imagine if he wasn't there. I
remember him saying `Don't shorten up on the bat' at Little League.
I just imagined not having that.''
   Fans may be most familiar with Macchio's starring roles in ``The
Karate Kid'' and ``The Karate Kid II,'' box-office smashes that have
grossed over $200 million. And yes, there will be a ``Karate Kid
III,'' but Macchio, fulfilling a contractual obligation, is
approaching the film with mixed feelings.
   ``I'm somewhat looking forward to it,'' he said with a thin
smile. ``The people like it, it's a good story. The first film
really turned out nice. I think we owe it to the public and it will
be nice to complete the saga.''
   Macchio was born and raised on Long Island. He didn't do much
acting as a youngster; dancing was his first love.
   ``When I was a little kid, I liked Gene Kelly movies. I took
dancing lessons from 2{ to 15 or 16. My parents read it was good for
kids. It helped in making `The Karate Kid,''' said the actor, whose
karate moves at times resembled dance steps.
   In 1977, a local casting agent, Marie Pastor, saw him perform at
a dance recital and encouraged him take up acting. His first feature
film was ``Up the Academy,'' in 1980, but his real break came three
years later with ``The Outsiders.''
   Macchio was a teen-ager when he read the S.E. Hinton novel and
was desperate to get the part of Johnny. ``I remember thinking, `I
need this,''' he recalled.
   He was turned down for the part but learned that Francis Ford
Coppola was directing and vowed to try again.
   ``Then there was no way I wasn't getting it,'' Macchio laughed.
``I auditioned and I got the part. Coppola wanted me to read for
some other parts and I said, `No.' I still love that movie. It's
something special _ my first real role.''
   He followed with ``The Karate Kid,'' ``Teachers'' and
``Crossroads.'' In 1986, Macchio's career took a drastic change of
pace when he starred opposite Robert De Niro in the Broadway play,
``Cuba and His Teddy Bear.''
   ``When I first met De Niro, I was nervous as hell,'' Macchio
said. ``I wanted the part, I wanted to do theater and I wanted to
work with him. But after the first two days, you relax. You're all
actors trying to create reality through someone's words.''
   Having worked with an actor of De Niro's caliber, Macchio felt at
ease around Lithgow.
   ``I wasn't intimidated by him. He's what I describe as a
shoot-from-the-hip kind of guy. When it's time to do the work, he's
right in it. When it's time to take a break, he's a lot of fun. I'm
the same way. I think the scenes we have together are really
strong.''
   For the future, Macchio would like to raise a family with his
wife, Phyllis, a nurse, and continue to grow as an actor.
   ``To try to be believable is the challenge of it. It's one of the
few professions where you get to see the work,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thu AMs, Dec. 1</NOTE>
</DOC>
