<DOCNO> AP881122-0209 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-88 2215EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e AM-APArts:LosLobos ADV02   11-22 0672</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AP Arts: Los Lobos, ADV 02,0684</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, Dec. 2 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>For Los Lobos, A Bow To Tradition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As children growing up in East Los Angeles, the
members of the rock band Los Lobos listened to their parents' music,
the folk music of Mexico. As might be expected, the effect was
profound.
   ``As soon as we were tall enough to get to the knob on the radio,
(we'd say), `Hey, no more of that stuff, Mom,''' recalls drummer
Louie Perez. The knob would spin. ``This is what we're listening to.
... Rock 'n' roll.'''
   Eventually, the knob spun back. As teen-agers just out of high
school, Perez and his friends recreated those traditional Mexican
songs for weddings, dances and the like, and then melded them with
their second love _ rock _ to invent the sound that characterized
their first three albums.
   Now, after scoring a commercial hit with the soundtrack to the
movie, ``La Bamba,'' Los Lobos has come back again to their roots.
The band's new LP, ``La Pistola y El Corazon'' (``The Pistol and the
Heart'') is a rousing, loving sampler of the traditional music of
Mexico.
   ``We've always wanted to do something like this,'' Perez said in
an interview before a concert at Carnegie Hall. ``And the timing
just seemed to be right.''
   Some might doubt that last statement, as Perez acknowledged. ``A
lot of people I've talked to have said, `Why do you want to do
something like that now? You'd want to follow up the big hit,
wouldn't you?'
   ``And I'd say, `Not really.' We've always stayed away from the
predictable and the obvious sort of thing. And for us, this is a
real artistic sort of step. And that's sort of a reaction to the
commercial ... success that we entertained last year. It's our way
of responding to that in a constructive, more responsible, artistic
way.''
   For the album and the 11-city tour that followed, the band used
only traditional, acoustic instruments _ violin, accordion, upright
bass, plus guitarron, jarana, hidalgarron and other relatively
exotic instruments rarely heard, or even heard of, in this country.
   They also purposely varied the song selection to give U.S.
audiences a taste of Mexico's different regional styles _ Veracruz,
Huapango, Michoacan and so forth.
   ``We wanted to expose music from Mexico that's relatively unknown
to most people _ kind of shatter the myth of Mexican music as just
mariachi music,'' Perez said.
   There was one concession to the non-Mexican market _ the album is
short, just over 25 minutes long, because the band ``didn't want
anybody who was unfamiliar with this music to get burned out.''
   The band members also had hoped to offer the album at a special
low price, but Warner Bros. _ which otherwise was supportive and
agreeable to the project, Perez said _ wouldn't go for it.
   According to Perez, sales of the album in its first few weeks
have been satisfying _ nearly 100,000 copies. The band's next step,
after recouping for the holidays, will be to get back into the
studio for another rock 'n' roll album that should be out in late
spring.
   Meanwhile, the members of Los Lobos are having fun introducing
Norteamericanos to the music of their parents, the music of their
heritage.
   ``That's pretty much what we've always set out to do _ do
something that represents who we are, our identity,'' Perez said.
``In a way, this record is showing some vulnerability and I think
people appreciate that. Letting people know this is who we are, this
is what we've done and this is the music that got us going.
   ``This is the stuff that was around my house when I was a little
kid. And you might be from Minneapolis and maybe there was something
else around when you were a little kid. But maybe it's worth it to
check it out.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, Dec. 2</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
