<1ST_LINE>s a BC-EmptyHouses-Neighbors ADV27   11-22 0684</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Empty Houses-Neighbors, ADV 27,0703</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv27</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Nov. 27, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Philadelphia Struggles to Put Homeless in Empty Houses</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Empty Houses</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TED DUNCOMBE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The boarded-up house seems out of place among
the neat terraces and well-tended sidewalks where children walk
unescorted from school.
   The middle-class Oxford Circle neighborhood of brick and stone
rowhouses is a good place to live, neighbors boast. No argument,
says Dignity Housing Inc., a non-profit corporation that wants to
repair the empty house and permit a homeless family to enjoy the
neighborhood's calm and stability.
   But the neighbors don't want the homeless problem on their
doorstep. They say the area real-estate market is strong and the
house could sell easily to someone who would have a personal stake
in keeping it up.
   ``The poor people, they come and trash up the neighborhood,''
said John Shepherd, a retiree who lives a few doors away. ``It
doesn't matter if they're black or white.''
   It's still uncertain who will prevail.
   The house, which was occupied until May 1986, when a family that
had defaulted on its mortgage left, was included in the Dignity
Housing program by mistake. When City Council approved the purchase
of 36 houses from the federal Department of Housing and Urban
Development, the resolution stated this house was in the West Oak
Lane section, several miles to the northwest.
   City Councilman Jack Kelly, who represents the Oxford Circle
section, insists the house should be privately sold. In June, he won
City Council approval of a resolution ordering the house removed
from the program.
   ``That's why they have erasers on pencils,'' he said.
   But Dignity Housing officials contend the deal is final.
   ``I say `hurray' that this mistake was made, because we need to
put a family in there,'' said Chris Sprowal, the group's executive
director and president of the Philadelphia-based National Union of
the Homeless.
   Dignity Housing has placed 28 homeless families, far fewer than
it had planned, but expects to fill 50 houses by the end of the
year, Sprowal said. City agencies are helping.
   Kelly said city efforts should encourage more private developers
to provide housing for the homeless in areas where neighbors want
them, especially in dilapidated blocks.
   ``I have no problem with that,'' he said. ``I have real big
problems when they start coming into stable neighborhoods.''
   Edward A. Schwartz, director of the city Office of Housing and
Community Development, said he understands the concern and feels
proper screening is needed to ensure the homeless people can assume
responsibility and that the neighborhoods won't turn against them.
   ``But are we to say that we are now going to return to
poorhouses?'' Schwartz said.
   ``The idea is to try to rebuild neighborhoods,'' said Bill Burke,
who founded the non-profit Modular Development Corp. in 1984 with
the idea of making pre-fabricated houses for use by the poor. He
sees Philadelphia's city-owned vacant lots _ Schwartz counts 7,210
of them _ as ripe for building.
   In addition, Schwartz said, Philadelphia owns 6,576 vacant
residential units, of which 5,283 are in single-family dwellings,
mostly rowhouses.
   Philadelphia has enough housing for its 1.6 million people,
according to a June report by Cushing N. Dolbeare, a
Washington-based consultant on housing and public policy. But the
city needs at least $447 million to stem the cycle of deterioration
and abandonment, she said.
   City records show the costs of rehabilitating one group of nine
properties for Dignity Housing averaged $28,300 per unit. But fixing
up houses in the city's more abandoned neighborhoods could cost
$80,000 or more per unit, much more than the city usually can afford
to spend per family, Schwartz said.
   ``A great many units will have to be knocked down,'' Schwartz
said. ``We're knocking down vacant houses at the rate of 1,000 a
year.''
   Demolition has other drawbacks. Many of the houses reflect a lost
elegance and prosperity and are considered part of the city's
architectural heritage.
   Whenever houses must be destroyed, Schwartz said, ``It's going to
be a very wrenching decision.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Nov. 27</NOTE>
