<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-88 0736EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     11-22 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls Against Yen, Shares Hit Record High Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell today against the Japanese yen
following its overnight decline overseas, while share prices rose
moderately to another record high on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 121.87 yen, down 0.74 yen from Monday's
finish at 122.52 yen. The currency opened at 121.85 yen and ended
slightly lower despite the Bank of Japan's reported intervention.
   Market sources said the central bank began buying dollars when
the currency fell to around 121.60 yen Tuesday morning and made
intermittent purchases in the afternoon.
   The dollar's bearishness in Tokyo followed its overnight decline
on overseas markets, said Minori Takeuchi of Chemical Bank in Tokyo.
   ``The dollar started lower this morning and stayed that way,''
she said, adding: ``There was no new factor in Tokyo to lower the
dollar otherwise.''
   However, dealers were inclined to sell dollars ahead of the Labor
Thanksgiving Day holiday Wednesday, when currency and stock markets
will be closed, said a dealer with the Bank of Tokyo. He said many
others were sitting on the sidelines because of the bank's
intervention.
   Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa said today that Japan is willing
to take measures to save the dollar from declining further, but
indicated he was not overly concerned about its fall to the
121.00-yen level.
   He said the dollar's slide after the U.S. presidential election
Nov. 8 has been based on speculation and has ignored basic economic
fundamentals between the United States and Japan.
   Meanwhile, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average added 145.86
points, or 0.50 percent, to finish at a record high of 29,430.12.
The index has gained for eight consecutive days since Nov. 11.
   The index moved little during the morning session, mainly because
of profit-taking and directionless trading, said a dealer at a major
securities firm. Investors began buying speculatively in the
afternoon, and the index rose, he said, speaking anonymously.
   In active trading with volume on the first section estimated at
1.2 billion shares, steels and shipbuilding attracted attention.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
