<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     11-22 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar drifted lower in early European trading
today.
   Gold prices fell slightly.
   Foreign currency dealers in London said the dollar will likely
remain under pressure in the near-term, but they expect trading to
be quiet all week because of a Japanese holiday on Wednesday and the
American Thanksgiving holiday on Thursday.
   Dealers said the market is keeping an eye on the central banks.
One trader noted the dollar is currently trading around the same
levels as it was last Thursday when central banks joined together to
defend the U.S. currency.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.74 yen to a closing 121.78, despite reported
intervention by the Bank of Japan. Later, in London, it was quoted
at 121.60 yen.
   Traders in Tokyo said the Japanese central bank began buying
dollars when the currency fell to around 121.60 yen this morning and
made occasional purchases in the afternoon.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Monday's
rates, included: 1.7285 West German marks, down from 1.7305; 1.4545
Swiss francs, down from 1.4575; 5.9075 French francs, down from
5.9305; 1.9475 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9550; 1,284.50 Italian
lire, down from 1,288.62; and 1.1975 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2117.
   Traders said the Canadian dollar's rise was due to Monday's
electoral victory by Prime Minister Brian Mulroney's governing
Conservative Party.
   The win means the free trade agreement with the United States
will go ahead, and that's good news for the Canadian currency,
dealers say.
   ``Everyone is happy,'' said a trader at a U.S. bank.
   The British pound cost $1.8260 in London, almost 1 cent more
expensive for buyers than late Monday's $1.8175.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $415.70 a troy ounce,
down from $416.75 bid late Monday. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $416.10.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $416.00, down from $416.50 bid late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 75 cents to close at a bid
$418.04.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.05 a troy
ounce, up marginally from Monday's $6.04.
</TEXT>
