<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-88 0740EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-CanadaTrade-Glance     11-22 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Canada Trade-Glance,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Highlights Of U.S. Free Trade Agreement</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Canada-Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are highlights of the Canada-U.S. free trade agreement:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE TRADING PARTNERS _ The two nations already are each other's
largest trading partner. The annual exchange of $150 billion makes
it the largest two-nation trading partnership in the world.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE AGREEMENT _ President Reagan and Prime Minister Brian
Mulroney signed the agreement Jan. 2. The U.S. Congress approved the
agreement but it still needs Canadian parliamentary approval. The
agreement would take effect Jan. 1, 1989, and eliminate any
remaining tariffs between the countries over a 10-year period,
dismantle many investment barriers, free up trade in energy and
services, and create Canadian-U.S. panels to settle disputes.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   SOCIAL PROGRAMS _ Opponents charge that Canadian social programs
such as medicare, unemployment insurance and pensions will be
affected by the need to compete on an equal footing. Supporters
maintain social programs are unaffected by the agreement and
protected by international tradelaw.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   CULTURE _ Critics say Canadian industries such as publishing,
broadcasting and cinema could be overwhelmed by American programs.
Supporters argue that cultural policies are exempt from the
agreement and remain protected.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EMPLOYMENT _ Opponents charge that Canada would pay too high a
price under the agreement for a relatively small number of
lower-paying jobs in the service sector that would be created by
increased trade. They say farmers and food processors and the
textile and appliance industries would be among the hardest hit by
U.S. competition. Supporters forecast as many as 250,000 new jobs in
Canada during the first 10 years of the agreement.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ENERGY AND NATURAL RESOURCES _ The United States would gain
non-discriminatory access to Canadian energy supplies. Opponents
argue this could lead to Canada losing control of its vast energy,
water and other natural resources and being reduced to a source of
raw materials for the U.S. market. Supporters maintain the agreement
means Canadian energy exports will no longer face the future threat
of U.S. trade sanctions that could limit sales and that Canada still
would control its resources in the event of shortages.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE FUTURE _ Opponents paint a grim picture of Canada losing
control of its economic future and say political sovereignty could
suffer as a result of the agreement. They say Canada already is too
dependent on the United States as a customer and should develop
markets in other countries instead. Supporters say access to the
larger U.S. market must be guaranteed to ensure future Canadian
prosperity. They argue that without the agreement Canada risks
becoming an isolated international backwater, the smallest
industrial nation without participation in a larger trading bloc.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881122-0219 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-88 0746EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Mexico-Salinas     11-22 0549</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-Salinas,0567</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mexican President Hopes For Quick Talks On Debt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Lead prospects uncertain.
^By RICHARD HERZFELDER</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexico hopes to begin cabinet-level meetings
on ways of relieving Mexico's foreign debt even before George Bush
takes office, sources close to President-elect Carlos Salinas de
Gortari's transition team say.
   Mexico's $102 billion debt is an urgent priority for Salinas, who
was to meet with the U.S. president-elect this afternoon in Houston.
   As Salinas sees it, Mexico must resume economic growth and debt
payments leave little money for development.
   Salinas believes discussions could begin soon after his six-year
term begins Dec. 1 because Bush has already said he will retain
current U.S. Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady in office, the
sources said Monday night.
   Bush does not take office until Jan. 20.
   Salinas has never met Bush and hopes their two-hour luncheon
meeting today will establish a personal bond and set a tone for
U.S.-Mexico relations for at least the next four years.
   ``Both Bush and Salinas are men with open minds who are willing
to listen to the interests and concerns of others. We have different
problems and common interests,'' said Juan Enriquez, a top official
of Mexico's governing Institutional Revolutionary Party.
   Salinas also wishes to begin discussions on commercial relations.
He fears protectionist sentiment in the United States would hurt
Mexico's effort to improve its economy via non-petroleum exports,
said the sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Salinas also is concerned about Mexican migration, a result of a
lack of jobs and development in his homeland. He believes the
``tremendous current'' should be discussed and recognized openly so
it can be both orderly and controlled, the sources said.
   Some Mexicans fear the United States may see drug trafficking as
the main bilateral problem. Outgoing President Miguel de la Madrid's
six meetings with President Reagan were marked by U.S. demands,
often irritating to Mexico, that it do more to fight drug
trafficking.
   At their final meeting in February, de la Madrid said bluntly
that the best way to fight the drugs was for citizens of the United
States to stop using them, but the U.S. believes Mexico could do
more.
   Salinas plans to fight drug trafficking more energetically and is
also concerned about the ``cash crop'' problem _ in some areas,
Mexican campesinos can increase their income 10 or 20 times by
growing marijuana.
   The two governments have managed to work out temporary or partial
solutions to many other problems, including water contamination
along the border.
   The Bush-Salinas meeting ``represents a first positive step in
identifying the issues that will occupy the agenda'' during their
presidencies, said a statement released Monday night by Salinas'
office.
   The meeting's agenda was to be flexible, the statement said, with
its main goal to establish a personal basis for ``a fruitful and
consistent relationship.''
   Mexican foreign policy is often at odds with that of the United
States, especially in Central America, and Mexicans feel U.S.
government officials do not understand their culture and politics
well enough.
   But Salinas aides privately speak of a Bush who ``likes Mexico
and knows the country and its culture and its problems.'' Bush has
lived in the border state of Texas for many years, and his son is
married to a Mexican.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
