<1ST_LINE>d f PM-Japan-Survey     11-22 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Survey,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poll: Love Affairs, Divorce, Changing Jobs Top Wishes Of Japanese
Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese male office workers dream most of having
love affairs with their female colleagues, getting divorced or
changing their jobs, says a recent survey by a local insurance
company.
   The poll of 500 men aged 20 to 60 by the Tokyo-based Fukoku
Mutual Life Insurance Co. also found that only 12.8 percent of
Japan's diligent workers say they are required by their employers to
focus solely on work matters while in the office.
   A full 58.4 percent said they are allowed to read newspapers and
50.8 percent said they can leave the office on personal business
during working hours.
   Asked what they dreamed of doing but knew they could not, 37
percent of the men surveyed in the Tokyo poll said they would like
to have love affairs with younger female colleagues in their office
and 34.2 percent said they dreamed of divorcing their wives.
   Changing jobs was another popular fantasy, cited by 36.2 percent
of those surveyed.
   Workers aged 20 to 39 favored love affairs, while those in their
40s dreamed most of changing jobs and those in their 50s preferred
divorce, the survey said.
   Although Japanese on average work over 200 hours a year more than
Americans, time counted as working time isn't always what it seems.
   Some 36.6 percent of the men surveyed said they could relax in
coffee shops during office hours, and 16 percent said they could go
shopping.
   The insurance company conducted the survey to gauge the impact of
workers' business life on their family life and free time, said
company spokeswoman Miki Tanaka.
</TEXT>
