<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Britain-Stocks     11-22 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Higher At Midday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were higher, near the day's best
levels, at midday Tuesday, helped by Wall Street's late rally on
Monday.
   But trading activity slowed following a spurt of volume at
midmorning, dealers said.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was up 7.3
points, or 0.4 percent, at 1,818.4 at about 12:45 p.m.
   The index opened 2.2 points up, its lowest level for the day, and
peaked shortly before midday at 7.9 points higher.
   Volume was light to moderate, as 278.9 million shares changed
hands by midday, with much of this volume concentrated in selected
stocks. It compared with volume of 173.4 million shares at the same
time Monday.
   Dealers were encouraged by Wall Street's performance, where the
Dow Jones industrial average ended Monday with a gain of 3.56 points
at 2,065.97, after being down about 17 points earlier in the day.
   Meanwhile, prices of Canadian shares traded in London surged
higher at midmorning Tuesday, propelled by the clear-cut win of the
Progressive Conservative Party in Monday's federal elections in
Canada.
   Canadians reelected Prime Minister Brian Mulroney, thereby
approving the controversial free trade agreement with the United
States.
   ``Now that the Conservatives have a majority, the free trade
agreement is academic,'' said Jeff Richmond, institutional equity
salesman at Wood Gundy in London.
   A week ago, Canadian stocks were ``inordinately knocked back on
fears the (free-trade) pact would be scrapped, giving way to
negative sentiment,'' he said.
   Peter Guldberg, a trader at Scotia McLeod Inc. in London, said
there is a sense of relief with the Conservative victory because
``it makes people more confident about the Canadian dollar and the
trade agreement.''
</TEXT>
