<1ST_LINE>d f PM-FieroPlant     11-22 0185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fiero Plant,0192</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Decision on Closed Fiero Plant Due Early Next Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A decision by General Motors Corp. on
whether it will assemble a new pair of rear-wheel drive cars at its
idled Fiero assembly plant is expected early next year, a union
official says.
   Dick Long, vice president of United Auto Workers union Local 653
said Monday the union is hoping GM will decide to build its newly
designed Chevrolet Camaro and Pontiac Firebird models at the plant.
   Long also said plants in Oklahoma City and Van Nuys, Calif., are
in the running to get the new cars. The California plant assembles
the current versions of the Camaro and Firebird.
   GM spokesman Darwin Allen declined to discuss the new cars other
than to say their design is totally new.
   ``It's not just a face-lift,'' he said.
   GM closed the Fiero plant in August after assembling the
two-seat, plastic-body car there since 1983. Fiero sales slumped
badly in 1987 and this year after getting off to a fast start when
the car was introduced. No other plant builds the Fiero.
</TEXT>
