<1ST_LINE>r f PM-GMPlants     11-22 0168</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-GM Plants,0174</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GM Shutting Georgia and Kansas Plants for 2 Weeks Each</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp.'s assembly plants in
Doraville, Ga., and Fairfax, Kan., will be closed for two weeks
each, affecting about 7,600 hourly workers, the automaker says.
   ``We've been faced with problems from certain suppliers that led
us to make a decision to get the situation back into control,'' said
GM spokeswoman Sharon Hines. She refused to identify the suppliers
or elaborate on the problems.
   Hines said Monday the Doraville, Ga., plant will be shut down
this week and next week, and the company's plant in Fairfax, Kan.,
will close the weeks of Nov. 28 and Dec. 5.
   The company makes Oldsmobile Cutlass Supreme and Pontiac Grand
Prix cars at the two plants. The closings will reduce production by
13,000 to 14,000 cars.
   ``They have either overestimated the strength of the market or
they overestimated their share of it,'' said auto analyst Ted
Sullivan of the WEFA Group in Bala Cynwyd, Pa.
</TEXT>
