<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-88 0951EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f PM-PorkRinds     11-22 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pork Rinds,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Will Pork Rinds Be The New `In' Snack in Washington?</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OWENSBORO, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The grocery stores in Owensboro are abuzz
with talk about pork rinds, the favorite snack of President-elect
George Bush.
   ``We did see a slight increase in that department during the
campaign,'' said Ted Belcher, spokesman for one local chain. ``And
I've heard people talking about them in the stores. It's kind of
like jelly beans.''
   Jelly beans, of course, are President Reagan's favorite snack.
   Owensboro grocers, however, say they have seen little change in
pork-rind sales this month.
   Months ago, in the days when Vice President Bush was trying to
establish a more macho image for his presidential campaign, his
staff let it be known that his favorite snack food is pork rinds.
   Pork what? many city dwellers asked.
   Pork rinds, as in fried pig skin. That's right. The fried hide of
a hog.
   Until Bush's campaign, pork rinds were virtually ignored by the
media. But the industry is expected to reach the $200 million sales
mark this year. The Snack Food Association in Alexandria, Va., a
Washington suburb, said final figures for 1988 won't be in until
June 1989.
   In 1987, Americans gobbled $195 million worth of the skins,
compared with $186 million in 1986 and $184 million in 1985.
   ``It's too soon to tell if the Bush publicity is translating into
increased sales,'' said a spokeswoman for the Snack Food
Association. But sales have been climbing steadily without the
publicity.
   John Rudolph, president of Rudolph Foods Co. in Lima, Ohio, said
his company, which specializes in pork rinds and cracklings and
controls 35 percent of the national market for those products, has
received a lot of publicity.
   ``But we're busy as the dickens already. We work 24 hours a day,
seven days a week,'' Rudolph said.
   And Rudolph said he can't tell if all the pork-rind publicity is
translating into sales.
   ``But it can't hurt,'' he said. ``Pork rinds have always been a
working man's product. It's unusual to have them associated with the
president.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
