<HEAD>Suburban Newspaper Publisher Resigns in Management Dispute</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Only version planned</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The publisher of two suburban Detroit daily
newspapers has resigned in an apparent dispute with the
Florida-based owner of the papers.
   Gene Chambers, publisher of The Macomb Daily in Mount Clemens and
The Daily Tribune in Royal Oak, said Monday he reached a mutual
agreement with Adams Communications Corp. to step down from his post.
   ``I don't know who pulled the trigger first,'' he said. ``We just
had differences on too many things. Right now, I'm looking for a new
challenge _ something I can get excited about.''
   Chambers, 48, has been publisher of the 53,000-circulation Macomb
Daily since April 1982. The newspaper was sold to Adams' publishing
division in December 1987.
   When Adams purchased the 39,500-circulation Daily Tribune last
summer, Chambers assumed the publishing duties of that newspaper as
well.
</TEXT>
