<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-88 1029EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet10am     11-22 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 10am,0334</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices were mixed today in trading marked
by some buying of blue chips.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 3.55 to 2,069.52 in
the first half hour of trading.
   But losers outnumbered gainers by about 5 to 3 in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 316 up, 559
down and 492 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 16.08 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Before the trading day began the Labor Department reported that
the consumer price index rose 0.4 percent in October. The figure
came in a bit above advance estimates on Wall Street.
   But analysts said traders were still showing interest in big-name
stocks, apparently believing those issues were due for a rebound
after the market's broad decline earlier this month.
   Brokers said there also might be some buying by people hoping for
quick trading profits.
   Considerable attention has been devoted to the market's
historical tendency to post at least a small gain over the two
sessions before and after Thanksgiving.
   Whether this is simply coincidence or not, Newton Zinder at
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. noted that stocks have had a net gain
over those two sessions in 33 of the past 36 years.
   Hospital Corp. of America fell 3[ to 43{. The company agreed to a
management buyout proposal after apparently failing to attract other
bidders.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks edged
up .04 to 150.14. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .84 at 288.01.
   On Monday the Dow Jones industrial average closed with a 3.56
gain at 2,065.97.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 5 to 3 on the
NYSE, with 552 up, 920 down and 482 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 120.43 million shares, against 119.32
million in the previous session.
</TEXT>
