<DOCNO> AP881122-0228 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-88 1030EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EEC-MeatBan     11-22 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-Meat Ban,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Rejects Compromise on Hormone Ban; EEC Goes To GATT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and the European
Economic Community moved closer to a tit-for-tat trade war Tuesday
over EEC plans to ban imports of meat treated with growth-boosting
hormones as of Jan. 1.
   At a meeting here, U.S. officials rejected EEC compromise
proposals to reduce the ban's effect while EEC foreign ministers
stuck by the ban for health reasons.
   The proposed ban affects $145 million of U.S. meat exports a year
to the EEC, according to U.S. figures.
   The United States has drafted a list of EEC imports of roughly
the same value which are to be taxed in retaliation for the ban.
U.S. officials also have threatened to halt imports of EEC meat said
to contain hormones, which they say indicates the EEC ban is being
violated in the 12-nation Community itself.
   The EEC is asking the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade to
rule the planned retaliatory measures illegal. The EEC foreign
ministers said in a statement that the retaliation Washington
considers would be ``a violation of the GATT rules'' on free trade.
   In talks last week with U.S. Trade Representative Clayton
Yeutter, the EEC offered to exempt from its ban meat used for pet
food coupled with a rise in imports of top-quality U.S. beef.
   Alfred Kingon, the U.S. envoy to the EEC, said the United States
accepted the offer on pet food but ``was not willing to move on
high-quality beef'' which would still have to be free of hormones.
   The foreign ministers asked the EEC Commission to continue to try
and reach a solution. But Willy De Clercq, the EEC's External
Relations Commissioner, told reporters, ``I am not very optimistic.''
   De Clercq opposes delaying implementation of the ban which, he
said, is not discriminatory as it applies to all meat imports.
   One source quoted him as telling the ministers, ``The United
States has blocked any progress though we tried to get a
compromise.''
   Britain, the Netherlands, West Germany and Denmark urged the EEC
Commission to ``do its utmost to prevent a trade war,'' said the
source.
   The two sides will meet twice before the Dec. 5 start of a
gathering of officials from the 96 GATT nations in Montreal next
month, officials said.
   A British proposal to delay the hormone ban for six months to
enable the new U.S. administration to deal with the issue was
rejected.
   The EEC first decided to ban hormones in meat at the beginning of
1988. The ban's implementation was delayed in the hope a compromise
solution could be found with the United States.
   The EEC adopted its blanket ban on hormones in meat for health
reasons. The United States bans the use of some, not all, hormones,
and says this poses no health hazard to consumers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
