<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Corn, Soybeans Open Higher; Wheat Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean and corn futures opened higher today on
the Chicago Board of Trade while wheat futures were mixed.
   The higher soybean and corn prices also prompted some selling by
speculators, which tended to limit the early gains, analysts said.
   The wheat market continued to struggle amid disappointment over
the lack of a new long-term grain sales agreement with the Soviet
Union to replace the one that expired on Sept. 30.
   ``The LTA (long-term agreement) is still an intangible _ we just
can't feel that situation yet and that's starting to be felt in the
market,'' said Pat O'Connell, grain market analyst with Refco Inc.,
a large, Chicago-based commodities brokerage house.
   In early trading, wheat was \ cent lower to \ cent higher with
the contract for delivery in December at $4.08 a bushel; corn was \
cent to 1 cent higher with December at $2.62 a bushel; oats were 2
cents to 3 cents higher with December at $2.09 a bushel; and
soybeans were 1} cents to 2 cents higher with January at $7.48 a
bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .13 cent to .40 cent higher with December at
72.72 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent to .40 cent higher
with January at 81.75 cents a pound; live hogs were .80 cent lower
to .23 cent higher with December at 40.05 cents a pound; and frozen
pork bellies were unchanged to .20 cent higher with February at
42.60 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly lower on Monday.
</TEXT>
