<1ST_LINE>u f PM-OPEC 2ndLd-Writethru   11-22 0573</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-OPEC, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0592</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>OPEC Ministers Try to End Dispute</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to update with Iranian oil minister
expressing optimism about possible accord, oil prices rising; Picks
up 5th graf pvs, The cartel ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's oil minister suggested today that a
breakthrough was possible in OPEC's effort to reach an oil
production agreement, and crude oil prices soared more than a $1 a
barrel on the news.
   ``I think we can reach an agreement,'' Gholamreza Aghazadeh said
between private talks with other OPEC ministers.
   Aghazadeh's comment was in stark contrast to Iran's earlier open
refusal to allow rival Iraq oil quota parity, which has been one of
the chief stumbling blocks to an accord among all cartel members.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the January contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, stood at
$13.99 a barrel shortly after 11 a.m. EST, up $1.01 from Monday's
close.
   Venezuelan, Indonesian, Nigerian and Algerian ministers were
meeting separately with representatives from the formerly warring
gulf states to try to reach agreement before Wednesday.
   Iran had previously threatened to increase its oil production if
there is no agreement. The Iranian oil minister told reporters
Monday the country is pumping well above the production quota set by
the 13-nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries.
   The cartel is trying at its winter meeting, which officially
began Monday, to work out a new accord to restrain a production glut
that has sent prices downward.
   Iraq is insisting it get the same quota as Iran, and refused to
join the quota system now in effect because of this demand. Iran
wants to retain its ranking as the No.2 OPEC producer after Saudi
Arabia.
   The Saudi oil giant, which produces a quarter of the cartel's
oil, says it will not join a new quota system unless all 13 nations
take part.
   ``Everybody has indicated a willingness to be integrated (into a
production pact), but to what extent they will cooperate now is
unclear,'' said a senior delegate, who demanded anonymity.
   A member of a key delegation said Aghazadeh has suggested
ministers rework a proposal recommending OPEC boost its official
output ceiling, which now excludes Iraq, from about 15 million
barrels a day to a minimum of 17.4 million barrels.
   The higher ceiling would make room for Iraq, allotting it the
same share of 2.4 million barrels a day now held by Iran. Iraq's
current cap is 1.5 million barrels a day.
   Aghazadeh, according to the senior delegate, suggested that
rather than giving the same quota to Iraq, the cartel divide the
additional production between Iran and Iraq. Both want more money to
help rebuild their war-damaged economies.
   That would give Iran a quota of about 2.9 million barrels and
Iraq presumably about 2 million.
   That scenario _ apparently rejected by other ministers _ shows
Aghazadeh's unwillingness to give in.
   He told reporters Monday that Iran could boost oil production to
more than 4 million barrels a day within a year.
   He said the country currently is pumping more than 3 million
barrels a day.
   Analysts, however, have estimated Iran's production at 2.3
million to 2.5 million barrels.
   They estimate Iraq is producing at least 2.6 million barrels a
day, an amount that could reach 3.7 million barrels in mid-1989 when
a new pipeline through Saudi Arabia to the Red Sea is completed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
