<DOCNO> AP881122-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-88 2211EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-Post-DryBeer Adv28   11-22 0687</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Post-Dry Beer, Adv 28,0711</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 28</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday Nov. 28 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Japanese Market Hit By Post-Dry Beer Innovations</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TOK1 of Nov. 21</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although Asahi Breweries says ``dry'' beer is still
the biggest thing since the hop, the competition believes Japan may
now be ready for the next step in specialty brews _ post-dry.
   Yoshiki Koga, a spokesman for Sapporo Breweries, battling Asahi
for second place in domestic beer sales, said his company is now
marketing ``post-dry'' beers _ aimed at even more discriminating
tastes.
   ``Dry beer has taken a certain share of the market, but I've
heard rumors that as a fad it has reached its limit,'' Koga said.
``And, to give beer drinkers a more diverse market, Sapporo has
introduced Rocks and The Winter's Tale.''
   Rocks, which went on sale in March, has 9 percent alcohol
content, double the usual, and is for those _ as the name suggests _
who want to drink their beer with ice cubes.
   The Winter's Tale, which takes its name from the title of one of
Shakespeare's late plays, went on sale in the Tokyo area in November
and is to be sold only during the winter.
   Koga admitted the new products were influenced by Asahi's success
with dry and said Sapporo was hoping to spark a similar hit.
   The nation's leading brewer, Kirin, on Nov. 16 introduced Half
and Half, a mixture of light and dark beers, in some urban areas.
   ``We didn't plan it as a rival for dry,'' said Keisuke Suzuki, a
Kirin spokesman. ``But the dry phenomenon does seem to be slowing
down and many people are awaiting something new.''
   Kirin, which sells half of all the beer in Japan, began marketing
its own dry brew earlier this year and now has 30 percent of that
market, Suzuki said.
   He said that in 1987, 1.4 billion gallons of beer were consumed
here, making Japan the world's fourth-largest market after the
United States, West Germany and England.
   ``Brewers hadn't tried to change the taste of beer much until we
came up with the idea of producing something with a crisper taste,''
Asahi spokesman Ryuji Amada said.
   The dry brew is higher in alcohol content and has less sugar than
regular beer _ a prescription that, according to Amada, was just
what consumers were after.
   ``There has never been anything like dry,'' gloated Amada, whose
company controls about half the growing market for dry beer.
   ``Since we first introduced dry beer in March last year, our
overall sales have gone from 10 to 20 percent of the total beer
market.''
   The Kirin, Sapporo and Suntory breweries followed Asahi with
their own versions of dry, but remain far behind Asahi.
   Amada said sales of ``dry'' now make up about one-third of all
beer sales in Japan, ``and we think that could go as high as 50
percent next year.''
   Dry has even begun penetrating the U.S. market, he said, and
along with Japanese imports in Hawaii, California and New York,
Anheuser-Busch is brewing Michelob Dry for nationwide distribution.
   Dry beer was so successful that ``dry'' burgers _ they are
spicier, not less moist _ assaulted the Japanese diet.
   But the dry fad ``seems to have peaked last summer,'' according
to a spokesman for First Kitchen, a nationwide fast-food chain that
put ``dry'' hamburgers on its menu in June with Mexican spices
setting them apart from other burgers.
   ``The dry hamburgers were popular, but we've decided to
discontinue sales by the end of November,'' he said, requesting
anonymity.
   Even so, Asahi is not about to give up on a good thing and scoffs
at the challengers' products.
   ``It won't be easy to beat dry,'' said Amada. ``The products
going on the market aren't really new, and it was specialty beers
that dry ate up to begin with.''
   He said, ``We don't think dry is the best possible beer, but we
do think it still has a long way to go in the market and aren't
contemplating a followup product just yet.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday Nov. 28</NOTE>
</DOC>
