<HEAD>Crop Futures Advance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed mostly higher
Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade with the wheat market showing
new vigor on speculation that the Agriculture Department was
preparing to offer wheat to China.
   The rumors that the USDA would target China for a large amount of
U.S. wheat at subsidized prices apparently were rooted in the buying
activity of several grain companies, notably Cargill Inc., analysts
said.
   ``That sometimes touches off rumor-mongering but it's hard to
say'' how accurate the rumors were, said Walter Spilka, a grain
market analyst with Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc. in Chicago.
   ``That rumor comes up on a two-week rotation,'' he said.
   Corn and soybean futures advanced modestly, mostly on
follow-through buying from Monday's late rally, Spilka said.
   Japan bought nearly 57,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat overnight
while Taiwan purchased 33,000 metric tons of U.S. soybeans.
   At the close, wheat was { cent to 6{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.14} a bushel; corn was 1}
cents to 2 cents higher with December at $2.62} a bushel; oats were
1} cents to 3 cents higher with December at $2.09 a bushel; and
soybeans were 2{ cents lower to 6 cents higher with January at
$7.51{ a bushel.
