<1ST_LINE>u f AM-TravelInformation Bjt   11-22 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Travel Information, Bjt,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Allegis Chief Invests In New Vacation Directory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard Ferris, whose dream of making Allegis
Corp. a complete travel company fizzled, announced a new venture
Tuesday _ a one-stop source book for vacations ranging from dude
ranches to beach resorts.
   The former Allegis chairman is a chief investor and partner in
``The North American Vacation Brochure Directory,'' which unites
some of the travel industry's major leaders, including the Travel
Industry Association of America and Family Vacation Services, a
major supplier of vacation brochures.
   ``Until now most people have found it necessary to spend a lot of
time and effort writing or phoning numerous offices to request
vacation brochures,'' said Marvin Williams, president of Family
Vacation Services in Columbus, Ohio.
   ``Our directory solves this hassle by giving the consumer an
opportunity to `browse' through the vacation facilities and services
listed, fill out one of the enclosed order cards for the desired
brochures, and then receive them in a single envelope mailed from
the FVS fulfillment center,'' Williams said.
   The directory, a $4.95 booklet to be sold at bookstores,
newsstands and supermarkets, will be available in February. In
addition to listing thousands of hotels, resorts, campgrounds,
historical sites and other vacation spots, it will include calendars
of seasonal events for all 50 states and the provinces of Canada.
   Coupons for discounts at various vacation spots listed also are
included in the directory, published by Meredith Corp., whose
publications include Better Homes and Gardens magazine.
   So far, 6,000 vendors have agreed to list their vacation
offerings.
   Merchants receive a free directory listing and are billed when a
consumer specifically requests their brochures. There is no charge
for the consumer for the brochures.
   Ferris said he became involved at the request of Paula Spence,
president of Hameroff, Milenthal, Spence, Inc., a Columbus-based
travel promotion agency and one of the partners in the new directory.
   ``After leaving Allegis, I received a lot of interesting mail,''
Ferris said. ``This was pretty interesting. I immediately recognized
that here was an idea that the industry had long needed and wanted.''
   Ferris declined to say how much he had invested in the project.
   ``We think it's a service to the consumer and a service to the
industry,'' said Ferris, 52, who resigned from Allegis in June 1987
amid turmoil within the company's various units, including United
Airlines.
   With Ferris gone and his plans to create a travel conglomerate
defeated, Allegis changed its name back to UAL Corp. and launched a
restructuring program to sell off its non-airline businesses: Hilton
International Co., Hertz Co. and Westin Hotel Co.
   Ferris said if the directory proves to be a hit, the partnership
plans to create a computerized service offering personalized
vacation planning for consumers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
