<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     11-22 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Precede LONDON BC</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar continued to fall Tuesday against all
major currencies in cautious trading despite reports of some
central-bank intervention.
   Gold prices rebounded. Republic National Bank quoted bullion at
$418 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, up $2.50 from late Monday.
   Currency dealers reported the Federal Reserve bought modest
amounts of dollars with Japanese yen throughout the trading session,
but they said the intervention had only limited impact on the
bearish market.
   ``There's a preponderance of (dollar) selling,'' said George
DeLuna, a vice president and trader at Irving Trust Co.
   Traders have become increasingly worried about the lingering
trade and budget deficits and the ultimate effect of both on the
economy.
   At issue is whether President-elect George Bush, who has vowed
not to raise taxes, and the Democrat-controlled Congress can agree
on necessary spending cuts.
   Bush told a gathering of Republican governors Tuesday in Point
Clear, Ala., that he considered the deficit a pressing problem and
promised to ``work constructively'' with Congress. He said he
planned to name budget negotiators to represent the executive branch
during his first day on the job.
   But DeLuna said, ``The market is looking for something more
specific,'' and without that, the dollar will remain weak.
   Dealers said they expected fairly quiet trading this week because
of a Japanese holiday on Wednesday and the Thanksgiving holiday in
the United States on Thursday.
   In Tokyo, traders said the Japanese central bank made occasional
dollar purchases Tuesday, but the dollar fell 0.74 yen to a closing
121.78 yen. The dollar was quoted at 121.75 yen in London, and fell
in New York to 121.315 yen from 122.025 yen late Monday.
   In London, the British pound jumped to a five-month high of
$1.8305 from $1.8175 late Monday. Later, in New York, sterling
fetched $1.83375, up from $1.8235.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Monday,
included: 1.71855 West German marks, down from 1.72815; 1.44575
Swiss francs, down from 1.45495; 1.2008 Canadian dollars, down from
1.20695; 5.8765 French francs, down from 5.9070; and 1,277.50
Italian lire, down from 1,284.575.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with Monday: 1.7230 West
German marks, down from 1.7305; 1.4545 Swiss francs, down from
1.4575; 5.9090 French francs, down from 5.9305; 1.9480 Dutch
guilders, down from 1.9550; 1.2002 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2117; and 1,285.00 Italian lire, down from 1,288.62.
   Gold bullion prices were boosted by the weaker dollar and higher
oil prices, dealers said.
   On the New York Commodity Exchange, gold for current delivery
rose to $417.70 a troy ounce from $415.80 late Monday.
   In London gold rose to a late bid of $419.65 a troy ounce, up
from $416.75 bid late Monday. Gold rose in Zurich to $418.90 an
ounce from $416.50.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 75 cents to a closing bid of
$418.04 an ounce.
   Silver prices gained ground. On the New York Comex, silver
bullion rose to $6.061 a troy ounce from $6.010 on Monday. It rose
in London to a late bid price of $6.11 an ounce, up from $6.04 bid
late Monday.
</TEXT>
