<1ST_LINE>u f AM-EconomicForecast 1stLd-Writethru   11-22 1007</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Economic Forecast, 1st Ld-Writethru,f0162,1034</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Administration Sees Robust Growth Next Year, But Economists Doubt
It</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 7-8 pvs bgng, `The administration ... with 2 grafs
to UPDATE with revised budget deficit estimate for 1990. Picks up
9th graf pvs, `Beryl Sprinkel ... Also moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration issued its final
economic forecast on Tuesday, optimistically predicting that the
economy will expand at a robust 3.5 percent annual rate next year.
   However, private economists said the projection was far too rosy
and would spell big headaches for President-elect George Bush in his
efforts to reduce the federal budget deficit.
   The administration also was optimistic on the outlook for
inflation, predicting it would ease next year. The forecast also
said interest rates, which have shot up recently because of
inflationary fears, would drop as well. Both of the assumptions are
disputed by private economists.
   The economic forecast provides the underpinning for the
administration's estimates on government spending and revenues and
the shortfall between the two _ the budget deficit.
   The administration often has been criticized for basing its
budget estimates on rosy scenarios, only to see the deficit swell
far higher when the optimistic growth outlook did not come about.
   This estimate will form the basis for the administration's final
budget to Congress in early January. The document will cover the
1990 fiscal year, which begins next Oct. 1.
   Joseph Wright, head of the Office and Managment and Budget, said
in an interview after the economic forecast was released that the
revised growth projections would add another $3 billion to the
budget deficit for 1992, pushing it up to $135 billion. That means
Reagan will have to come up with $35 billion in deficit reductions
to meet the Gramm-Rudman target of a $100 billion deficit in 1990.
   Officials said the higher deficit figure resulted primarily from
a slightly lower growth estimate for 1988 caused by the loss in farm
income due to the drought.
   Beryl Sprinkel, Reagan's chief economic adviser, told reporters
the administration will meet the Gramm-Rudman target and will
project a balanced budget in 1993 without resorting to increased
taxes.
   However, private economists were skeptical, contending that
Reagan's final budget will make Bush's deficit challenge even more
difficult because it is based on unrealistic economic assumptions.
   They said that when the economy's actual performance is reviewed
at mid-year, Bush may have to propose even deeper spending cuts to
make up for lost revenues or face the prospect of doing what Bush
has pledged repeatedly not to do: raise taxes. Failing both of
those, the Gramm-Rudman law could trigger automatic,
across-the-board spending cuts.
   ``To use the administration's estimate for budget policy is very
risky,'' said Lawrence Chimerine, head of the WEFA Group, a Bala
Cynwyd, Pa., economic consulting firm. ``We've already seen signs
that the economy is slowing.''
   Blue Chip Economic Indicators, which surveys 51 top economists
monthly, said its consensus forecast for economic growth next year
is 2.2 percent, a full 1.3 percentage points lower than the
administration's revised forecast.
   But Sprinkel insisted that private economists were being too
pessimistic and were failing to take into account the boost the
economy will receive next year, once the effects of last summer's
severe drought are no longer felt.
   ``I do not want to be accused of making the final forecast of the
Reagan presidency too rosy,'' Sprinkel said.
   Sprinkel said the drought had reduced GNP growth by 0.7
percentage point this year and would boost growth by 0.8 percentage
point next year.
   Sprinkel said without the drought, growth this year would have
been 3.3 percent, exactly on target with the administration's
revised estimate last August. The administration on Tuesday put 1988
growth at 2.6 percent, when measured from the fourth quarter of 1987.
   In August, the administration projected 1989 growth at 3.3
percent, which was revised to the 3.5 percent estimate in the newest
forecast, based on a better rebound in the farm sector than
previously believed.
   In other predictions, the administration said inflationary
pressures will ease substantially next year. It predicted consumer
prices will rise by just 3.7 percent, down from an annual rate of
4.6 percent in the first 10 months of this year.
   However, other economists expect inflation will worsen next year,
climbing above 5 percent because of a rebound in oil prices and
production constraints in this country.
   The administration also was optimistic on interest rates,
expecting three-month Treasury bills, which on Monday shot up to
their highest levels in more than three years, to begin coming down
in 1989, averaging 6.3 percent for the year.
   The interest forecast is used to estimate how much the government
will have to pay to finance the $2.6 trillion national debt, now the
third largest spending category behind Defense and the Department of
Health and Human Services.
   The administration forecast that unemployment next year would
average 5.2 percent, declining to 5.1 percent in 1990 and then 5
percent in 1991 through 1994. The civilian unemployment rate was 5.3
percent in October.
   The administration forecast sees no recession through 1994,
projecting growth above 3 percent for the next six years.
   Economists also disputed this outlook, calling it highly
unrealistic to expect that the current expansion, which has lasted a
peacetime record of six years, could last that long.
   But Sprinkel insisted that recoveries do not die of old age but
rather by bad economic policies pursued by the government.
   Sprinkel said the administration's economic expectations were
based on a belief that the country's trade deficit would continue to
make substantial improvements next year, triggering continued strong
business investment by companies expanding production facilities to
meet higher export demand.
   Sprinkel also denied that there was any conflict between the
administration's forecast for growth above 3 percent and the
economic outlook at the Federal Reserve that the economy, at this
advanced stage of the recovery, should be growing at a slower 2
percent to 2.5 percent rate in order to avoid triggering run-away
inflation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
