<DOCNO> AP881122-0252 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-88 1855EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-TW-Coniston     11-22 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-TW-Coniston,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delaware Court Dismisses Coniston Challenge of Anti-Takeover Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The investor group whose buyout offer was snubbed
last month by TW Services Inc. said Tuesday that a Delaware court
dismissed on procedural grounds the group's challenge of the state's
anti-takeover law.
   New York-based Coniston Partners said the U.S. District Court for
Delaware on Tuesday rejected its suit to have a portion of
Delaware's anti-takeover law declared unconstitutional.
   The court based its action on the fact that Coniston's partial
tender offer for TW Services is not affected by the Delaware law,
Coniston said.
   After its initial $28-a-share offer was rejected, Coniston
announced in late October that it would begin a $29-a-share tender
offer as the first step of a proposed $1.14 billion takeover of the
food services giant. The two-step buyout plan was aimed at
sidestepping restrictions of the anti-takeover law of Delaware,
where TW Services is incorporated.
   The statute prohibits a hostile acquirer who buys 15 percent of a
company's stock from completing a takeover for three years, unless
it immediately gets approval from 85 percent of the company's
outstanding shares, excluding its own.
   Coniston's first-step cash tender offer for 15.75 million shares,
amounting to about $456.75 million, would give the investors a
majority stake in TW Services. The group already owns around 19
percent of TW Services' 48.5 million common shares outstanding.
   In a statement announcing the Delaware court ruling, Coniston
said it remains ``fully committed to acquiring TW Services and
intends to continue to explore alternatives to meet that objective.''
   In addition to its 1,200 Denny's and its 400 Hardee's fast-food
franchise restaurants, TW Services also runs Canteen Corp., a food
services company, and a small nursing home chain.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
