<DOCNO> AP881122-0253 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-88 1923EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-PhoneService     11-22 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Phone Service,0508</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AT&T To Offer New Telephone Information Service</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Telephone & Telegraph Co. is proposing
to start a new nationwide service that will connect callers with
companies offering information on topics ranging from food
preparation to legal advice.
   Callers from anywhere in the country could dial 1-900 plus a
seven-digit number and pay a flat rate to reach any of these
services, and the charges would appear on their monthly phone bill,
AT&T said.
   The new service may appeal to some companies that now offer
toll-free 800 service. If some of these companies switched to the
new 900 service, consumers could have to pay for some services they
now get free.
   AT&T envisions the new service being used, for example, by
companies interested in selling financial, investment, legal or
medical advice. A food company might offer recipes, and a consumer
product manufacturer might offer household maintenance tips, the
telephone company said.
   ``The purpose is to get information when you need it at a flat
rate from anywhere in the country,'' said AT&T spokesman Ralph
Dobriner.
   Charges, which would be determined by the sponsor of the service,
would range from 75 cents to $2 for the first minute and from 50
cents to $1 for each additional minute.
   AT&T filed plans for its new MultiQuest service with the Federal
Communications Commission on Monday. The company said it wants to
start the service Jan. 5.
   Dobriner said that while some switching from 800 service to 900
service may occur, many companies will stick with the toll-free
service because it better suits its needs.
   Companies that might be inclined to switch are those that offer
information, as opposed to hotels and airlines, which use 800
numbers primarily for taking reservations, he said.
   ``This is a value-added information service,'' he said.
   Bruce Kushnick of National TeleVoice, a marketing research and
consulting firm that does work for telephone companies including
AT&T, predicts some switching will occur because many companies see
the cost of 800 service ``going through the roof.''
   However, Blair Pleasant, a telecommunications analyst with the
Yankee Group in Boston, doesn't foresee many companies switching
services, but rather that that companies will find different
applications for 900 services.
   However, she believes that 900 services are ``a novelty,'' and
that ``when people realize how much they're going to have to pay for
900 service ... they won't be as apt to use it.''
   MCI Communications Corp. and US Sprint Communications Co., AT&T's
two largest competitors, have said they plan to offer a similar
service.
   AT&T has another 1-900 service, but it provides only recorded
information and is limited in the number of businesses it can serve.
   Kushnick estimates that AT&T's current 900 business and the 900
and 700 business of other companies amounts to $450 million in
revenues. He projects that these pay services will become a $2.9
billion a year industry by 1992.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881122-0254 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-88 1939EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Delta-Investigation 2ndLd-Writethru a0751 11-22 0801</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Delta-Investigation, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0751,0825</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FAA Cites Continued Problems In Delta Cockpits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While there have been improvements, pilots at
Delta Air Lines continue to have problems with cockpit crew
coordination and at times skirt established procedures, the Federal
Aviation Administration said Tuesday.
   The FAA said that while Delta's management ``has taken strong and
positive action'' in response to a critical review of the airline's
operations 14 months ago, much of its program has yet to be fully
implemented.
   ``Both line operations and training were found to be improved,''
an FAA inspection team reported in a summary of findings from
follow-up checks conducted at the Atlanta-based airline in early
October.
   A copy of the report became available Tuesday.
   Delta spokesman Bill Berry said the company was ``in general
agreement with the report.''
   Delta has taken aggressive steps to deal with problems discovered
by the FAA in its audit more than a year ago, Berry said, although
the FAA investigators found some still-existing problems that will
be addressed by programs just starting up.
   ``We think they gave us a pretty good report, although they
recognized there are some things we're just starting to do,'' he
said.
   Delta's cockpit operations and its training program came under
intense FAA scrutiny in the summer of 1987 after a series of errors
by Delta pilots brought the airline close to having several serious
accidents including a near-collision over the Atlantic.
   In a report in September l987, the FAA chastised Delta for
``lapses of discipline'' and allowing a ``breakdown of
communications (and) ... coordination'' in its cockpits.
   More recently, federal investigators have focused on pilot
performance in connection with the crash last August of a Delta
Boeing 727 as it attempted to take off from the Dallas-Fort Worth
airport. Authorities are trying to determine whether the three-man
crew forgot to properly set the wing flaps, causing the crash.
   The FAA's latest report on Delta makes no mention of the Aug. 31
crash in which 14 of the 108 people aboard were killed.
   It said the review in early October was aimed at re-examining
Delta's operations and training programs and to determine what
corrective actions have been taken since the l987 audit.
   While there were improvements noted, the FAA said ``deficiencies
identified in the previous audit were observed ... (including)
ineffective crew coordination and failure to follow established
procedures'' during regularly scheduled flights.
   Delta has more than 6,500 pilots.
   The FAA said that Delta's check pilots should be tougher on line
pilots during proficiency tests. It said the pilots should be
exposed to a ``greater degree of ... challenge'' rather than held to
``minimum standards.''
   Delta's management, said the FAA, has improved its operations and
training manuals during the past year but ``fundamental changes to
checklists and procedures are still pending'' and are not yet
reflected in the cockpit.
   ``Some of the major actions taken by management have not yet
become fully operational or have not yet become effective,'' the FAA
said. It cited as an example, Delta's revised ``cockpit resource
management training program'' which has been under development for
some time but is not scheduled to be implemented until next January.
   It noted that Delta plans to introduce next month a series of
changes in the way pilots conduct checklists before departure and
prior to landing. The role of each pilot will become more clearly
defined with pilots using the ``challenge and response technique''
more widely to guard against oversights.
   The FAA said it plans to continue monitoring the airline's
progress on implementing the various programs already under way.
   ``The ultimate effectiveness of these actions will depend on the
company's commitment and the individual acceptance by middle
management and the pilot group,'' the FAA said.
   The FAA's special review of Delta's training and cockpit
procedures comes at a time of increased agency interest in how
pilots perform in the cockpit.
   That interest was sharpened after the August l987 crash in
Detroit of a Northwest Airlines jet in which the two pilots forgot
to set the wing flaps, preventing the aircraft from gaining proper
lift.
   At the time of the Detroit accident, the FAA's attention already
had been aimed at Delta because of a string of unusual errors by
Delta pilots during the spring and summer of l987.
   That year, a Delta Lockheed L-1011 strayed 60 miles off course
over the North Atlantic and almost collided with a Continental
Airlines jumbo jet after the Delta crew entered the wrong navigation
coordinates in a computer.
   A captain of another Delta plane mistakenly turned off both
engines causing the jet to come within 500 feet of ditching into the
Pacific before the engines were restarted. Other 1987 incidents
involved pilots landing at the wrong airport and on the wrong runway.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
