<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MediaGeneral     11-22 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Media General,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Media General Announces Sale Of Broadcast Services Unit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Media General Inc. said Tuesday it had agreed to
sell its broadcast services unit, a leading buyer of radio and
television time for advertisers, to the senior managers of the
operation.
   Terms of the sale, which is expected to be completed by January
1989, were not disclosed, but Media General said it planned to take
an after-tax charge of $35 million to $40 million on the sale in the
fourth quarter.
   Media General earned $11.4 million, or 40 cents a share, on
revenue of $183.7 million in the fourth quarter of 1987.
   Donald B. Miller, who has headed the broadcast services unit
since 1986, will be chairman and chief executive officer of the new
company.
   Media General, which has interest in newspapers, broadcasting and
cable telellsion, bought the broadcast services operation in 1982.
It has specialized in buying television and radio time for
advertisers and also provides media planning, research and analysis
for its clients.
   The new company will buy essentially all of Media General
Broadcast Services assets except its broadcast production operation
and a travel agency, and will assume the broadcast services unit's
liabilities to stations.
   The bradcast services unit is not expected to post a profit this
year on revenue of more than $75 million, but Miller said he expects
the new company will be profitable in 1989.
   ``The company will be run by hands-on, day-to-day managers with
reduced corporate overhead, and without the financial drain of other
ancillary operations,'' he said. ``We'll be leaner, more targeted
and better able to respond quickly to constantly changing market
conditions.''
   James A. Linen IV, executive vice president of Media General,
said the divestiture of Media General Broadcast Services ``will
provide both short-range and longer-term economic benefits through
reduction of various liabilities and associated termination costs.''
   Media General publishes daily and weekly newspapers in cities
including Richmond, Tampa, Fla., and Winston-Salem, N.C.; owns
network affiliated television stations in Florida and South Carolina
and has cable television interests in Virginia.
</TEXT>
