<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Interco     11-22 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Interco,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Interco Boosts Special Dividend Paid In Restructuring</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interco Inc.'s board of directors on Tuesday
declared the final special dividend it will pay under the
restructuring and recapitalization it undertook to thwart a $2.7
billion hostile takeover bid.
   The adjustments approved by the board brought the total value of
cash and securities under the restructuring dividend to
approximately $71 per share, according to Harvey Saligman, Interco's
chairman and chief executive.
   Cardinal Acquisition Corp., headed by brothers Steven M. and
Mitchell P. Rales of Washington, D.C., last week abandoned their
$74-a-share takeover attempt after Interco repeatedly resisted
attempts to negotiate a buyout.
   The group controls 8.7 percent of Interco's common shares, and
has indicated it may seek control of the furniture and apparel
company in the future.
   Interco stock closed down $1 at $64.75 a share in New York Stock
Exchange trading Tuesday.
   The dividend declared Tuesday was the third and final special
dividence of the restructuring. It consists partly of $5.60
per-share in principal amount in 14.5 percent pay-in-kind debentures
and $9 a share of $100-a-share stated value preferred stock.
   Total payments under the restructuring thus include $38.60 per
share in cash, declared in the first and second special dividends,
plus securities that bring the total declared value to $71 a share.
   Shareholders also are to receive warrants to acquire 22 percent
of Interco's common shares.
   Interco said a supplement to its previously distributed
information statement describing the restructuring and the special
dividends will be mailed soon to shareholders.
   As announced in September, a $2.8 billion Interco restructuring
and recapitalization plan valued by the company at $76 a share could
include the sale of most of the furniture and apparel maker's 20
companies, which include Ethan Allan and Broyhill furniture, and
Florsheim and Converse shoes.
   The Raleses' hostile tender offer, valued at $2.7 billion,
expired last Wednesday and was not extended.
</TEXT>
