<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-88 2226EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Xerox-Soviet     11-22 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Xerox-Soviet,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Xerox Announces Its First Joint Venture With Soviets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA STOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union's first public copy
centers will begin opening early next year under a joint venture
between Xerox Corp.'s European affiliate and a Soviet agency.
   ``The Soviets have purchased copy machines for use within
organizations, but there have never been copy shops as you see in
the West which provide access to ordinary businesses who don't have
specialized equipment or the general public,'' said Ralph Land,
general manager for Xerox affiliate Rank Xerox Ltd. in London.
   ``Our Soviet partners say we will be surprised with the pent-up
demand,'' he said Tuesday.
   Under the agreement, the Eastern Export Operations Division of
Rank Xerox Ltd. will cooperate with Vnesghtorgizdat, the
international division of the Soviet state publishing organization.
Together they will open, equip and train staff for the copy centers.
   The shops, to be called Reprocentres, will open first in Moscow.
They will will provide photocopying services for the foreign
business community, paid for in convertible currency, and for Soviet
businesses, institutions and individuals, payable in rubles.
   While photocopying machines are in some offices, only specified
Soviet workers are allowed to use them. None have been available to
the general public until now.
   Land said he did not know how many copy centers eventually would
be opened. He said only one shop would be opened initially, but ``we
believe it will be successful and hope to be able to open many
more.''
   Rank Xerox and Vnesghtorgizdat also will establish a specialized
copying service that, for the first time, will make artistic,
historic and archival Russian documents available for sale to
Western universities and institutions.
   ``There is historical material sitting in the Soviet archives
that is much required by scholars in the West and we will be able to
copy that material and sell it to the western universities and think
tanks,'' Land said.
   Paul Bushkovitch, associate professor of history and chairman of
the Soviet and East European Studies Council at Yale University,
called the deal a ``breakthrough in communications.''
   He said of the Soviets: ``I think they got tired of doing things
the old way. When you deal with a Soviet office, you get, at best, a
carbon copy. ...There's one copy of everything. This is no way to
run things any more.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881122-0259 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-88 2256EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Chevron-Takeovers     11-22 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Chevron-Takeovers,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chevron Adopts Stockholder Rights Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chevron Corp. announced Tuesday it had
adopted a shareholder rights plan designed to prevent hostile
takeovers.
   The company's board of directors said no hostile bids had been
made for Chevron, the nation's fourth-largest oil company, and
blamed the current era of mergers and acquisitions for prompting the
move.
   ``We have instituted the stockholder rights plan in recognition
of an extremely active merger and acquisition environment in which
hostile, non-negotiated takeover bids have become common,'' board
Chairman George M. Keller said in a statement.
   The past two months have seen several takeover fights of
unprecedented size, including the record $20 billion-plus tussle to
acquire RJR Nabisco Inc. and last month's $13.1 billion agreement by
Philip Morris Cos. Inc. to acquire Kraft Inc.
   Details of the Chevron plan are outlined in a letter to be mailed
to all stockholders after Dec. 15, the company said.
   As part of the plan, the board Tuesday also declared a rights
dividend payable on shares of Chevron's common stock. For each share
of Chevron common stock held at the close of business Dec. 15,
stockholders will receive one right.
   The rights consist of a contingent right to purchase, under
certain circumstances, one or more fractional shares of a newly
created series of perferred stock or other securities in some cases.
   The rights would become exercisable and trade independently from
Chevron's common stock 10 days after the acquisition of 20 percent
or more of the voting power of Chevron, the company said.
   The rights expire Nov. 22, 1998, unless redeemed earlier by the
company.
   Keller said many other public companies have adopted similar
plans to enable their boards of directors to protect stockholders
from offers they consider inadequate and coercive.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
