<1ST_LINE>r f BC-BlinderProbe     11-22 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Blinder Probe,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IRS Investigation at Blinder, Robinson Apparently Winds Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal agents apparently finished their search of
records at Blinder, Robinson & Co. on Tuesday, in an investigation
that officials said covered the same companies scrutinized in a 1987
securities probe.
   The search began Saturday morning when 24 federal agents armed
with a search warrant entered the firm's headquarters in suburban
Englewood and began going through records.
   Denver spokesmen for the Internal Revenue Service and U.S.
Attorney's office have refused comment on the purpose of the probe.
The order, from the U.S. Attorney's office in Las Vegas, Nev., is
sealed.
   Nevada sources said the investigation involved laundering of
money skimmed from businesses in Las Vegas.
   Blinder, Robinson had been the subject of earlier federal
investigations involving allegations of fraud, stock price markups
and misrepresentation.
   The Securities and Exchange Commission has two actions ongoing
against the firm, including one that seeks to bar the firm's
president, Meyer Blinder, permanently from the securities business
and suspend the company's new issues underwritings for two years.
   Blinder, Robinson also has been hit by investigations and
penalties by the National Association of Securities Dealers, the
industry's self-regulatory body.
   The search warrant issued in Denver named 53 investors and 16
publicly traded securities, company executives said. None of the
investors is a Blinder, Robinson employee or has an account with the
brokerage, said Senior Vice President Steven B. Theys.
   ``Of the 16 issues, Blinder, Robinson probably had some market
activity in eight or 10 of them, but none of those are underwitten
by Blinder, Robinson,'' Theys said.
   Theys said the information sought by the federal agents was
turned over to the SEC as part of an investigation last year.
   Theys said the federal agents worked in a reduced number at the
office on Tuesday, and all left about 4:30 p.m. He said the Blinder,
Robinson staff and operations were at full strength Tuesday, about
150 workers.
   A skeleton crew of about 60 worked at the office Monday, when
people going into the building had to show identification to federal
guards and those leaving were subject to searches of their
briefcases.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
