<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Murdoch-Disney     11-22 0509</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Murdoch-Disney,0529</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Murdoch, Disney in Joint Satellite TV Venture in U.K.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rupert Murdoch's News Corp. media empire is
adding The Disney Channel to the four Sky Television services that
it plans to bring to Britain and Ireland via satellite next year.
   The venture will be the first of several satellite-to-home
television services that are expected to compete in Britain over the
next few years.
   It gives Murdoch's Sky Television service the drawing power of a
well-known supplier of family-oriented programming, and gives Disney
a ready-made outlet in a new market as it expands globally,
including its planned 1992 opening of a European Disneyland near
Paris.
   Viewers with satellite dishes in Britain and Ireland will be able
to get three of the free Sky Television services, which are a sports
channel, a news channel and a general entertainment channel.
   Murdoch also planned to offer a pay movie channel, Sky Movies,
that viewers could get if they obtained a decoder and paid a monthly
fee.
   On Monday, Murdoch and Disney chairman Michael D. Eisner said
they had agreed to offer The Disney Channel, which carries
family-oriented programming and movies, as part of the package with
Sky Movies.
   Murdoch, chief executive officer of News Corp., and Eisner, who
is Disney's chief executive, refused to disclose how much they were
investing in the deal. They appeared at a New York news conference
that was broadcast via satellite to London.
   The Sky Movies programs are to be available in February, while
the Disney Channel is to begin broadcasting in May or June.
   Murdoch said he hoped 1 million satellite dishes would be in use
in Britain and Ireland within 18 months and said he expected the pay
service to become profitable within two to three years.
   The Disney Channel has about 4 million U.S. subscribers.
   Disney officials said the service for the Sky Movies audiences
would contain some programming from the U.S. service, plus other
material developed for the British and Irish markets.
   Eisner said Disney would benefit from News International's
knowledge of the British market and the steps it already took to
deliver programming.
   The five channels News International will be delivering to
Britain will be carried on the 16-channel Astra direct broadcast
satellite to be launched next month.
   Sky Movies will broadcast Disney's Touchstone films and News
Corp.'s Twentieth Century Fox films, among others, along with
special event programming.
   The Disney Channel will operate 18 hours a day with children's
programming in the day, family entertainment in the early evening
and mainstream programs in the evening.
   On another topic, Murdoch said News Corp. was considering ways to
raise the $1 billion to pay for its $3 billion acquisition of
Triangle Publications Inc., which publishes TV Guide.
   ``We don't have anything on the block at the moment, but we are
considering various things,'' he said.
   He said the company was looking at ``some portfolio investments
we have talked about in Australia and Britain'' but is ``not
planning to sell any major assets.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
