<DOCNO> AP881122-0268 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-88 0051EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-TriangleIndustries Bjt   11-22 0656</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Triangle Industries, Bjt,0685</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Triangle Buyout Would Make French Company World's Biggest Packaging
Maker</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state-owned French conglomerate Pechiney SA
will be the world's largest consumer packaging maker following its
$1.26 billion acquisition of Triangle Industries Inc.
   But at least one industry analyst speculates the Paris company
may have to sell off some of Triangle's assets to offset the huge
debt load it will inherit from the company.
   Triangle said Monday that it accepted an unsolicited offer from
Pechiney that will allow top management to buy back Triangle's
non-packaging operations for $225 million. The $56-a-share deal
still needs regulatory approval.
   Triangle stock soared $35.78{ a share to close at $46.25 in the
over-the-counter market Monday.
   Triangle Chairman Nelson Peltz and President Peter W. May control
63 percent of the company's stock, and have 89 percent of the total
voting power. Before the company was taken semi-private last summer,
Triangle stock had been trading as high as $45 a share, said Timothy
Burns, an analyst with Prescott, Ball & Turbin Inc. of Cleveland.
   For Peltz and May, the cash deal provides a capital windfall
while allowing them to concentrate on Triangle operations outside of
container and packaging manufacture, which include the production of
juke boxes and vending machines and wire and cable.
   The acquisition would greatly strengthen Pechiney's presence in
the consumer containers and packaging business, making it by far the
largest in the world, as it prepares for the unification of the
Western European market in 1992.
   Pechiney is a diversified industrial group with operations such
as metals production, packaging and aerospace equipment.
   In a statement, Pechiney Chairman Jean Gandois said the company
planned no major changes in management and strategic operations at
Triangle's American National Can.
   ``Together, we will have the depth of resources, leading-edge
technology, global distribution network and worldwide market
presence necessary to compete successfully in today's rapidly
changing and increasingly demanding marketplace,'' Gandois said.
   Under the definitive agreement, Pechiney would pay $56 cash for
each of Triangle's common shares and $101.02 cash a share for the
company's $2 preferred stock, which is convertible to 1.82 common
shares.
   Triangle's 15} percent preferred stock would be redeemed at
$10.62{ a share plus accrued dividends.
   Both companies valued the agreement at $1.26 billion, but the
price actually is higher when Triangle's debt is included. Pechiney
essentially agreed to assume Triangle's outstanding debt, which
includes $2.6 billion in long-term securities.
   Burns speculated that Pechiney may have to sell some of
Triangle's assets, such as its glass or plastics operations, to
reduce that debt.
   Triangle accummulated its huge debt load over the years through
several acquisitions that have turned the company into the world's
biggest consumer packaging and container concern.
   Triangle acquired National Can Corp. in 1985 and American Can
Co.'s packaging business a year later, all primarily financed
through high-yield, low-rated junk bonds underwritten by Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc.
   Triangle manufactures metal, glass and plastic containers and
packing products through its American National Can operations.
   The company had been looking for ways to expand, and about a year
ago even considered making an offer for Pechiney's packaging
operations.
   ``We first became acquainted with Pechiney management in 1987,
when we approached them about buying their packaging business, Cebal
Group,'' Peltz said in a statement. ``We did not pursue that
transaction. However, Pechiney approached us recently with their own
proposal for a business combination of Pechiney and Triangle.
   ``The current proposal will enable ANC (American National Can) to
fulfill that objective by providing it greater capacity to grow
internationally.''
   Triangle's other interests include Rowe International Inc., which
manufactures vending machines and juke boxes; Brandt Inc., a
manufacturer of automated coin sorters and counters; and Triangle
PWC, a producer of wire and cable.
   Triangle spokesman John W. Sullivan said that in addition to
those operations, Peltz and May would acquire the company's New York
headquarters and Florida offices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
